<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN-Quayle-BabyBoom     08-18 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN-Quayle-Baby Boom,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle's Chore: Turn Baby Boomers into GOP Grownups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush tapped Sen. Dan Quayle as his
running mate in hopes of turning baby boomers into GOP boosters,
but analysts say younger Americans may prove too diverse for the
overture to pay off.
   Although the roughly 75 million Americans born between 1946 and
1965 shared such formative experiences as Vietnam and Watergate,
there is no evidence that such generational links create a voting
bloc, pollsters note.
   ``They cross all income, occupational and ideological lines,''
pollster Peter Hart said Wednesday.
   Bush and his strategists portrayed the selection of Quayle, 41,
as a daring bid for the loyalties of the younger generation, noting
that he is the first baby boomer on a major-party ticket for
national office.
   Campaign chief James A. Baker III called it ``a bold stroke,''
and Bush said: ``Do I need help in this area? Sure. And have I
gotten it by the selection of a young, experienced United States
senator? I think so.''
   Pollsters say, however, that some of the values shared by
younger Americans just don't mesh with Quayle's beliefs.
   ``Quayle fits on the economic stuff pretty well'' as a proponent
of deregulation, entrepreneurship and low taxes, said public policy
researcher Edward H. Crane, president of the Cato Institute in
Washington.
   But Crane, whose nonpartisan group has been a leader in
analyzing the baby-boom generation, said Quayle's foreign policy
views are more hawkish and his social views more conservative than
those of many baby boomers.
   ``He doesn't have that combination of views that I would argue
is unique to baby boomers,'' Crane said. ``So he won't be able to
appeal to a large group of them.''
   Young Americans are the least reliable voters, and Republican
pollster Neil Newhouse said Quayle may be able to improve turnout
among the one-third of baby boomers who already identify with the
Republican Party. He said the next step, drawing new adherents, was
possible even if difficult.
   ``Will it encourage younger Democrats, younger independents, to
cross party lines for a candidate of their generation? Who knows?''
he said. ``But there's a shot at that happening.''
   There are some openings for Quayle. Hart, a Democratic pollster
who studied the baby-boom generation for Rolling Stone magazine,
said that younger adults could find it easier to relate to him ``at
least in terms of appearance and metaphor.''
   And Newhouse noted that baby boomers are less strongly committed
to either political party than are older Americans.
   ``It goes beyond whether you are liberal or moderate or
conservative to what kind of concerns you have,'' Newhouse said.
``If he can demonstrate shared concerns over the things the
baby-boom generation is concerned about'' _ such as day care and
education _ ``then he can have a tremendous impact.''
   Another Republican pollster, Linda DiVall, also said Quayle's
candidacy could have an impact, so long as it was not overstated,
simply through the message his selection sent to younger voters.
   ``I don't think anyone is saying that Dan Quayle single-handedly
is going to deliver the baby-boom generation,'' she said. ``But I
think it's the first time that either of the major parties has made
an absolute gesture of basically passing the torch a couple of
generations and saying, `This is the future leader of our party,
this is the way we're going to go.'''
</TEXT>
