<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Reagan     08-18 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Reagan,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Quickly Enlists Reagan In Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush
apparently is losing no time taking President Reagan up on his
offer to march as a ``foot soldier'' in the Bush campaign for the
presidency.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Wednesday that a
joint appearance with Bush has been penciled in as a ``possible
political event'' on the president's schedule while he is in Los
Angeles next week.
   Fitzwater said Reagan, vacationing at his ranch north of here,
planned to watch on television Wednesday night as Bush formally
became the GOP nominee for president.
   He said the Reagan-Bush appearance next week was planned for
Wednesday, a day when the president had not scheduled any public
appearances. He did not know whether the event would be a
fund-raiser, a rally, or something else.
   The event would be the third joint Reagan-Bush appearance in
less than two weeks.
   Last Friday, in their first political duet since the president
endorsed Bush at a Washington fund-raising dinner May 11, they
appeared before a group of Reagan political appointees whom Bush
described as ``the field commanders of the Reagan revolution.'' The
president predicted, ``We are going to hold the White House with
George Bush.''
   On Monday night, addressing the Republican National Convention
in New Orleans, Reagan reversed Bush's ``field commanders''
metaphor and promised that ``I'll leave my phone number and address
behind just in case you need a foot soldier.''
   Bush was watching the president's speech on television at the
vice president's residence in Washington.
   On Tuesday morning, the two got together at Belle Chasse Naval
Air Station near New Orleans as Bush arrived and Reagan departed
for three weeks of vacationing and political fund-raising in
California.
   ``Nancy and I want you to know that you have all our support all
the way,'' he told Bush. The vice president then took Reagan aside
and told him privately of his choice of Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana
as his running mate.
   Reagan telephoned Quayle from the ranch Tuesday night to
congratulate him, Fitzwater said.
   The presidential spokesman said he did not think the second-term
senator would be handicapped by his relative youth and inexperience.
   ``He's a young man, but he has accomplished a lot in his 41
years,'' Fitzwater said.
   He recalled that Quayle was one of those who recommended that
Reagan veto the Pentagon spending bill that Defense Secretary Frank
C. Carlucci and other advisers had urged him to sign. In vetoing
the measure, Reagan argued that it would cripple his ``Star Wars''
system of space-based missile defense, among other things.
   Fitzwater quoted Quayle as telling the president, ``We can paint
our opposition in gray, or we can paint them in bold colors.''
   ``The president chose to go with the bold colors, and I think
this is a bold selection,'' the spokesman said.
   The tentative Bush-Reagan appearance next week would be
sandwiched between previously announced fund-raisers for Sen. Pete
Wilson in Irvine on Tuesday and for the California Republican Party
in Thousand Oaks and Rep. Robert Lagomarsino in Santa Barbara on
Aug. 27. Lagomarsino is the president's congressman. Reagan votes
in Solvang, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
