<1ST_LINE>u a AM-LastTemptation     08-18 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Last Temptation,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Last Temptation' Opens In Eight More Theaters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Universal Pictures has added eight
theaters for showing the ``The Last Temptation of Christ,'' which
set box office records last weekend amid protests from Christian
groups.
   A spokesman for Universal said each theater will be in a
different city and they will bring to 17 the number of screens
showing the movie.
   The openings were expected by this weekend in Detroit; Austin,
Texas; Houston; Santa Ana, Calif.; San Diego; Phoenix, Ariz.;
Tucson, Ariz.; and Philadelphia.
   Last weekend, the movie played to sold-out crowds in seven U.S.
cities and two in Canada, earning $401,211, a $44,579 per-screen
average.
   Five of the theaters taking on ``The Last Temptation of Christ''
for this weekend are owned by American Multi-Cinema. Previously,
movie chains such as General Cinema Theaters, Edwards Cinemas and
Luxury Theaters all said they would not show the film.
   Last week, an estimated crowd of 25,000 protesters gathered
outside Universal Studios to protest the film, based on a novel of
the same name by Nikos Kazantzakis and directed by Martin Scorsese.
Demonstrators also marched and handed out leaflets to moviegoers at
theaters showing the film.
   The protesters consider the movie sacrilegious, particularly a
scene in which Jesus on the cross hallucinates abandonment of his
role as redemeer, makes love to Mary Magdalene and raises a family
with her.
   Scorsese on Wednesday bought a full-page advertisement in the
trade paper Daily Variety. The open letter expressed thanks to MCA
Chairman Lew Wasserman and other executives of MCA Inc., parent
company of Universal, and to Garth Drabinsky, chairman of Cineplex
Odeon, which co-distributed the film with Universal.
   ``Without your help, `The Last Temptation of Christ' could never
have been made, nor could it have been released,'' Scorsese wrote.
   In Texas, 50 members of the Richardson Unitarian Universalist
Church signed a petition asking Universal Pictures to show the
movie in the Dallas area.
   ``So far, everybody's been boycotting, picketing and trying to
ban it without having seen it,'' said Rev. Dick Nelson. ``We're
just saying, `Let's have it here so if people want to see it they
can go see it,'' Nelson said.
   The petition was signed by church members on Sunday.
</TEXT>
