<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0259EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Zia     08-18 0884</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Zia,0911</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zia Was Longest Serving Pakistani President</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq was a
dictator who blended firmness with political shrewdness in a
formula that kept him in power 11 years, longer than anyone else in
Pakistan's 41-year history.
   Zia imposed martial law and executed the man he overthrew, but
did not instill the fear of prison and midnight knocks on the door.
   He was a zealous Moslem who stamped Islamic law on his nation,
but did not enforce such cruel punishments as amputation for theft
and stoning to death for adultery.
   A Western diplomat said a few years ago: ``Zia is something of a
paradox. By and large he's had an unfavorable press in the West,
but he's not nearly as bad as people make out.''
   Zia, 64, died Wednesday when his military plane exploded after
taking off from Bahawalpur, 330 miles south of Islamabad.
   He was a strong ally of the United States, and his regime was
helped by international politics and luck. Soviet military
intervention in Afghanistan in 1979 led to more Western aid, and
good harvests produced more food in the early 1980s.
   Recently, however, he has had difficulty with the unprecedented
opposition generated by Benazir Bhutto, the daughter of the prime
minister he overthrew, and other political leaders.
   Zia called himself a ``reluctant ruler'' in an interview with
the Los Angeles Times earlier this month, but added: ``I am not a
person to just give up in disgust and walk away. I am determined to
stay here until I solve all of the many problems that continue to
face our country.''
   The man whose surname means ``Light of God'' was a career
military officer and had spent 30 years in the army before Prime
Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto made him a full general and army chief
of staff on March 1, 1977.
   Zia banned alcohol in officers' messes and tried to instill the
Islamic principles of Imam (faith), Taqwa (abstinence) and Jihad
(readiness for holy war).
   Some military colleagues called him ``Bhutto's butler'' because
of the deference he showed the prime minister, so they were
surprised when he seized power in a bloodless coup July 5, 1977.
   Other observers, who had described Zia as ``dumb like a fox,''
were not surprised.
   Once in charge, Zia arrested the Cabinet and proclaimed martial
law. He had Bhutto tried later that year for conspiracy to murder a
political opponent, who was not killed, three years earlier.
   Bhutto was hanged in 1979, and his daughter, Benazir, has became
Zia's main political opponent.
   At first Zia had deferred to Bhutto and expressed hope that the
former prime minister would compete in elections scheduled for
October 1977.
   After studying secret documents on Bhutto's years in power,
however, he called his predecessor an ``evil genius'' who had run
the country ``on more or less Gestapo lines, misusing funds,
blackmailing people, detaining them illegally and even, perhaps,
ordering people killed.'' The trial ensued in September and Zia
canceled the elections.
   Last month, after announcing that ``free, fair and impartial''
national elections would be held in November, he made election
rules that hobbled the opposition.
   Zia kept up his nation's military strength to guard the borders
with India, with which Pakistan has fought three wars since
partition and independence from Britain in 1947.
   He supported Moslem guerrillas fighting the Soviet-backed
communist government in neighboring Afghanistan. After the Soviet
troop withdrawal from Afghanistan began May 15, the Kremlin accused
him of continuing to funnel arms to the insurgents.
   Mass arrests and floggings occurred even after Zia lifted
martial law and his public image was stern, but acquaintances said
he was warm in private and aides report many instances of kindess.
   According to one story, ``He was on a trip through the interior
when he heard about a village boy who was sick. He directed the
local authorities to get the child examined at state expense or
flown to another country if the proper treatment was not available
in Pakistan.''
   Zia resisted a cult of personality and did not permit his
portrait to hang in government offices or public places, unlike
previous military leaders in Pakistan. He was married with five
children.
   The general was the first head of state to use the national
language Urdu at all state functions, instead of English, and
encouraged officials to wear national dress.
   He was born into a middle-class family Aug. 12, 1924, at
Jallunder in what now is the Indian state of Punjab, and became a
devout Moslem in his youth.
   In June of this year, he issued a presidential decree making
Islamic law supreme, thus bringing much of Pakistani life under the
supervision of Islamic scholars and priests.
   ``His great passion in life is Islam,'' a close aide said.
   One acquaintance of Zia said: ``During his prayers, he forgets
everything worldly. He forgets his status as a general and head of
state, and even as a father and a husband. I have seen him crying
like a baby at the Prophet's tomb at Medina.''
   Several Pakistani and Western analysts said Zia believed running
the country was destiny, not duty, and in 1983 he declared: ``It's
not important what people say about you now, but what history
remembers after you've gone.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
