<HEAD>President Bans Student Union, Campus Politics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONROVIA, Liberia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Samuel K. Doe has banned the
national student union and ordered an end to all campus politics
because of what he called ``disobedience to constituted authority.''
   The order Wednesday also authorized heads of all public and
private schools to dismiss students for any misconduct, agitation
or engaging in campus politics.
   Doe said he was concerned by ``the increase of vandalism and
destruction of properties on school campuses, as well as students'
disobedience to constituted authority.''
   Students at C.H. Dewey High School, 30 miles from the capital,
Monrovia, recently set the school on fire, causing damages
estimated at more than $10,000. Doe banned Dewey High School
students from enrolling in any other school until theirs is
reconstructed.
   The Liberian National Students Union was founded in 1959 to
unite university and high school students.
</TEXT>
