<DOCNO> AP880818-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0019EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TacomaDrugs     08-18 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tacoma Drugs,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Using Loitering Arrests To Crack Down on Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council has given police
permission to arrest convicted drug dealers and illegal users for
loitering in parts of the city known to be drug hangouts.
   The council approved the ordinance on Tuesday and declared that
the drug problem was an emergency, requiring that a 10-day comment
period for new ordinances be waived.
   ``We have a grave emergency, and we need these emergency
measures,'' said Councilman Tom Stenger just before the 6-0 council
vote.
   Under the ordinance, 40 police officers specially trained to
recognize tactics of drug sellers will start cruising the city
Thursday, said Mark Mann, a police department spokesman.
   The ordinance permits police to arrest people who:
   _Show physical characteristics of drug intoxication or use, such
as needle marks.
   _Possess drug paraphernalia.
   _Were ordered by a judge to stay away from particular areas of
the city.
   _Are physically identified by police as a member of a gang known
to deal drugs.
   _Transfer small objects or packages for currency in a furtive
fashion.
   _Run when police appear.
   _Attempt to conceal themselves or an object that police believe
is related to a drug deal or behave in any manner that police
believe looks like drug-deal behavior.
   Councilman Jack Warnick cautioned police about violating
people's civil rights, saying, ``we're giving the police
extraordinary powers and hope they will be extraordinarily careful
in their use of those powers.''
   Kathleen Taylor, executive director of the American Civil
Liberties Union of Washington, said from Seattle that based on
accounts she had read of the measure, ``I think there are some
serious civil liberties problems with the ordinance, and we're
going to look into them further.
   ``Specifically, there are problems with the loitering
sections,'' she said. ``They're going to arrest people for merely
being in a certain location. People who have already served time
(for drugs) aren't supposed to carry the burden with them. They
would be the target for special treatment.
   ``People may be arrested for hanging out in their own
neighborhood. The breadth of the ordinance is very likely to cause
people not at all engaged in illegal activity to get caught up in
some sort of police action.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
