<HEAD>Republicans Make Hay With Dukakis Endive Remark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans led by standard-bearer George
Bush are making clear that they are not going to let Democratic
presidential nominee Michael Dukakis forget his Belgian endive
remark.
   Bush and other party leaders appeared at a Wednesday breakfast
of Midwestern Republicans less than a day after Bush's selection of
Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle as his running mate.
   Bush, Kansas Sen. Bob Dole and Agriculture Secretary Richard
Lyng all hammered Dukakis for suggesting in Iowa that farmers could
bolster their operations by growing different crops _ like Belgian
endive.
   ``I don't think that Belgian endive is the answer to American
agriculture,'' Bush said. ``My wife likes Belgian endive, but I
hate them.''
   ``Poor Michael, he can't be blamed,'' Lyng said. ``He grew up in
the city and he doesn't know the difference between Belgian endive
and corn.
   ``I don't know how many truckloads of Belgian endive it would
take to surplus the market,'' Lyng said. ``It wouldn't take very
damn many.''
   ``I thought it was part of his foreign policy,'' said Dole.
</TEXT>
