<HEAD>Names in The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No, it's not the latest variation on ``The
People's Court,'' but a ``rent-a-judge'' program has actress
Valerie Harper delighted about her starring role in a real-life
courtroom this week.
   The trial of multimillion-dollar suits and countersuits filed
between Miss Harper and her former employers, Lorimar and NBC-TV,
opened Wednesday following a bitter dispute over the television
series ``Valerie.''
   Miss Harper was fired from ``Valerie'' last summer after a
heated dispute with Lorimar and the show's producers. They claimed
she threw tantrums and was difficult to work with. She claimed they
fired her without reason.
   Also at issue was a dispute over Miss Harper's request for an
increase in her $56,750-per-episode salary.
   Under an unusual ``rent-a-judge'' program that brought the
dispute to trial about four years faster than usual, all parties
agreed to share costs of about $15,000 a week to hire retired
Superior Court Judge William Hogoboom and a staff of court
personnel to handle the case.
   ``I'm very glad to finally have my day in court,'' Miss Harper
told reporters. ``And it's wonderful to have it settled in a very
timely fashion.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GRETNA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Debra Murphree, who claims she posed nude for
evangelist Jimmy Swaggart, was stunned to receive a six-month jail
term in an unrelated prostitution case because she has begun to
chang her ways, her lawyer says.
   ``Obviously she committed the crime,'' said defense attorney Tom
Weymann. ``But it's a shock, given the circumstances.''
   Since the Swaggart scandal, Weymann said, Miss Murphree has
returned to her hometown of Patoka, Ind., and has been living with
her parents and three children, ages 7, 8, and 10. She was making
arrangements to return to school to study interior design, her
lawyer said.
   Miss Murphree, 28, was sentenced Wednesday for a 1987 arrest at
a suburban New Orleans motel. She pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor
charge of prostitution May 20, three months after she identified
herself as the woman at the center of the Swaggart scandal.
   Swaggart never acknowledged any encounter with Miss Murphree,
but tearfully confessed from the pulpit that he had committed
unspecified sins.
   Miss Murphree sold her story about Swaggart to Penthouse
magazine, accompanied by a series of explicit photos showing the
poses and acts she said Swaggart asked her to do in the motel room.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No charges will be filed against
the wife of pop singer Lionel Richie for allegedly beating another
woman she found with her husband, prosecutors said.
   Brenda Richie, 35, and dancer Diane Alexander, 22, ``view this
as a very unfortunate and situational incident,'' Los Angeles
County Deputy District Attorney Eldon Fox said Wednesday.
   ``But for the noise and screaming from this incident, law
enforcement would not have been contacted, both complainant and
suspect agree,'' Fox said.
   Mrs. Richie was arrested June 29 after a noisy brawl with her
husband and Miss Alexander at Miss Alexander's apartment. Richie,
39, and Miss Alexander have known each other for four years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version of the following is moving on sports wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Los Angeles Lakers' center Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar says he'll be ready to jump to the entertainment
industry right after he takes his final sky hook.
   Abdul-Jabbar announced Wednesday that he has signed an agreement
with talent agent Arnold Rifkin of Triad Artists Inc. to represent
him in all entertainment fields.
   The 7-foot-2 center, the National Basketball Association's
all-time regular season scoring leader with 37,639 points, is under
contract to play one more season with the defending NBA champion
Lakers. It will be his 20th professional season.
   A couple of entertainment projects already are planned when his
time on the court ends, including a Home Box Office special that
will incorporate film of Abdul-Jabbar's career and of his final
season.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Daniel Inouye's thoughts lately have
centered on winning the vote for Senate majority leader, but he
says his gaze sometimes reflects memories of the day he became a
hero during World War II.
   Inouye, D-Hawaii, won honors that day as a soldier with the
Japanese-American 442nd Regimental Combat Team during an assault in
Italy's Po Valley. It was also the day he lost his right arm.
   That morning he couldn't find his good luck charm _ a silver
dollar won in a poker game that he said had already stopped a
bullet.
   ``I told my friend Terry, `Today's my day. I'm going to get it.'
... To this day he reminds me of that,'' he said recently.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Feisty designer Pauline Trigere is kicking off a
new advertising campaign with a ``Dear John'' letter that teases
powerful Fairchild Publications chief John B. Fairchild.
   ``After all these years, and so many terrific collections _ is
it really over between us?'' the 75-year-old Paris-born designer
asks. ``You don't call. You don't write. I still love you.''
   The ad, which will appear in The New York Times Magazine on
Sunday and later in several other national fashion magazines, is
Trigere's response to being left out of the influential trade paper
Women's Wear Daily, which critiques designer collections.
   ``For three years our name has not appeared in Women's Wear at
all,'' Miss Trigere said Wednesday. ``I don't know why. Whenever I
see Mr. Fairchild we always talk very friendly.''
   ``I think it is very courageous,'' said John Weitz, a fashion
designer who says his name also has received scant mention in the
magazine. ``How wise it is, I don't know.''
   Fairchild, who is rumored to bar WWD reporters from mentioning
certain people in fashion and social circles, declined comment on
the advertisement.
</TEXT>
