<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--GodandPolitics Bjt   08-18 0838</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--God and Politics, Bjt,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reporter's Notebook: When the Saints Go Marching In</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY SHULINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the atheists of America, it's been a long
week. Just listen:
   ``This is my 10th Republican National Convention and, God
willing, not my last,'' said Gerald Ford.
   ``With God's help, and the help of George Bush, we will redeem
the American dream,'' said Thomas Kean.
   ``As Americans,'' said Pat Robertson, ``we are not ashamed to
pledge allegiance to a flag that is a symbol of one nation under
God.''
   Despite being subjected to ``intense bigotry and hostility''
ever since he hit town, 35-year-old Bob Sherman is gamely going
about his duties for the monthly American Atheist Press, which
declares itself ``the leading watchdog for the separation of church
and state.''
   As the magazine's Chicago bureau chief, Sherman is on the alert
for any and all incidents of atheist-bashing. Just the other day,
he says, an Illinois delegate turned to him and said, ``We don't
need any atheists here. Why don't you get lost?'''
   Ongoing crusades by the atheists include stamping out
``religious graffiti on our currency'' and ``offensive, secular
religious editorializing in our pledge of allegiance.''
   At the convention, things aren't going well. ``They've mentioned
the `G' word frequently,'' he said sadly. ``They haven't said the
`A' word once.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Washington delegation, on the other hand, cheers lustily at
the mention of the ``G'' word.
   Hushed and attentive during invocations and benedictions, the
Washington delegates shout ``amen'' when each prayer is over. When
the Rev. Billy Graham gave the benediction, they raised their hands
heavenward.
   They say grace at restaurants and read their Bibles on breaks.
And they managed to persuade the management at their hotel to pull
the plug on the movie channel.
   They've been less successful on tawdry Bourbon Street, where
several have witnessed for Christ outside the strip joints.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Somebody asked me yesterday, was I disappointed I didn't get a
call. I said I got a call. I'm not disappointed.''
   At an early morning breakfast packed with supporters, Sen. Bob
Dole's quip got a laugh. But the crowd laughed even harder when
Dole, who didn't get the job, poked gentle fun at Sen. Dan Quayle,
who did.
   ``He called me,'' Dole said. ``He was shaving. First time.''
   For Dean Banker of Russell, Kan., Dole's hometown, the humor was
reassuring. Still, it wasn't until he'd ``looked him in the eye and
shook his hand'' that Banker knew his old friend was OK.
   ``We Kansans are notorious for not wearing our hearts on our
sleeves. I was concerned about him,'' Banker said. ``But having
seen him today, his spirit, his vivaciousness, I can tell you that
he is OK.''
   Banker owns a clothing store on Main Street in Russell, where
Dole was among his first customers. As a sign in the window
attests, ``Bob Dole Suited Up Here First.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dan Quayle drew the most attention, and the warmest applause, in
an appearance before the California delegation when he recouped
from his mangled delivery of one of his intended campaign lines.
   ``This election is about whether we're going to go forward to
tomorrow or past to the back,'' Quayle said. Pause. ``Past to the
back. That's a Hoosierism. You'll get used to them.''
   The crowd cheered.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   What if you gave a cholesterol screening and nobody came?
   At a booth in the shopping arcade adjacent to the Superdome, the
Health Screening Lab of Covington, La., has slashed the price of
its Body Composition Analysis. Still, business is way off.
   For $10 instead of the usual $20, conventioneers can learn their
percentage of body fat, lean body mass and basal metabolism rate.
Carolyn Meadows, a registered nurse, will provide a weight loss
recommendation, daily diet plan, exercise prescription and
individual calorie burn chart.
   Nevertheless, her only customer at the moment is a tourist from
Nigeria, whose cholesterol weighs in at a respectable 191. There
isn't a delegate in sight.
   Given the typical delegate's diet of fried seafood and eggs
Benedict, ``I guess I can understand it,'' Meadows said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The centerpiece was an ice swan backlit by pink bulbs and
flanked by pink shrimp and pink crabmeat. The lilies were pink. The
tablecloths were pink. The guest of honor, Elizabeth Dole, wore
green.
   The invitation-only luncheon was sponsored by Avon, whose
scarves, earrings, perfumes and lipsticks decorated the room, and
whose soaps, talcs and perfumes guests carried home in little gift
bags.
   Dole has been on-duty _ and on-camera _ ever since she arrived.
But the temporary chairman of the Republican National Convention
showed no signs of flagging as she worked her way past the bottles
of ``Breathless'' and ``Accolade,'' posing for endless pictures and
shaking countless hands.
   ``I try to cut the partying off at a reasonable hour, and I try
to get a good night's sleep,'' she said.
   Does she use Avon products?
   She smiled diplomatically. ``I use a mixture of products, some
of which are Avon,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
