<DOCNO> AP880818-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0343EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--MoneyMuscle     08-18 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Money Muscle,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Strikes Back at Democratic Fund-raising Challenge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican fund-raisers, rising to their
stiffest Democratic challenge in decades, are working this
convention week on their fall strategy and celebrating their
success so far.
   Their challenge comes from Robert Farmer, the vaunted Democratic
money man who has pledged to raise $50 million for Democratic
nominee Michael Dukakis' effort in the fall presidential campaign.
   That sum, though unprecedented for a Democrat, has instilled
newfound fervor in Republican campaign donors.
   ``We're concerned about it,'' said Fred Bush, chief fund-raiser
of Vice President George Bush's campaign. ``There seems to be a lot
of interest in fund raising on the Democratic side. I've never seen
that before.''
   Bush, no relation to George Bush, is responding by marshaling
his own forces _ more than 600 contributors of $10,000-plus who are
in town for the Republican convention. In addition to a full slate
of parties, the top 200 fund-raisers held a 1{-hour meeting to plan
their efforts in each state.
   ``Our guys understand. They know what's going on out there,''
Fred Bush said in an interview. ``A lot of them have come to us and
said, `I don't want the Democrats to beat us on fund raising. What
can I do?'''
   One thing they could do was attend a $1,000-per-plate lunch at
the city Convention Center to benefit the Republican National
Committee. The goal: a whopping $4 million, compared with $2.5
million at the Dallas gala in 1984.
   ``It's our one big gala every year,'' said RNC spokeswoman
Katherine Murray. ``It's an opportunity for us to honor the new
nominee and vice presidential nominee. It's a celebration of our
all being here together.''
   It's also a chance for corporations to get in good with the GOP
by reserving tables at $100,000 each. And it's a way for the
Republicans to stroke their wealthy supporters with a personal
appearance by the nominee.
   So far the Republicans have done well at raising money. For
starters they have raised the legal limit of $8.3 million in
privately donated money the campaign can spend directly. That
supplements $46 million from the federal government for direct
spending.
   They also have come up with about $7 million, of a $25 million
goal, for state party accounts to be spent in coordination with the
presidential campaign, and several million dollars more for general
party-building. A separate item is the RNC's operating budget,
beneficiary of Thursday's gala.
   If the Democrats meet their goal, ``they're going to do better
than they've ever done,'' said Fred Bush. ``And we Republicans are
going to try to match them, or even beat them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880818-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0732EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     08-18 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLARKSVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Folks around Fairgrounds Park who
thought they saw a lawn mower flying overhead weren't hallucinating.
   Not only did Clarksville inventor Freddie Roberts fly the remote
control lawn mower for several minutes in the park, he even made it
fly loops, turns and upside-down.
   ``I made it for fun and to silence a few critics who think I'm
crazy, including my wife,'' Roberts, 44, said Monday.
   ``Who says a lawn mower can't fly? This one can fly but it can't
cut grass ... unless we have a crash landing.''
   The flying mower, made of balsa wood and Styrofoam, weighs less
than 5 pounds and is equipped with a model airplane engine. It is
guided by a model-airplane radio remote control.
   Roberts, a model airplane enthusiast for 30 years, also flies
gyrocopters, ultra-lights and is getting his pilot's license.
   ``I plan to build a (remote control) flying Santa Claus and
sleigh with reindeer for Christmas,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DURANGO, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A head start and a filibuster couldn't
stop City Council's meeting this week from becoming Durango's
fastest council meeting ever _ 11 minutes.
   The previous record of 12 minutes was set in 1984, when Bill
Casey was mayor.
   Casey, still a member of the council, tried a good-natured
filibuster Tuesday to protect his place in the record book, but
other council members cut him off by voting to call the question on
the one item on the agenda.
   Mayor Greg Bell banged the gavel to end the meeting at 7:40 p.m.
The meeting started at 7:29 p.m., a minute early.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OSHKOSH, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Alfred Wilhelm traveled from Germany
to Oshkosh in search of his roots, he never expected to hit paydirt
in a cemetery by meeting one of his living relatives there.
   The 38-year-old Bavarian was diligently copying birth and death
dates from headstones in the Riverside Cemetery last year when
Wilhelm Mauritz walked by.
   Mauritz, 84, was born in a farmhouse near the German-Austrian
border in 1904. His father, Joseph, wrote to three uncles living in
Oshkosh and asked them to sponsor their voyage to America. They
complied, and the Mauritz family came to America in 1905 on the
steamship Pennsylvania.
   But Mauritz's father did not forget his German relatives,
keeping in touch with them through letters and photographs. The
letters and photographs came back to his son via Wilhelm.
   The two first met last year when Mauritz struck up a
conversation with Wilhelm at the cemetery. Wilhelm explained he was
from Munich, researching his family history and then brought out a
photograph _ a copy of the same picture Mauritz had at home.
   The woman in the photograph was Katharina Drachsler, Wilhelm's
great-great-grandmother. She was also a great-aunt to Mauritz'
first wife, Rosa.
   ``That took me by surprise when he took that picture out and
says, `Where is this lady buried?''' Mauritz recalled.
   Wilhelm, who is on a second visit here, said he started tracing
his family history 10 years ago. ``My grandpa also searched for
family and I followed him,'' he said.
</TEXT>
