<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0345EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Quayle-Degree     08-18 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Quayle-Degree,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>It Took Two Ballots to Award an Honorary Degree to Quayle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle won an honorary degree from
his alma mater, DePauw University, in 1982 _ but it took more
ballots than will be required tonight to give him the Republican
vice presidential nomination.
   Faculty members at the Greencastle, Ind., liberal arts college
first voted not to award Quayle the degree, but relented after the
university president said he had already invited Quayle to be the
school's commencement speaker.
   Professors were troubled that Quayle's youth, brief record in
Congress and mediocre academic record made him a bad candidate for
the honorary doctor of laws, DePauw Professor O. Ralph Raymond said
Wednesday night.
   ``It wasn't that his career was undistinguished, it was just
that it was such a short career,'' said Raymond, a specialist on
Soviet affairs who opposed the degree award.
   ``I hope honorary degrees mean something ... and I think
prematurity tends to trivialize them,'' he said. ``I was simply
trying to protect two institutions, the university and the honorary
degree.''
   Raymond said some faculty members thought Quayle, at 35, needed
a longer record of accomplishment.
   He added that ``certainly there were some people quite bothered
by the fact that we were honoring a person whose intellectual
achievements were unimpressive,'' said Raymond, who never taught
Quayle. ``We like to see students achieve a little bit more than he
did.''
   The arguments of Raymond and other opponents of the degree
initially carried the day when the faculty voted 32-24 against
giving the award.
   But then DePauw President Richard F. Rosser said he had already
extended Quayle an invitation to speak at commencement and pick up
the degree.
   About 16 faculty members, wanting to avoid embarrassing Rosser,
later switched their votes, clearing the way for the award that
Quayle listed on his official campaign biography in 1986.
   Quayle is a 1969 graduate of DePauw and an attorney trained at
the Indiana University law school.
   Another dispute followed the degree spat when two reporters at
student radio station WGRE broke the story.
   They were fired for reporting on what Rosser claimed was an
off-the-record meeting. A news supervisor at the station quit to
protest.
   Quayle, who once worked as a reporter at his father's newspaper,
wrote a letter to the university to urge the reporters'
reinstatement.
   He said the firings ``could have a chilling effect on freedom of
the press.''
   The students didn't get their jobs back, Raymond said.
   Rosser is now president of the American Association of
Independent Colleges in Washington, D.C. He could not be reached
for comment Wednesday night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
