<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0352EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--MediaVisitors     08-18 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Media Visitors,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reporters From Near, Afar Seek Local Angle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joaquin Rabago feels an affinity for this
Mediterranean-style city with its easygoing atmosphere and
cosmopolitan foods, but he may be one of few visiting journalists
who's seen much of New Orleans.
   Rabago, the Washington bureau chief of EFE, an international
news wire serving Spain and Latin America, says the French Quarter
makes him nostalgic for Spain.
   ``The atmosphere, the smells. The food is the best I've had in
the states by far,'' he said. ``There's some indolence about it,
savoir vivre. Things you don't find in other cities in the United
States.''
   Joel Southern, meanwhile, has gotten acquainted mainly with the
inside of the press room at the Louisiana Superdome, site of the
Republican National Convention.
   Southern, here with the Berns Bureau, a Washington-based radio
service, said of the work area: ``I probably know this room better
than anyone else. One day was about 32 hours long. Yesterday was 25
or 26.''
   Both Rabago and Southern are among the 12,000 journalists in
town for the convention, many of whom don't have their own
headquarters and work out of a common press room equipped with
telephones and typewriters.
   While he's glad to be in New Orleans, Rabago says he can't
understand why the Republicans chose this city for their convention.
   Cabbies are telling him tales of former jobs in the oil drilling
business, he said, underscoring the gap between the upbeat
Republican economic theme and the downbeat Louisiana economy.
   And then there is the French Quarter.
   ``All that eroticism and voluptuousness doesn't seem to fit into
their message, particularly the conservative sector,'' he said.
   Though the city may remind Rabago of Spain, it doesn't remind
John Ralston of home.
   ``This place is much more decadent than Las Vegas,'' said the
reporter for the Las Vegas Review-Journal. ``There's no place in
Las Vegas where you can look from the street and see topless and
bottomless dancing, and women dancing in the streets virtually
taking their clothes off.''
   The media visitors to New Orleans range from correspondents for
Japanese newspaper groups to Chris Holly, a reporter for the Herald
of Rock Hill, S.C., circulation 30,000.
   ``We have a pretty hot Republican team here. They're going
places and we couldn't afford to ignore them,'' said Holly. Lee
Atwater, George Bush's campaign manager, is from South Carolina,
and Gov. Carroll Campbell was on Bush's short list of vice
presidential possibilities.
   Kawauchi Takas, Washington correspondent for the Mainichi
newspaper group in Japan, said his predecessor had given him some
tips on convention coverage: ``If you go to a Republican
convention, the first thing you notice will be the smell of the
perfume. If you go to a Democratic convention, the first thing you
notice will be the smell of sweat.'' He laughed. ``I think my
predecessor's advice was not quite correct.''
   Unlike reporters from bigtime news organizations, many of those
in the common press room are searching for local stories _ with
mixed success.
   Reporters from Southern's bureau had just completed sending a
story to Guam but weren't having much luck for a client in
Edmonton, Alberta.
   ``We tried to find the Canadian observers down here, but we
couldn't,'' Southern said. ``I tried a few free trade questions on
some Michigan delegates, but they weren't in a position to say
anything intelligent,'' said Matt Kaye.
   Yoichiro Miwa, chief of The Nishi-Nippon Shimbun (West Japan)
Daily's Washington bureau, said the 14-hour time difference means
``we must work everyday until very late at night, sometimes very
early in the morning. It's very difficult for us to find sleeping
time. We are workaholics.''
   Still, he added: ``I would like to go to the French Quarter. It
is very popular in Japan.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
