<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Bush 4thLd-Writethru a0442 08-18 0859</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Bush, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0442,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Surrounded by Family as Convention Delivers Nomination</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts new 9th graf on acceptance speech, ``Bush told xxx''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, surrounded by his grandchildren
and other relatives, watched from his hotel room Wednesday night as
his oldest son announced the roll call vote that delivered the
Republican presidential nod he has awaited so long.
   The vice president grinned and applauded as son George W. Bush,
a delegate from Texas, announced the 111 votes that put the state's
``favorite son and the world's best father'' over the 1,139
delegates needed for nomination.
   ``It is a special moment,'' Bush said. ``The conclusion was
foregone, but it's special.''
   In what looked like a Bush family production, scenes of the vice
president in his hotel suite, seated on a couch with his six of his
10 grandchildren swarming over him, were flashed on the large
screens of the Superdome as the balloting progressed.
   His wife, Barbara, sat for a while in the hall alongside Sen.
Dan Quayle, Bush's vice presidential choice, then later joined her
husband to watch the roll call.
   All of Bush's five adult children are delegates to the
convention. His Mexican-born daughter-in-law, Columba, delivered
the final seconding speech for his nomination from the floor in
Spanish.
   Son Neil announced the Colorado vote, daughter Dorothy Bush
LeBlond called out the Maine tally. Son Marvin announced the vote
from Virginia vote, speaking after the Texas count had been posted.
   As the Texas vote approached, Bush exclaimed, ``Here we come.
Here's the big moment.'' Then, turning to his wife, he pointed to
the scene on television and said: ``There's Junior,'' referring to
his son by his nickname.
   Bush told reporters that his acceptance speech was ``all ready''
and that he was ready to go.
   Earlier, Bush had vowed to show off three generations of his
family to America, claiming ``I get my strength from my family.''
   The vote was the culmination of a campaign that began officially
on Oct. 12, 1987, and seemed on the verge of ending after his
third-place finish in the Iowa caucuses. But Bush bounced back with
a victory in the New Hampshire primary and then swept 16 primaries
on Super Tuesday, a showing that left little doubt this convention
would belong to him.
   Bush's first bid for the presidency in 1980 and stunned many
observers with his victory over Ronald Reagan in Iowa. But Reagan
was not to be denied and Bush ended up as vice president.
   His down-the-line loyalty in that post earned him support from
many conservatives and he picked up additional political support as
a tireless campaigner and fund-raiser for Republican candidates, a
base that proved more difficult to shake than his GOP rivals
imagined.
   During a news conference hours before he was to be nominated,
Bush reacted indignantly to criticism of his introduction Tuesday
of his three Mexican-American grandchildren as ``the little brown
ones.''
   ``Those grandchildren are my pride and joy, and when I say
`pride' I mean it,'' he said, his voice rising angrily.
   ``For anyone to suggest that that comment of pride is anything
other than what it was, I find it personally offensive,'' he went
on. ``And P.S., I don't want to see these kids hurt.''
   The three youngsters _ Jeb Jr., Noelle, and George P. _ are the
children of Bush's son, Jeb, and his Mexican-born wife, Columba.
   His family was also the subject of Bush remarks moments later
when he visited the California delegation.
   ``I'm saying to myself, you're going to have share more to show
where you get your strength,'' he told the delegates. ``And I get
my strength from my family.''
   Bush said he intended to put them ``under the spotlight'' at the
convention. After he delivers his acceptance speech Thursday, Bush
will be joined at the podium by his four sons and daughter, their
spouses and 10 grandchildren.
   The vice president and his advisers were clearly impressed by
the family images projected at the Democratic convention last month
at which presidential nominee Michael Dukakis was joined on the
podium by his wife and three children, his mother and actress
cousin. In addition, there was the prominent role given the five
children of Jesse Jackson.
   Bush commented after that convention that Dukakis ``did a good
job at the convention with his speech and showing those wonderfully
warm pictures.''
   Bush aides said that after the convention, Bush and Quayle would
set out on a joint campaign trip through Indiana, Ohio and Illinois
_ the latter two states, key industrial battlegrounds in the fall
election.
   Bush will head off without Quayle on Monday to address a VFW
convention In Chicago and then fly to the West Coast for
appearances in Washington and California, where he will make a
joint appearance with Reagan.
   Looking ahead to the campaign, Bush said he and Quayle were
``going to tell the truth, and it's going to see like you've
engaged a couple of pit bulls. ... We will be telling the truth
about where we want to lead this country, spelling out my
priorities.''
</TEXT>
