<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0235EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bentsen-Reports Bjt   08-18 0838</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen-Reports, Bjt,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>VP Nominee Releases Reports Saying He's Healthy and Wealthy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At age 67, Democratic vice presidential
nominee Lloyd Bentsen follows a low-fat diet, takes a common
medicine to keep his cholesterol level down and ``is in excellent
health,'' his doctor says.
   ``I would say he's in better physical condition than men 20
years younger than he is,'' says Antonio M. Gotto Jr., a Houston
internist.
   Bentsen's wife, Beryl Ann, kidded about whether he had the body
of a 41-year-old, said Wednesday: ``You bet. No question about it.''
   Bentsen is the oldest of the four men on the Republican and
Democratic tickets this year. Democratic presidential nominee
Michael Dukakis is 54, Republican nominee George Bush is 64, and
his running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana, is the youngest at 41.
   Bentsen's doctor said the senior senator from Texas spends 18
minutes a day on a treadmill or plays a vigorous game of tennis
three to four times a week.
   Gotto said Bentsen also inherited good genes from his father,
who is 94 and in good health, and takes responsibility for his
health by avoiding tobacco and limiting his intake of alcohol,
eating right, and keeping his weight, 167 pounds, in check for his
6-foot-1 frame.
   ``He follows a diet low in saturated fat and cholesterol of the
type recommended by the American Heart Association,'' Gotto said in
a statement released Wednesday along with the senator's income tax
returns for the past five years.
   Those returns show Bentsen and his wife paid an average of
$264,453 annually in federal taxes on gross earnings averaging
$772,181 between 1983 and 1987.
   Gotto, Bentsen's personal physician since 1986, last examined
him in April and prescribed a low dose of lovastatin, a drug to
reduce his cholesterol level from 245 milligrams per decaliter. In
early 1986, Bentsen's cholesterol level reached 267.
   Government guidelines say cholesterol counts of 245 are
considered ``high risk.''
   Gotto said that after the senator used the drug for a month, his
cholesterol level fell to 200, a level the government guidelines
say is desirable.
   Bentsen's spokesman, Jack DeVore, said the senator continues to
take medicine for his cholesterol level, but that he requires only
the lowest dose available.
   Results of the April physical were ``completely normal with the
exception of a slight elevation of systolic blood pressure to 148
and two small lesions on the skin,'' Gotto said.
   A followup examination found Bentsen's blood pressure was normal
and the skin lesions had disappeared.
   In his financial disclosure report, Bentsen, a former insurance
executive, did not declare his net worth. On the campaign trail in
Lubbock, Texas, Bentsen said he did not know the precise figure.
   ``Frankly, I haven't made out a financial statement that has
given me my net worth in a number of years. (I) don't know what it
is,'' Bentsen said.
   However, he added later, ``I have paid a lot of taxes.''
   A source close to the senator who spoke on condition of
anonymity said he would not argue with other estimates that
Bentsen's net worth exceeds $10 million.
   Bentsen also revealed Wednesday that he had opened a blind trust
because of his race for vice president. Holdings in the trust
include interests in mineral leases and land, mutual funds and
common stock in more than a dozen well-known companies such as
Chevron, Boeing, Exxon, Johnson & Johnson and Unisys.
   Bentsen's income tax returns for the years 1983 through 1987
show that he and his wife earned a high of $1,020,607 in 1983 and a
low of $597,906 in 1984. He paid his highest taxes of $403,932 in
1983 and a low of $155,329 the following year.
   The couple had gross earnings of $604,587 and taxes of $253,098
in 1985; gross earnings of $718,237 and taxes of $298,495 in 1986;
and gross earnings of $919,566 and taxes of $211,411 in 1987.
   The three-term senator and his wife also distributed an average
of $21,381 in charitable contributions during each of those five
years, about 2.8 percent of their income. Their federal taxes over
the five years averaged 34.2 percent of adjusted gross income.
   Bentsen also issued new financial disclosure forms, which mixed
his blind trust income and assets with other holdings and earnings.
   The new figures considerably increased his reported worth from
the financial disclosure report he filed with the Senate last May,
which did not include details of the blind trust's holdings.
   The new figures show assets ranging from $5.1 million to more
than $7.9 million; income ranging from $894,000 to more than $2
million; and liabilities ranging from $260,000 to $615,000.
   In his May statement, which covered his assets, income and
liabilities as of the end of 1987, Bentsen reported income ranging
from $296,000 to $418,000, assets of $1.4 million to $2 million,
and liabilities of $100,000 to $250,000.
   The disclosure forms only require a range of figures for all
categories. In addition to his other earnings, Bentsen earns
$89,500 annually in Senate salary.
</TEXT>
