<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0735EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Pakistan Bjt   08-18 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Pakistan, Bjt,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Despite Drawbacks, Zia Was a Key US Ally</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq, who guided
Pakistan for 11 years, enjoyed close ties with the United States
despite liabilities that would have doomed that relationship had he
governed a less strategically important country.
   Zia's refusal to be intimidated by the presence of over 100,000
Soviet troops in neighboring Afghanistan overrode all other
considerations in Washington, enabling Pakistan to be among the
largest recipients of American assistance.
   Zia, who died Wednesday in a plane crash along with U.S.
Ambassador Arnold L. Raphel and an American brigadier general,
allowed U.S.-backed Afghan rebels to use Pakistan as a staging
ground for attacks on Afghanistan. He also permitted Pakistan to be
used as a safe haven for 3 million Afghan refugees.
   So dependent was the Reagan administration on Pakistan for
achieving its policy goals in Afghanistan that Washington
soft-pedaled other aspects of Zia's rule that many in Congress
found objectionable.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, in New Orleans on Wednesday
for the Republican national convention, credited Zia with inducing
the Soviet Union to begin withdrawing its forces from Afghanistan.
   The Reagan administration normally favors multiparty democracy
but essentially remained silent in the face of Zia's scornful
attitude toward his country's political parties.
   He decreed that the Nov. 16 national elections would be
conducted on a non-party basis, meaning that the largely illiterate
Pakistani population will not have the benefit of party symbols
when they cast their ballots.
   ``If you have the spirit of democracy, why insist on the form?''
Zia asked an interviewer recently. ``Why must there be parties?''
   There are also congressional concerns about Pakistan's role as
source of supply for U.S.-bound heroin.
   But the greatest concern to members of Congress was the
suspicion that Pakistan under Zia's rule was developing _ or
already has developed _ a nuclear weapons capability.
   U.S. law prohibits aiding countries that acquire uranium
enrichment technology and do not put it under the International
Atomic Energy Agency's safeguard system.
   Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, has criticized the Reagan
administration for aiding Pakistan even though that country has not
provided ``ironclad assurances'' that it is not building nuclear
weapons.
   Leonard Spector, an expert on the spread of nuclear weapons, has
said ``available evidence leaves little doubt'' that Pakistan is
indeed developing nuclear arms.
   President Reagan has certified repeatedly that Pakistan has not
developed such a capability and therefore is eligible for continued
U.S. assistance. The U.S. aid program totals $3.28 billion over six
years, a generous sum in an age of worldwide aid cutbacks.
   To Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., Zia's critics overlooked his
role as a ``bulwark against Soviet imperialism,'' a sentiment he
repeated Wednesday while attending the GOP conclave in New Orleans.
   After Zia's death, the State Department was quick to reaffirm
support for Pakistan.
   ``We have a long history of close and friendly cooperation with
Pakistan,'' department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said. ``At this
moment of extreme trial, I want to reiterate our commitment to
Pakistan and our full support for the acting president and his
government.''
   Former United Nations Ambassador Jeane Kirkpatrick wondered
whether Pakistan's strong stand on Afghanistan would continue under
Zia's successors and whether the country would be able to contain
Islamic fundamentalists.
   She called Zia ``a very strong person, very important to the
whole geopolitical strategic constellation of the region, very
important to the freedom fighters of Afghanistan.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   George Gedda covers the State Department for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
