<DOCNO> AP880818-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0413EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-EasternAirlines     08-18 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern Airlines,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Airlines Defends $30 Million Payment to Continental</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Eastern Airlines says paying
sister carrier Continental Airlines $30 million to hire and train
pilots in the event of a strike is the equivalent of a corporate
``insurance policy.''
   Eastern President Phil Bakes was questioned about the plan
during cross-examination Wednesday by lawyers challenging Eastern's
plan to curtail service to 14 cities and lay off 4,000 employees.
   Three unions are seeking to prove in the case that Texas Air
Corp., the parent company of Eatern and Continental, is trying to
break the power of organized labor at Eastern by transferring
assets of the financially troubled airline to its non-union
subsidiaries, such as Continental.
   Bakes said the $30 million payment to Continental will assure
the company has 400 pilots in case Eastern pilots honor a walkout
by the International Association of Machinists and Aerospace
Workers.
   The machinists' union, the Air Line Pilots Association and the
Transport Workers Union obtained an injunction temporarily blocking
Eastern's plans to reduce its service and close its Kansas City hub
by Sept. 1.
   U.S. District Judge Barrington D. Parker is conducting hearings
to determine whether to issue a preliminary injunction.
   The unions also are trying to undermine the company's argument
that the service cutbacks are needed because the airline is short
on cash.
   The unions contend that the planned layoffs cannot take place
unless Eastern negotiates with its employees under the Railway
Labor Act.
   Bakes testified that in addition to the $30 million payment for
pilot hiring and training, Eastern loaned Continental $40 million
in June at an interest rate of 17.5 percent. Asked by the judge to
explain the loan, Bakes said the company didn't want its money to
be idle.
   Eastern wants to concentrate its service along the East Coast
and to the Caribbean and Latin America. Bakes testified earlier
this week that the Kansas City hub has lost money virtually since
Eastern opened it in 1983.
   He testified that the operational changes would save the company
$100 million.
</TEXT>
