<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0248EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PakistanCrash-Wassom     08-18 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan Crash-Wassom,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wassom Lauded As Well-Respected Commander</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Army general killed in the plane
crash that took the lives of Pakistan's president and the U.S.
ambassador to the country was an oft-decorated senior officer
serving in his first diplomatic post.
   Brig. Gen. Herbert M. Wassom, 49, commander with the 101st
Airborne Division, became the chief U.S. defense representative to
Pakistan in July 1987.
   Pentagon officials said he had accompanied U.S. Ambassador
Arnold L. Raphel and Pakistani President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq
Wednesday on a trip to eastern Pakistan to view a demonstration of
the M-1 tank.
   The Pakistani C-130 transport plane carrying the men exploded
shortly after taking off Wednesday from the city of Bahawalpur,
killing all aboard, according to Pakistan's official radio. The
Pentagon later confirmed that Wassom had been aboard the plane.
   Wassom received numerous honors during his more than 26 years of
active duty, including the Defense Meritorious Service Medal, the
Legion of Merit with Oak Leaf Cluster and the Bronze Star.
   Wassom, who was promoted to general in September 1985, held a
bachelor's degree in industrial arts from Western Kentucky
University and a master's degree in international relations from
George Washington University.
   He also graduated from the U.S. Army Command and General Staff
College and the National War College.
   A native of Rockwood, Tenn., he was trained as an artillery and
missile officer and served in Vietnam. He rose through a variety of
command positions with the 101st Airborne Division in the 1970s
before becoming head of the 528th Army Artillery Group in the U.S.
Army Southern European Task Force in 1980.
   In 1981, Wassom became deputy director of the staff for the
Army's chief of staff in Washington, then in 1983 became the chief
of staff for the 101st at Fort Campbell, Ky. He later served as the
assistant division commander for the 101st before assuming the post
in Pakistan.
   ``He was a very capable guy who was extremely well liked,'' said
one Pentagon official, who asked not to be named.
   ``Everybody respected him,'' added an Army official. ``He was a
comer.''
</TEXT>
