<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WeaponsReactor     08-18 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weapons Reactor,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Carolina Reactor Shut Down After Power Surge</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Clif is cq in 8th graf.
^By BARTON REPPERT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Energy has moved to shut
down a nuclear reactor used in weapons production in the wake of a
power surge that occurred last week while operators were seeking to
restart the reactor.
   Ernest C. Baynard III, assistant secretary for environment,
safety and health, said Wednesday night that the incident involved
the P-Reactor, one of three reactors located at the Savannah River
Plant in South Carolina.
   ``They're bringing it down to zero power level,'' he said.
   The two other Savannah River weapons reactors also are shut down
_ one of them for a scheduled maintenance outage and the other due
to safety concerns.
   Baynard said the government is particularly concerned that
operators of the reactor continued building up power despite the 2
percent ``power spike'' _ an abrupt and unexpected increase in
temperature and pressure.
   ``In simple terms, it's not the machine that bothers me so much
as the reaction of the people running it,'' he said. ``So we've had
a lot of discussion with them (Savannah River Plant officials)
about what we need to do here.''
   In Aiken, S.C., a spokesman for the Du Pont Co., which operates
the complex for the Energy Department, said the reactor had been
shut down while an independent review panel investigates the Aug.
7-9 restart process.
   The spokesman, Clif Webb, said the review panel has ``questions
and concerns'' about the operators' decision to continue to build
power in the reactor although there were indications of problems in
maintaining a nuclear reaction.
   According to Webb, the reactor was shut down Aug. 9, then
restarted briefly after tests showed that the problem was a buildup
of helium in the reactor vessel.
   Du Pont then proposed this week that the reactor be shut down
early for routine testing that had been scheduled for September, so
that the reactor would be out of service while the review panel
studied the restart incident, Webb said.
   Jim Gaver, an Energy Department spokesman at the Savannah River
Plant, said Wednesday night that the concern of the oversight panel
``is not whether that restart process was safe, but a question
about the procedures and the contractor's checks and balances.''
   The concern is whether it would have been more prudent to
examine unusual reactor readings at a lower power level, Gaver said.
</TEXT>
