<1ST_LINE>r i PM-IncaFire     08-18 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Inca Fire,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Closes Inca Hiking Trail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire swept toward the Sacred Valley of the
Incas and forced the closing of a world famous Andes hiking trail,
and police arrested a campesino for allegedly starting the blaze, a
Civil Defense official said.
   About 550 military and civilian firefighters were sent Wednesday
to the isolated zone between Machu Picchu and Cuzco, in the
2-mile-high Andes about 330 miles southeast of Lima, Civil Defense
spokeswomen Rebeca Anaya said.
   Flames cut a swath up to a half-mile wide and 13 miles long
through grass and forest-covered mountainsides.
   The mountaintop Inca ruins of Machu Picchu, one of Latin
America's most famous tourist attractions, have not been threatened
by the fire, which started just four miles south of the site,
officials said.
   Anaya said winds pushed the flames away from Machu Picchu
southeast toward the Urubamba River valley, known as the Sacred
Valley of the Incas for the dozens of ruins there. But she said the
fire forced closure of the trail leading to Machu Picchu.
   She said police arrested an area campesino for starting the
blaze in an attempt to clear land for planting.
   There have been no reports of injuries to humans in the fire.
</TEXT>
