<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Protests     08-18 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Protests,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shouting Match At The Free-Speech Stage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A demonstration by a group of ``skinheads''
sparked a shouting match with a group of young Republicans who
briefly were aligned against them with some anarchists in town for
the GOP convention.
   Emotions ran so high during the confrontation Wednesday at
Lafayette Square that 50 police officers stood two-deep to protect
the skinheads while they held forth on a stage, promoting their
separatist beliefs.
   One person was arrested later as the skinheads were escorted
from the park by a phalanx of police.
   The stage and a sound system were set up for demonstrations
during the Republican National Convention, but _ as has been the
case all week _ neither GOP politics nor presidential nominee
George Bush was a topic.
   The afternoon's bitter exchanges were the most heated at the
stage in three days of demonstrations.
   Most of the protests have been uneventful with many of the
90-minute time slots for demonstrations going unclaimed.
   The skinheads, with shaved heads, military boots and camouflage
pants, railed Wednesday against minorities, blaming blacks, Jews
and Hispanics for the world's ills.
   The crowd shouted back, ``No fascists, no KKK!''
   One cluster in the crowd, carrying signs denouncing fascism and
Nazism, was joined in chants by the college-aged Republicans, some
of whom were wearing suits, with their green guest passes to the
convention still hanging around their necks.
   Then about 20 members of a third group calling themselves
anarchists showed up with anti-racist leaflets and joined in the
shouting.
   The anarchists have been at the stage during the week with their
own ``guerrilla theater,'' advocating a dismantling of government
in favor of community rule.
   The exchanges grew more and more heated as the skinheads on
stage harangued the audience with denunciations of minorities.
   The young Republicans jeered and called the skinheads communists.
   The people on stage responded that those out front were
ignorant, prompting cries of ``Nazi scum.''
   ``We stand behind our separatist beliefs,'' a speaker retorted.
``Segregation is the only way.''
   A small number of passersby laughed in disbelief.
   After the demonstration ended, about 25 of the police encircled
the half-dozen skinheads and escorted them safely to their cars two
blocks away.
   Earlier, the young Republicans had jeered gay activitists who
called for stepped-up efforts to fight AIDs.
</TEXT>
