<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Graves     08-18 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Graves,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Graves of Stalin's Victims Found in Byelorussia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A popular picnic spot on the outskirts of Minsk
was a killing field during the purges of Josef Stalin and contains
the graves of 500 people shot during the dictator's bloody reign,
according to Soviet news reports.
   Moscow News said Wednesday that a recent report in a
Byelorussian newspaper about the discovery of the graves in Kurpati
Forest, outside the Byleorussian capital of Minsk, had ``stirred
the whole republic.''
   ``From 1937 to 1941, every day they shot people who were brought
here by cars,'' according to Moscow News, a weekly at the forefront
of Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or
openness.
   The thickly forested area of about 32 acres was surrounded
during the 1930s and 1940s by a solid wood fence topped by barbed
wire, witnesses said.
   ``Residents of surrounding villages tried to bypass this
terrible place where from which day and night were heard shots,
screams, cries and pleadings,'' Moscow News said.
   One witness was quoted as saying people were shot in batches and
that dogs guarded the area.
   The fence surrounding the forest was eventually taken down and
in recent times the site was a favorite place for city-dwellers,
unaware of the bloody past of the area, to rest and have picnics.
   Stalin launched a bloody purge against Byelorussians in June
1937.
   ``The Great Terror,'' Robert Conquest's chronicle of Stalin's
purges, says many Byelorussian officials, writers and other
cultural figures were accused of being Polish spies or otherwise
anti-Soviet and expelled from the Communist Party. Many were
arrested and executed.
   The espionage charges and other allegations touched industrial
enterprises, the Academy of Sciences, the banks, cement industry,
bread supply organization and railways, Conquest wrote.
   Western historians estimate up to 20 million people were killed
in Stalin's purges. There is no breakdown on the number of victims
in Byelorussia.
   Moscow News said the Byelorussian government and prosecutors
office launched an investigation after the newspaper of the
republic's writers' union published a report on the discovery.
   Moscow News did not say when the discovery was made or when the
Byelorussian newspaper article appeared.
   A government commission exhumed human remains and found 500
graves at Kurpati. Investigators also discovered signs of a
previous exhumation and are trying to learn who was responsible,
Moscow News said.
   Some of the graves were destroyed when a gas pipeline was run
through Kurpati and a road built, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
