<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Germany-Bandits 6thLd-Writethru a0466 08-18 0868</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Bandits, 6th Ld - Writethru, a0466,0894</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Robbers Flee in Getaway Car With Hostage AFter Killing One</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs with robbers fleeing in getaway car with
hostage, other hostages free. ADDS byline. Pick up 6th pvs,
`Fechner said...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HENGELO, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bank robbers fled West Germany
in a hijacked bus Thursday after killing a teen-age hostage, then
escaped with another hostage in a car provided by Dutch officials,
police said.
   The bandits had taken 25 people hostage in the bus, which
crossed the border into the Netherlands early Thursday. They
released two women and three children but demanded a getaway car in
return for the freedom of the remaining captives, Dutch police
spokesman Jan Houdel said.
   Houdel told The Associated Press that at about 6:30 a.m., the
hijackers sped off in a BMW provided by Dutch authorities and
headed west. About 30 minutes earlier, two captives on the bus were
injured when the bandits fired two shots, Houdel said. Their
conditions were not immediately known.
   The other captives escaped after the hijackers left the bus, he
said.
   Houdel said Dutch police were in pursuit of the car. There was
no information on the person still held captive.
   West German police spokesman Horst Fechner said a 15-year-old
boy shot Wednesday night had died in a Bremen hospital, where he
was taken after being dumped at a highway rest area. His identity
was not released.
   Fechner also said a West German police officer died in a car
crash while pursuing the bus. No further details were immediately
available.
   Reporters who had been following the bus after it left Bremen
earlier Wednesday said the young man was shot at about 11 p.m. (5
p.m. EDT), after police at the rest area grabbed a woman who
apparently was an accomplice of the bank robbers.
   Two hostages taken when the gunmen robbed a bank Tuesday in
Gladbeck were freed at the rest area.
   As the bus roared back onto the highway, the gunmen opened fire
inside the vehicle, their bullets smashing windows, Associated
Press photographer Peter Maer said.
   ``They started firing wildly,'' said Maer.
   Many passengers could be seen standing in the back of the bus,
Maer said, but he did not know whether the bandits were shooting at
the hostages or just at the windows.
   Police grabbed the woman at the rest area, then one of the
bandits aimed his gun at the young man's head and fired, reporters
at the scene said. Two passengers pulled the victim out of the bus
and left him on the ground, they added.
   Earlier Wednesday, the gunmen had seized the vehicle at a bus
stop in Bremen. They drove off three hours later with about 25
hostages aboard after freeing five elderly passengers.
   The ZDF television network showed film of one bandit, identified
by law officials as 31-year-old Hans-Juergen Roesner, holding his
pistol against the head of a small girl outside the bus in Bremen.
   Captor and hostage then re-entered the bus, and the vehicle left
the bus stop at 9:50 p.m. (3:40 p.m. EDT).
   Journalists reported seeing the bus drive onto the highway
connecting Bremen and Hamburg minutes later.
   Earlier, Roesner used the bus radio to demand a fast getaway car
with a handcuffed policeman as hostage inside, or else ``there
would be shooting,'' according to police spokesman Hermann Scholz
and ZDF.
   About 100 heavily armed police officers, many with pistols drawn
and crouched behind cars, had been surrounding the bus in Bremen.
   Roesner radioed during the Bremen siege that he and his partner
had been joined by a woman friend, and witnesses said the woman was
also armed.
   Lawmen identified Roesner's male accomplice as 32-year-old
Dieter Degowski. They did not know who the woman companion was.
   Scholz said that after five passengers were freed, unhurt,
Roesner offered to let the rest of them go. In exchange, he
demanded that a police officer be left inside a getaway car,
handcuffed and wearing only a bathing suit to make sure he carried
no weapon, the spokesman said.
   In an interview with ZDF earlier in the evening, Roesner also
demanded $157,000 to $210,000.
   ``If our demands our not met, there will be shooting,'' Roesner
said.
   On Tuesday, the two gunmen fled a bank in Gladbeck, about 135
miles southeast of Bremen, with two hostage bank employees and
$227,000 in a police-supplied automobile.
   Police lost the trail after the robbers switched cars.
   The two gunmen surfaced in Bremen, walking into a vegetable
market, firing shots which hurt no one and taking a woman hostage,
said another police spokesman, who spoke on condition he not be
identified.
   Minutes later, at about 7 p.m. (1 p.m. EDT), ``with the new
hostage they went by foot to a bus stop and climbed into a bus with
about 30 people on board,'' said the spokesman.
   From time to time, Roesner left the stationary bus, parked not
far from the Bremen airport, to talk to reporters.
   He said he was ``totally ticked off'' that police had not given
up their search. He also warned against any attempt by police to
storm the bus.
   ``We have guns, too,'' Roesner said.
</TEXT>
