<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Little or No Relief Seen For Areas Hit By Drought, Heat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Weather Service says areas
throughout the United States hit by drought, high heat or the
threat of forest fires will continue to suffer.
   The service's 30-day forecast for mid-August to mid-September,
released Wednesday, said the Dakotas, Nebraska, Iowa and the
western Great Lakes area, the farming heartland already withered by
drought will continue to be dry.
   The same area, and the Eastern region from North Carolina to
Maine, also are expected to continue to endure higher-than-normal
temperatures, while the risk of forest fires will continue high in
the timberlands from Minnesota west to Washington and south through
California the weather service said. It warned that the risk will
be ``extreme'' for parts of Wymoning, Montana, Idaho, Oregon,
Nevada and California.
   Higher than normal rainfall is predicted for the Texas-Louisiana
Gulf Coast and for the Southeast, from Florida to North Carolina,
the weather service said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>25th Anniversary March Aimed At Reviving King's `Dream'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizers of a march to commemorate the
largest civil rights demonstration in U.S. history say they want to
revive the vision set Martin Luther King Jr. set forth in his ``I
have a dream'' speech 25 years ago.
   The Rev. Joseph E. Lowery, president of the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference and a chief planner of the commemorative
march said many people who attended the 1963 ``March on
Washington'' with King are concerned about the state of the dream.
   ``While the dream has been realized in some respects,'' he told
a news conference on Wednesday, ``in other aspects it has been
deferred, it is in a holding pattern.''
   Leaders of the march will call for legislation to relieve
poverty and joblessness, improve housing and human rights and
combat drugs and AIDS, the acquired immune deficiency syndrome,
Lowery said. They also will urge a moratorium on testing of nuclear
weapons and stiffer sanctions against South Africa.
   Organizers said they expected about 100,000 people to attend the
march Aug. 27.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Insurance Group Reduced Payments To Hopsitals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new study indicates that changes by the
federal government and efforts by the Blue Cross and Blue Shield
health insurance plans to contain hospital costs may be working.
   According to the study released Wednesday the private payers
reduced their payments to hospitals by $4.8 billion over a
three-year period.
   The study appears to counter claims made in 1983 when the
federal government changed the way it reimbursed hospitals for
Medicare patients and experts predicted that would result in
hospitals recouping losses from private insurors such as Blue Cross.
   Richard Scheffler, a California health economist who conducted
the study, covering the years 1983 to 1986, said hospitals tended
to apply the guidelines set under Medicare's prospective payment
system to their private patients as well.
   ``It (the prospective payment system) ended up profoundly
changing the overall operation of the hospital,'' Scheffler told a
news conference.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   He said some of the savings realized by Blue Cross and Blue
Shield plans resulted from Medicare-driven changes at hospitals and
some from the private insurors's own cost-containment strategies.
</TEXT>
