<1ST_LINE>d a BC-Theater     08-18 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angelina Reaux Sings, Acts Weill Songs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soprano Angelina Reaux confidently mixes acting
with singing Kurt Weill songs in ``Stranger Here Myself,'' now
running at the off-Broadway Susan Stein Shiva Theater in the Public
Theater complex.
   Her full-bodied operatic voice is sure and attractive and her
acting isn't overdone. Her show is effective to a degree but isn't
a completely rewarding evening of theater. The ingredient that's
missing is the ability to convey the emotion of the songs through
the sound of her voice.
   The stage is set as a hotel room with a few small tables, lamps,
a chair and a red spread on the bed. Miss Reaux wears a black
dress, has a small, battered suitcase. She sings one song after
another, not making a story line, but acting each of them.
   In ``The Barbara Song'' from ``The Threepenny Opera,'' when she
recounts saying no to men but not saying no to Macheath, she lies
on the bed and grabs the headboard as though she's in bondage.
   In the title song, ``I'm a Stranger Here Myself,'' with its
catchy melody and lyrics by Ogden Nash, from ``One Touch of
Venus,'' she's tipsy while really delivering the song. The next,
``Surabaya Johnny,'' has her whimpering, reaching toward a bottle
of pills, apparently considering suicide. Then she lightens the
mood again with ``Foolish Heart,'' also from ``One Touch of Venus.''
   Her operatic voice is perfect for ``Lonely House'' from ``Street
Scene'' but low-down irony is needed for ``Solomon Song'' from
``Threepenny Opera'' and Miss Reaux doesn't deliver it.
   There are survivors in Kurt Weill songs, there's tragedy,
heartbreak, abuse, hopeless love, daydreams of ships coming in and
rescuing a life. They're greatly to be enjoyed by people who like
strong songs instead of wimpy ones; they're enjoyed less by people
who prefer upbeat sentiments and situations.
   Miss Reaux has sung a great deal for conductor Leonard
Bernstein, which is a strong recommendation. Her show, which had
three instrumentalists, was directed by Christopher Alden.
   However, anybody who has heard Teresa Stratas, also an opera
singer, sing Weill knows that she can be bawdy, despairing,
misguided, hard-hearted or swaggeringly stoical just through the
sound of her voice. That has a stronger impact that Miss Reaux
singing as she acts out the songs' sentiments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880818-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0343EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NuclearTest     08-18 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Test,0628</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-Soviet Officials See Blast As Step Toward Nuclear-Free World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PAHUTE MESA, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Soviet officials say their
historic joint nuclear weapons test explosion could be the first
step toward a world without atomic bombs.
   Wednesday's Joint Verification Experiment was the culmination of
a four-year effort to slow the nuclear arms race and a product of
better U.S.-Soviet relations.
   It was the first time Soviet scientists joined their American
counterparts in the control room at the top-secret Nevada Test Site
to monitor a nuclear weapons explosion. Forty-five American
scientists and diplomats will gather similar data Sept. 14 at the
Soviet's Semipalatinsk test site.
   The detonation beneath this picturesque, 7,500-foot mesa had 12
times the force of the Hiroshima bomb. The scientists watched the
surface affects of the underground explosion, 30 miles away, by
television.
   ``It was a resounding success,'' said James Magruder, the test
controller for the experiment dubbed Kearsarge.
   The blast registered 5.4 on the Richter scale of ground movement
at the National Earthquake Information Center in Golden, Colo., and
caused some high-rise hotels in Las Vegas, 100 miles away, to sway.
   C. Paul Robinson, the U.S. ambassador to the negotiations that
led to the test, called the test ``a step down the road to a more
stable world.''
   ``How far we go depends on what we negotiate on weapons
themselves,'' Robinson said. ``I hope we can take the process to
the point where there is no need for weapons at all.''
   Igor Palenykh, head of the Soviet delegation to the talks in
Geneva, told reporters that the Soviet Union's goal is a total ban
on nuclear testing.
   ``As far as the Soviet Union is concerned we are prepared at any
time to cease nuclear testing along with the United States,'' he
said through an interpreter.
   About 35 anti-nuclear protesters turned out at the gates of the
1,350-square-mile site and 12 were cited for trespassing or
blocking traffic, then released.
   The size of the blast was listed officially as between 100 and
150 kilotons.
   The ability to measure the size of U.S. and Soviet tests is
critical in monitoring treaties signed in 1974 and 1976 limiting
the size of nuclear tests to no more than 150 kilotons. The
treaties were never ratified by the U.S. Senate.
   Thirty seconds after detonation, Viktor Mikhailov, leader of the
Soviet scientific team, answered a phone and raised his right hand
with an OK signal, indicating the Soviets had received the data
they were seeking from their monitoring equipment. Mikhailov's
signal was greeted with applause.
   U.S. and Soviet scientists monitored the test with sophisticated
equipment housed in unmanned trailers a few hundred yards from
ground zero.
   Later, Mikhailov joined scientists, diplomats and military
officials from the two superpowers at a crowded news conference.
   Mikhailov said he had been apprehensive about coming to the
United States and meeting his counterparts. But, he said, he grew
to trust and respect the Americans and felt the feeling was mutual.
   ``We have cut a window into their hearts,'' he said of the U.S.
scientists he has worked with since spring.
   The test, he said, could play a major role ``in the path leading
to a nuclear-free world.''
   The Soviet scientists first visited Las Vegas and the test site
last January a month after an agreement by President Reagan and
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev cleared the way for such exchanges.
Reagan had been trying for nearly four years to orchestrate the
joint verification tests.
   The Soviets returned in March, living at a test site base camp
in Mercury, 65 miles northwest of Las Vegas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880818-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0403EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Parties     08-18 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Parties,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Celebrity Conventioners Party Privately Amid Hoopla</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT CHARTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tommy Andrade discreetly recorded the dinner
reservation for ``Jones,'' and winked.
   ``It was a celebrity, but they want privacy,'' said Andrade,
maitre d' at the Fairmont Hotel's ritzy Sazerac Restaurant. ``It's
an alias, of course.''
   But of course.
   The stars of the Republican National Convention aren't just
politicos. They also include the likes of actor Charlton Heston,
evangelist Billy Graham, and billionaire real estate developer
Donald Trump.
   ``The people who use aliases, they want complete privacy,''
Andrade said. ``They have stressed complete privacy. They only
allow myself and one waiter into the private dining rooms.''
   A bunch of senators used the alias ``Jackson'' to reserve party
space in the Sazerac. The Rev. Jerry Falwell's private table was
held Wednesday night under the name of an assistant, Andrade said.
   Curious pedestrians are cued by the arrival of stretch
limousines, and some surge forward in hopes of a handshake,
autograph, or greeting. Jere Smith, a spokesman for Phillips
Petroleum, said his bosses from Oklahoma were embarrassed when
people bolted into busy streets to peer through their limousine's
tinted windows. A few onlookers posed for photographs beside the
luxurious wheels, he said.
   Trump said his invitation to the convention revelry came from
Vice President George Bush. They both were checked into the
high-rise Marriott, overlooking the Mississippi River. ``I'm
looking at this as a vacation. I'm really here to watch,'' Trump
said.
   Heston wowed Michigan delegates during a Wednesday gathering
with a blast at Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., who led the
``Where was George?'' chant during last month's Democratic National
Convention.
   ``It would have occurred to me to say to the senator, `George
was dry, sober and home with his wife,''' said Heston, a native of
St. Helen, Mich.
   Heston also appeared at parties sponsored by the National Rifle
Association. So did strongman actor Arnold Schwarzenegger, a
Republican whose wife, Maria Shriver, is kin to the Kennedys.
   But Schwarzenegger didn't make a much-anticipated visit to a
confab of the Mississippi delegation, said chairwoman Evelyn
McPhail.
   ``I was looking forward to meeting Arnold Schwarzenegger,'' said
Ms. McPhail, who hasn't seen any of the muscleman's films. ``I've
only heard of him because of his weightlifting. I'm not a
moviegoer.''
   The Mississippi delegation chief endorses using celebrities to
get attention for political causes. ``If it doesn't have an
influence on how people vote, at least it's magnetism in getting
them to listen,'' Ms. McPhail said.
</TEXT>
