<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--FamilyRollcall     08-18 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Family Rollcall,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Texas Proudly Casts 111 Votes For ... The Best Father In America'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was nomination day for George Bush, but it
might well have been Father's Day. No cards could have been sweeter
for a father than the public and affectionate tributes Bush's five
children paid him at the Republican convention.
   One by one, as the clerk called the roll of the states, the four
sons and one daughter of Bush _ all delegates _ announced the votes
for their respective states, adding a personal touch to a ritual
that was as unnecessary as it was overlong.
   It fell to George W. Bush, the oldest at 42, to announce the
vote from Texas that put his father over the top. Other states
passed their turn to accord the Bush home state the privilege.
   ``The great state of Texas proudly casts 111 votes for a man we
respect and a man we love,'' said George W., a director of a
Dallas-based oil company. ``Texas casts all its votes for her
favorite son and the best father in America.''
   Later, he told a reporter, ``there was never any question in my
mind, although I was there in Iowa (_ the caucus where Bush placed
third _ ) that this moment would come for George Bush. I'm happy
for him, and I'm honored that I had the chance to put him over.''
   The nominee's daughter, Dorothy Bush LeBlond, announced Maine's
vote.
   ``I have never been prouder than I am at this moment to be able
to cast all 22 votes from the state of Maine to the most decent,
the most honest, the most caring man ever to seek the presidency,''
she said. ``The man who made me proud every single day of my life
and a man who will make America proud, the next president of the
United States, my beloved father, George Bush.''
   Bush and his wife were babysitting for their 10 grandchildren at
their hotel, watching the proceedings on television. When he had
officially wrapped up the nomination, the picture was transmitted
to the five huge screens in the convention hall to the delight of
delegates.
   As the Texas vote approached, Bush exclaimed, ``Here we come.
Here's the big moment.'' Then, turning to his wife, he pointed to
the scene on television and said: ``There's Junior,'' referring to
his son by his nickname.
   Playing to prime-time television, the Republicans took the
unusual step of staging their 20-minute celebration of the
uncontested nomination before the vote, dropping 50,000 balloons on
the delegates while drums rolled, the band played and state flags
waved.
   Jeb Bush, 35, Florida's Secretary of Commerce announced that
state's vote ``for the next first lady of the United States,
Barbara Bush, and the next president, George Bush.''
   Neil, 33, president of a Denver oil and gas firm, was the first
Bush child to take one of the floor microphones.
   ``I am proud to cast Colorado's votes for a man I dearly love, a
man who's been there when I needed him,'' Neil said.
   And Marvin, 31, a partner in an investment advisory firm in
Charlottesville, Va., stood at his state's microphone and said:
   ``I'm not going to sugarcoat it for you. I'm proud. I'm proud to
be a delegate and resident of the Commonwealth of Virginia, but I'm
especially proud to cast all 50 of her votes for a man who is
adored by his wife and five children, his five in-laws and his 10
grandchildren _ and the next president, my dad, George Bush.''
</TEXT>
