<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HolocaustPact     08-18 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Holocaust Pact,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Sign Pact To Make Holocaust Material Available to U.S.
Scholars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union will make available millions
of Nazi documents, photographs and other records of the Holocausrt
captured in Eastern Europe by Soviet troops at the end of World War
II for inclusion in the U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum, according
to officials planning the museum.
   The U.S. Holocaust Memorial Council on Wednesday announced that
the materials will be made available for the first time to Western
scholars, investigators and legal experts through an agreement
signed with the Soviets in Moscow on July 29.
   ``We're obviously thrilled,'' said Miles Lerman, chairman of the
Committee of International Relations for the council.
   ``We have tried before to get this information, but were always
unsuccessful,'' added Lerman, who led a six-person delegation on a
visiting tour of Soviet archives for two weeks in July.
   The accord will give the council access to the materials for
copying and inclusion in the U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum which
is to be located near the Mall and expected to open in 1991.
   Council officials estimate that 30 percent to 40 percent of the
material currently available about the Holocaust is scattered in
dozens of archives in the Soviet Union.
   Lerman credited ``the new spirit of glasnost'' for Soviet
willingness to make the records available.
   Until now, the Soviets would only release information requested
for specific cases, like an identity card used as evidence in the
case against former concentration camp guard John Demjanjuk who was
sentenced to death in Israel in April.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
