<DOCNO> AP880818-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0324EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     08-18 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar High, Share Prices Lose Ground</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar stayed higher after a jump at the
opening, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost some
of their ground gained during Thursday's trading.
   The dollar, which opened at 134.00 yen, moved in a range of
133.73-134.10 yen, to close at 133.93, up 0.78 yen from Wednesday's
close.
   After opening the day's trade at 28,291.11 points following
Wednesday's rebound, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, the most widely used index of the market, edged down 49.50
points from Wednesday's close, or 0.18 percent, to finish at
28,129.36 points.
   The foreign exchange dealers attributed the dollar's jump to the
0.25 yen gained on Wall Street overnight.
   ``The dollar is basically firm, but profit-taking pushes it down
when it surpasses the 134.00 mark,'' said a dealer at a U.S. bank's
Tokyo office. ``As a result, the dollar is unlikely to move out of
the range of 132.00-134.00 for a while,'' he added, requesting
anonymity.
   A stock dealer who also asked to remain anonymous said
Thursday's trading was slow. ``Basically, it was a little break for
the market after its hectic trade yesterday,'' he said, adding that
the slow trading was partly because the steel and finance related
stocks did not do well.
   The stock market traded 500 million shares in the first session,
but it slowed down during the afternoon session, trading 250
million shares.
</TEXT>
