<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Dole 1stLd-Writethru a0489 08-18 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Dole, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0489,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole, His Ambitions Unrealized, Pledges to Serve Bush</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT age to 65 sted 69.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bob Dole hailed the selection of fellow
senator Dan Quayle as the Republican vice presidential candidate
while assailing Michael Dukakis as ``the Massachusetts liberal''
who would undermine the nation's defenses.
   Dole, 65, who came to the Republican National Convention
believing he had a chance to be tapped by George Bush for the
ticket's No. 2 spot, showed no sign of disappointment Wednesday
night as he pledged to work for Bush's election and portrayed
Quayle as ``articulate'' and ``dynamic.''
   The Kansas senator said Dukakis' bid for the White House should
be rejected by the nation because he is ``one of those liberal
doomsayers who believe that America cannot be trusted ... who is
uncomfortable when America stands on the side of freedom.''
   In a speech that was just four pages long, Dole called Dukakis a
liberal 17 times, six times calling him ``the Massachusetts
liberal.''
   Dole, the Senate minority leader, ran for vice president in 1976
and vainly sought his party's presidential nomination this year and
in 1980. He described himself as ready and eager to serve as George
Bush's ``point man'' in the Senate next January.
   ``I promise to beat back any Democratic schemes to raise your
taxes, or any effort to weaken our national defense,'' he said.
   He then launched his attack on Dukakis, sharply criticizing the
Democratic nominee's inexperience in foreign policy and his
declared opposition to military aid to Nicaragua's Contra rebels,
new-model nuclear missiles, the B1 bomber and the ``Star Wars''
strategic defense system.
   He asserted that Dukakis is ready to ``throw the Monroe Doctrine
away'' when it comes to confronting communism and Soviet influence
in Nicaragua and Central America.
   ``He speaks Spanish freely on the campaign trail, but he is not
concerned whether Spanish-speaking people in Central America have
the right to be free,'' Dole said.
   ``The governor is one of those liberals who is suspicious of
America's strength, embarrassed when America asserts its rights,
uncomfortable when America stands on the side of freedom,'' he
declared.
   Dukakis is ``one of those liberals with strange ideas _
Dukak-eyed ideas _ about the way the world works,'' he said.
   Dole said Dukakis does not understand that recent U.S. foreign
policy successes were made possible only by the rebuilding of the
nation's military strength.
   ``Liberals like the Massachusetts governor ... don't understand
that a strong America keeps the peace and a weak America invites
danger,'' he said.
   ``In the world according to Mike, America needs an OK from the
United Nations before it can act,'' he declared.
   Dole contended that improved relations with the Soviet Union
resulted because President Reagan ``said no to aggression.''
   ``Knowing when to say yes and when to say no,'' he said, ``it
separates leadership from mere office holding; it separates leaders
from technocrats.''
   Kansas delegates staged a brief but enthusiastic demonstration
on the Superdome floor when Dole was introduced by Sen. Nancy
Kassebaum, R-Kan.
   The Kansans brought more than 800 Dole signs into the arena,
distributing them among other delegations for the demonstration.
   Dole reciprocated by going to the Kansas section following his
speech and sitting with the delegation, shaking hands and posing
for pictures. He stayed until Gov. Mike Hayden cast Kansas' 34
votes for Bush in his first-ballot nomination.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
