<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Iran-Iraq     08-18 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Iran-Iraq,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Assembly Approves Funds For Gulf War Military Observer
Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Assembly has approved a $35.7
million assessment to cover the first three months of operations of
the U.N. force that will monitor a cease-fire between Iran and Iraq.
   The truce begins Saturday, and peace talks between Iran and Iraq
start Aug. 25 in Geneva, mediated by U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar.
   America's share of the cost of the U.N. Iran-Iraq Military
Observer Group is $10.9 million for the first three months,
according to the assessment formula for peacekeeping operations.
   The 159-member General Assembly on Wednesday adopted by
consensus its budget committee's recommendation for the assessment.
   A total of 1,300 personnel from 24 nations, including 350
unarmed military observers, will monitor the cease-fire.
   The General Assembly asked the secretary-general to report back
by Oct. 1 on the first phase of the operation.
   A U.N. report said the observer force should cost $75.6 for six
months. The United States was expected to pay about $23 million of
the total.
   Japan has pledged $10 million in extra contributions to the
peacekeeping costs, and Morocco has promised to donate $2 million.
   The Security Council created the U.N. Iran-Iraq Military
Observer Group on Aug. 9 after Iran and Iraq agreed to observe the
cease-fire.
   Prior to Wednesday's vote, members of the General Assembly
observed a minute of silence and offered eulogies for Pakistan's
President Mohammad Zia ul-Haq, who died earlier in the day in a
military aircraft crash.
   The U.S. ambassador to Pakistan, Arnold L. Raphel, was among
other victims who were aboard the C-130 transport.
</TEXT>
