<DOCNO> AP880818-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0542EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Pappan'sPicnic     08-18 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pappan's Picnic,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greek Immigrant Feeds Thousands To Say Thanks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE DRESSLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEAVER FALLS, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Greek immigrant who treasured the
candy, sugar and clothes he got in U.S. relief packages as a child
has found a way to say thanks over and over again: an annual picnic
for thousands of senior citizens.
   ``From the day I walk into this country, that's about 37 years
ago, I never had a sad day yet,'' restaurateur Lou Pappan said at
his 14th summer picnic Wednesday. ``I never met a person in this
country I did not really like.''
   The 12-hour picnic, a country hoedown in Bradys Run Park, has
become a summertime tradition for senior citizens in Beaver County,
a depressed patch of steel country about 25 miles west of
Pittsburgh.
   ``It's wonderful. Once a year you get out of the house and under
the trees. I think Lou's the most wonderful person in the world,''
said Elsie White, 58, of Coraopolis.
   She has been to all of Pappan's picnics and this year brought 33
senior citizens in a bus.
   ``I enjoy the bingo,'' said Rudolph Hiber, 77, of Aliquippa.
``I've been on a pension for 17 years. It's nice to meet some
people.''
   This year's picnic featured spaghetti and meat sauce, rolls and
tapioca pudding served on covered picnic tables in humid, 95-degree
weather. County Recreation Director Jack Hilfinger said more than
3,000 people were on hand by noon, and Pappan said he had expected
6,000 through the evening.
   He said the bash will cost him $30,000.
   Volunteers, many of them Pappan's employees, began serving cold
drinks at 9 a.m. Entertainment included a bluegrass band, square
dancing and contests for crafts, food and paintings.
   Pappan, 57, began throwing the picnics in 1975 to thank
Americans for helping Greece during World War II.
   ``This country's got a heart so big,'' Pappan said. ``Of all the
countries I could have went to, here I am. I came to the United
States, the best country in the world.''
   Pappan, born Illiasi Demetrios Papankolaou, grew up in
Makrakomi, Greece, where his father operated a restaurant. He
didn't speak English when he came to live with his uncle in Beaver
Falls in 1951.
   As a boy in the poverty-stricken Greek village during World War
II, Pappan said he watched some of his friends die of starvation.
He searched the skies for American aircraft that would bring help.
   ``They dropped big boxes full of clothing and also food,'' he
said in his thick Greek accent. ``We got sometimes white sugar,
sometimes brown sugar. We even received sometimes chocolate bars.
It was a very big deal.''
   Some of the clothing lasted years, Pappan said.
   ``I remember a pair of pants and a shirt I used to wear in my
high school days,'' he said. ``I graduated from high school wearing
those pants.''
   After Pappan enlisted in the U.S. Army during the Korean War, a
sergeant who called him ``Alphabet'' convinced him his Greek name
was too difficult for Americans to pronounce.
   He opened his first Pappan's Family Restaurant in 1964 near
Beaver Falls. Now about 1,200 people work at his 18 Roy Rogers
restaurants, 14 Pappan's Family Restaurants and three specialty
restaurants in western Pennsylvania. He says his food business will
gross about $20 million this year.
   Pappan acknowledges that publicity about the picnic is good for
business, but says ``it's better for our soul.''
   ``I want to die as a nice man instead of a rich man.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
