<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Briefs,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delegate Hat Features Quail In Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dick Bigelow has been parading around the
Republican National Convention all week with a thick, green
``bush'' atop his straw hat _ in honor of GOP ticket-topper George
Bush.
   He sported a new adornment on the chapeau when he arrived at the
Superdome on Wednesday night: tucked among the plastic leaves was
an actual stuffed quail _ a tribute to the No. 2 man on the GOP
ticket, Dan Quayle.
   ``It wasn't easy to find. I had to search all over town,'' said
Bigelow, an alternate delegate from Castro Valley, Calif. His
search ended at a riverfront shopping mall where he found the bird
encased in a lamp.
   ``I took the lamp apart, took the quail out and then I had the
lamp sent back to California,'' he said.
   Bigelow said it was worth the $235 cost.
   ``Everybody says, `Like that hat.' It's a symbol,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bentsen, Quayle Already Have Debated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Lloyd Bentsen and Republican Dan
Quayle had been on opposite sides of the debate podium even before
the two senators were selected to be their parties' vice
presidential candidates.
   The senators went head-to-head four months ago on public
television's MacNeil-Lehrer NewsHour over a trade bill eventually
vetoed by President Reagan because of a provision that would
require companies to warn workers of plant closings.
   The Public Broadcasting Service has released a transcript of the
April 22 show, billing it as ``the only known televised debate
between the two candidates.''
   The Senate eventually approved the trade bill, Reagan vetoed it
and Bentsen devised the successful strategy of putting the
plant-closing provision into a separate measure that Reagan allowed
to become law.
