<HEAD>NEW ORLEANS: to safety.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   On a bombing run at Chichi Jima, his plane was hit, both his
crewmen were killed. As flames swept over the wings and cockpit,
George Bush remembered the first obligation of a leader is to
accomplish the mission.
   He stayed on his bombing run and dropped two tons of TNT right
on the target. He turned his crippled plane out to sea and bailed
out. The Japanese sent boats to capture him, but his fellow pilots
hovered over him, strafing the Japanese to keep them back.
   With blood streaming down his face, with a .38 revolver in one
hand, he paddled away from the shore with the other hand to be
rescued by a submarine.
   Let me read from his citation for the Distinguished Flying Cross.
   ``By his superb airmanship, courageous actions, and loyal
dedication to duty, Lieutenant Bush reflected great credit upon
himself and upheld the highest traditions of the United States
Naval Service,'' signed, Franklin Delano Roosevelt.
   My friends, my friends, when Michael Dukakis vetoed that bill
providing for the pledge of allegiance to the American flag in
Massachusetts public schools he did not represent the views of
George Bush.
   We will never have to worry about George Bush's willingness to
stand up for America.
   He knows from real life experience that peace comes through
strength, not through wishful thinking.
   The commitment of George Bush and Ronald Reagan to a strong
national defense has brought peace. It has brought the Soviets to
the bargaining table and produced the unprecedented elimination of
a whole class of nuclear weapons.
   Under George Bush's leadership, we can keep America strong and
at peace. We can let the real competition begin, a competition of
vision and ideas.
   Building on the bedrock achievements of the Reagan-Bush years,
we can move beyond simply maintaining the little freedom which
exists on this Earth.
   The defense of freedom today begins in Nicaragua and
Afghanistan, but the competition of vision and ideas can never end
until all the world is free, including the people of Central
America and Cuba and Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union itself.
   George Bush, warrior when his country needed warriors, came home
from the war and married the girl whose name was painted on the
side of his plane _ Barbara.
   He came home to continue his education and to put the American
free enterprise system to work for him and for his family. George
took his family and moved to Midland, Texas, and started in the oil
business.
   He learned the business working for others and went into
business for himself. He met the payroll, paid the bills and
pioneered new technology used today around the world.
   In time, George Bush turned again to public service, being
elected as Houston's first Republican congressman since
Reconstruction. In the House of Representatives he fought against
excessive government spending and for civil rights.
   He later served as ambassador to the United Nations, and when
history was made with the opening of relations with communist
China, George Bush was sent to Peking to represent our nation.
</TEXT>
