<1ST_LINE>r p BC-CVN--DoleText 3Takes   08-18 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Dole Text, 3 Takes,670-2040</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Text of Dole Speech</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of the speech by Sen.
Bob Dole of Kansas to the Republican National Convention Wednesday
night.
   Thank you very much. Thank you very much. Thank you very much.
Thank you very much. I accept the nomination as majority leader of
the United States Senate.
   Let me underscore my priorities for 1988.
   First of all, I am committed to electing George Bush president
of the United States in November.
   I am committed to electing Republicans to Congress.
   So tonight, I am asking you to help us strengthen our party in
the House, and to help us regain the majority in the United States
Senate.
   I am ready and eager to serve as George Bush's point man in a
Republican controlled Senate come January. I promise to beat back
any Democratic schemes to raise your taxes, or any effort to weaken
our national defense.
   Let me congratulate my colleague Dan Quayle _ our next vice
president.
   I talked to Dan yesterday, I called to congratulate him. I
interrupted him. He was shaving _ for the first time.
   And I can say to my friends all across America I am proud to
have been his leader in the United States Senate. He is young, he's
dynamic, he's articulate. And he's already had 12 years experience
in Congress. If only the Democratic nominee had had half as much we
would be in a stronger position.
   This year's election represents a crossroads for America. The
alternatives have never been more obvious or the consequences more
important.
   The issues will be defense and deficits and detente and drugs.
But the bottom line question is: what kind of country will America
be as it enters a new century. Will we be truly strong, or barely
strong enough? Will we be self-confident, or self-doubting? Will we
be on the march, or at a standstill?
   Strength and security _ the founding fathers saw these two words
as an essential link between them 200 years ago. And we Republicans
see it today. We are secure as individuals only when the country we
live in is strong and confident. And when our country is weak and
uncertain and lacking in will, we are all vulnerable.
   The link between the strength of our nation and the security of
our people seems obvious. But there are always some, and there are
some out there now who never get the picture.
   These people _ the liberal doom sayers _ believe that America
cannot be trusted. They believe that the disarming of America is a
noble goal. They do not understand that America must be strong if
America is to be free. We understand _ all of us in this hall; in
this party and across the country; and of course, George Bush
understands, and George Bush has understood for a long, long time,
the importance of freedom.
   But the Democratic nominee does not. He is undoubtedly a fine
man. He did an excellent job in gaining his party's nomination. He
will work hard between now and November. But unfortunately, he is
one of those liberals who does not know where to draw the line, and
this puts America at risk.
   He seems willing to throw away the Monroe Doctrine. He says he
can live with Soviet client states in Central America. Oh, yes, he
speaks Spanish freely on the campaign trail. But he is not
concerned whether Spanish-speaking people in Central America have
the right to be free.
   And that's the difference.
   The governor is one of those liberals who is suspicious of
America's strength; embarrassed when America asserts its rights;
uncomfortable when America stands on the side of freedom.
   One of those liberals who knocks our president, questions his
principles, and assails his policies. One of those liberals who
suffers a sudden lapse of memory when it comes to the outrages of
the ayatollah, Colonel Gadhafi, Comandante Ortega and other Third
World tyrants.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
