<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Dole Text, 1st Add,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NEW ORLEANS: World tyrants.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   One of those liberals with strange ideas _ Dukak-eyed ideas _
yes, Dukak-eyed ideas _ Dukak-eyed ideas about the way the world
works.
   And think about the last time this kind of liberal occupied the
White House. Think about the four years of malaise and
mismanagement, of disaster.
   Think about all the countries that fell into the Soviet orbit.
Think about Cambodia, where Marxism led to genocide. And think
about Ethiopia, where Marxism led to famine. And Nicaragua, where
Marxism has led to a Soviet beachhead in the Americas. And think
about all these places where the liberals did not know where, or
how, to draw the line.
   And then, and then, think about Grenada, where Ronald Reagan and
George Bush did draw the line, and where its people now have a
democracy. And think about Libya, where Reagan and Bush drew the
line, and they silenced the terrorists. And think about
Afghanistan, where by drawing the line, this administration, Ronald
Reagan and George Bush helped a courageous people survive, and kept
alive their dreams of freedom.
   And think about Angola. And because we backed the freedom
fighters in Angola, a negotiated settlement is possible that could
result in the departure of 40,000 Cuban mercenaries.
   And yes, think about the Persian Gulf, think about the Persian
Gulf. Because we insisted, you insisted, that the American Navy
should draw a line protecting freedom of the seas, and because of
that the end of the Iran-Iraq war is in sight.
   Now I ask you this question, would this have happened if the
liberals had been in the White House? (Crowd: ``No!'')
   Would there have been an improvement in relations with Moscow
and an INF Treaty? (Crowd: ``No!'')
   You got it right both times.
   And you're right and I'll tell you why: because these liberals
define arms control this way: the Soviets arm, while we control.
   And liberals like the Massachusetts governor never get the
picture. They fail to understand that a strong America keeps the
peace. And a weak America invites danger.
   Harry Truman understood where to draw the line in 1947. And
because he did, Greece is a free nation today.
   John F. Kennedy understood where to draw the line in 1962, and
because he did, the Soviet missiles were yanked out of Cuba.
   And those kind of mainstream Democrats who still believe in a
strong national defense are now outcasts in their own party. And
today's liberals, led by Jesse Jackson and Michael Dukakis, will
never understand. They don't have a clue.
   For them, it's always mourning in America _ mourning with a
``U.'' A time to mourn America's recovery, a time to mourn
America's strength, a time to mourn America's new sense of purpose.
   But on the other hand, George Bush understands that strength and
freedom are two sides of the same coin.
   And as a young pilot he risked his life for his country in the
skies of the Pacific. As Ronald Reagan stated Monday evening, he
has helped give this country eight of the best years it has ever
had. That's why I'm proud of George Bush. That's why George Bush is
going to be elected in November of this year.
   And George Bush and Dan Quayle support SDI because it provides
defense against the accidents that cause war, and this keeps the
peace. He supports the B-1 bomber and the stealth bomber and the MX
and Midgetman missiles. Because they deter aggression. And this,
too, keeps the peace.
   George Bush and Dan Quayle support freedom fighters around the
world. And what does the Democratic candidate support? What
programs to keep America truly strong and free?
   Let me list them for you. (Pause.)
   I haven't lost my place, I just can't think of any. There's
gotta be one out there somewhere.
   His idea of national defense is ``one if by land, and two if by
sea'' _ if you can get through the polluted waters of Boston Harbor.
   In the world according to the Massachusetts liberal, defending
liberty is dangerous and it costs too much.
</TEXT>
