<1ST_LINE>r p BC-CVN--DoleText 2ndAdd   08-18 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Dole Text, 2nd Add,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NEW ORLEANS: too much.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   But there's a real world out there. Where America must provide
real leadership.
   In the world according to the Massachusetts liberal, America
should get an OK first from the United Nations before we ever do
anything.
   But there's a real world out there. And sometimes America must
act on its own to protect our interests, and your interests and
your children's interests.
   And in the world according to the Massachusetts liberal,
communism and terrorism and drugs are just issues to be managed.
   But there's a real world out there where America must defend the
freedoms we cherish, and stand against those who would take those
freedoms away.
   And finally, let me remind Americans _ all Americans,
Republicans and Democrats and independents _ there is no owner's
manual for the Oval Office. You don't learn to lead a nation
through on-the-job training or by having Harvard professors come to
Washington for a seminar.
   So, this campaign really boils down to one thing, keep one thing
in mind in this campaign, and that's leadership. And leadership
involves many things, but chief among them is knowing when to say
yes and when to say no.
   There's nothing more important. It is the mark of character in a
leader. It can change the course of history.
   In the early 1980s, for example, the Massachusetts liberal and
his fellow liberals were saying yes to the nuclear freeze and
George Bush was saying no. George Bush knew that the freeze the
Massachusetts liberal supported would have frozen in place 1,500
nuclear-tipped Soviet missiles aimed at the heart of Europe, and
frozen out of Europe our missiles.
   The Massachusetts liberal predicted that this would prolong the
Cold War.
   Well, he had it exactly wrong. It was only after our missiles
arrived in Europe that the Soviets began to bargain. And they
bargained until all of the intermediate-range missiles were gone.
And the bargaining is not over yet.
   Because Ronald Reagan and George Bush had said no to the huge
Soviet military build-up that took place the last time the liberals
were in charge, and no to the Soviet expansionism of the Carter
years _ because they said no to Soviet aggression _ Ronald Reagan
and George Bush were able to say yes to improved relations with the
Soviet Union.
   So knowing when to say yes and when to say no _ it separates
leadership from mere office-holding, it separates leaders from
technocrats.
   And so, yes, the 1988 election is very serious business.
   We're electing a president, and also the next leader of the free
world.
   And I realized this fully just three months ago in Moscow. I was
with President Reagan as he put his final seal on his historic arms
control treaty with the Soviet Union.
   And while there, I was seated next to Mikhail Gorbachev at a
state dinner. And for nearly three hours, I had an opportunity to
exchange views with him, face-to-face. And let me tell you, I was
impressed. Gorbachev is smart. He's shrewd. And believe me, he is
committed to the goals of the communist world he leads.
   After dinner, as I was driven back to my hotel, our car passed
through Red Square, and past the forbidding skyline of the Kremlin.
And I thought about Gorbachev, I thought to myself, and I thought
what might lie ahead. And I knew that the free world could not
afford to deal with this hard-as-nails communist with an untested,
unprepared, unsure president _ someone who did not know where to
draw the line, someone who did not know when to say yes and when to
say no.
   Today, we look at the world and our place in it, and say, thank
God for Ronald Reagan.
   Four years from now, we'll be meeting again. We will think about
the world again, we will think how fortunate it was that the
American voters _ Republicans and Democrats and independents _
didn't make a mistake in 1988. And we'll say in 1992, thank God for
George Bush!
   Thank you very much.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End Dole Text _ 3 Takes</HEAD>
