<1ST_LINE>r a PM-YonkersDeseg     08-18 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yonkers Deseg,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yonkers' Reprieve from Contempt Fines Continues _ For Now</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mounting fines against Yonkers have been further
delayed while a federal appeals court decides whether the judge who
imposed them exceeded his authority to punish the city for
resisting housing desegregation.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals continued a stay Wednesday
of potentially crippling fines leveled against the city and four
city councilmen for refusing to approve the court-ordered
desegregation plan.
   The three-judge panel did not say when it would rule on whether
to uphold the contempt citation and fines imposed by U.S. District
Judge Leonard B. Sand. On Aug. 1, the council refused by a 4-3 vote
to endorse the affordable housing plan that would integrate the
state's fourth-largest city. The plan calls for 200 units of
low-income housing and 800 units of moderate-income housing to be
built in the predominantly white east side.
   The escalating fines against the city began at $100, doubling
daily. The fines would surpass the city's entire $337 million
budget in 22 days. The city's fines had accumulated to $26,500 when
the appeals court ordered them temporarily halted last week pending
the appeal of the contempt order.
   The appeals court also stayed Sand's $500-a-day fines against
the four councilmen, who were to be jailed on Aug. 11 before the
2nd Circuit stepped in.
   The City Council again rejected the housing desegregation plan
early Tuesday by the same vote.
   At the hearing before the appeals court Wednesday, Yonkers
attorney Michael W. Sculnick said Sand had exceeded his judicial
discretion in imposing the crippling fines.
   Calling the council hopelessly divided, Sculnick said the city
should not be made to suffer. He said Sand should have bypassed the
council and deemed the housing plan approved himself or else
appointed a housing commission to implement the plan.
   ``The city is stuck. It is incapable of complying with the
federal court's order,'' said Sculnick. He said the four councilmen
had their own political agendas and were playing ``what amounts to
a game of chicken'' waiting for the other guy to change his vote.
   Linda Thome, an attorney for the Justice Department's civil
rights division, said the fines must be reimposed because ``it is
essential that the city be required now to comply with the federal
court's order.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
