<2ND_LINE>PM-DeSillers,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DeSillers Car Seized; Hearing Scheduled on Other Items</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge seized Maria DeSillers' BMW and scheduled a
hearing to decide whether she should be found in contempt of court
for failing to surrender other items allegedly bought with money
donated for her son's liver transplants.
   The $13,500 car was towed away Wednesday from the Coral Gables
office of her attorney. It will remain in storage until the
conclusion of the case, Dade Circuit Judge Francis Christie said.
   Christie scheduled the hearing for next Wednesday. He delayed a
decision on whether Ms. DeSillers can retain a burial plot near the
grave of her son, Ronnie, 7, who died last year after three
unsuccessful transplants.
   Ms. DeSillers' attorney, Roy Black, said he was pleased to have
a chance to present witnesses next week, but refused to comment on
the day's other developments.
   Earlier, Christie made no comment when denying the defense
motion that sought to oust Karen Gievers as curator of Ronnie's
estate. Ms. Gievershas been seeking the car, jewelry and other
items she said Ms. DeSillers purchased with donations for her son.
   Ms. DeSillers' attorney in financial matters, Frank Johnson, who
brought the motion, charged Ms. Gievers has been ``spending money
that was not necessary'' from the estate since her appointment by
Christie on March 7.
   Johnson asked for three days to produce expert testimony from
trust companies to back his motion that a new curator be appointed.
   But Ms. Gievers' lawyer, Michael Dribin, characterized Johnson's
request ``a further delaying tactic.''
   He accused Ms. DeSillers' attorney of seeking an indirect
continuance of Christie's Aug. 8 court order demanding Ms.
DeSillers surrender the contested belongings.
   Christie had extended the court deadline for Ms. DeSillers'
surrender of the items five times before Wednesday's hearing.
   Ms. Gievers has charged Ms. DeSillers spent up to $200,000 of
the nearly $700,000 raised in donations for her son's medical
expenses.
</TEXT>
