<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MaybeMozart     08-18 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Maybe Mozart,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premiere Tonight of New Work That May Be Mozart's</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Music lovers attending tonight's performance by
the Chicago Symphony Winds can expect to hear the American premiere
of a new work of Mozart's.
   Then again, maybe not.
   The question of the authenticity of the score _ a wind band
arrangement titled ```Harmoniemusik,'' which is part of Mozark's
opera ``The Abduction From the Seraglio'' _ along with that of
other scores found periodically, remain the topic of scholarly
debate.
   The piece was discovered last year in West Germany by Bastiaan
Blonhert, a Dutch musicologist.
   In a letter to his father dated July 20, 1782, Mozart wrote that
he hoped to complete a wind arrangement of the opera quickly ``or
else someone will step in front of me and reap the profit.''
   Whether he actually completed the work is not known. However,
musicologist H.C. Robbins Landon said that a newspaper article
written in August 1782 advertises a wind band performance of the
work, noting that ``tickets are available from the lemonade seller
at the new market.''
   The copy found in West Germany is not in Mozart's handwriting.
Nor is it in the handwriting of any of the copyists Mozart was
known to employ.
   While more evidence is certainly in order, Landon said, ``I find
a great deal in the music itself that leads me to believe that this
is Mozart's work.''
   Whoever crafted the work, Landon noted, was ``certainly not a
hack.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880818-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0645EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-John     08-18 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-John,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elton John Sells Out Two Hollywood Bowl Shows In Record Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elton John, the bespectacled piano-playing
pop star known for his outlandish costumes and fiery performances,
sold out two shows at the Hollywood Bowl in 24 hours, a record for
the landmark venue, officials said.
   The single day sell-out for shows scheduled on Sept. 23-24 was
the fastest run on tickets for a multiple show at the 18,000-seat
arena, spokeswoman Sarah McMullen said Wednesday.
   It will be John's first appearance at the bowl, nestled in the
Hollywood Hills, since his ``Too Low For Zero'' tour in 1982. The
upcoming dates are part of his 15-city ``Reg Strikes Back'' U.S.
tour that kicks off in Miami on Sept. 9.
   The 41-year-old singer is known for his many hit recordings
during the 1970s and '80s, including `Your Song,'' ``Goodbye Yellow
Brick Road,'' ``Rocket Man,'' ``Island Girl,'' ``Pinball Wizard''
and ``I'm Still Standing.''
</TEXT>
