<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CorporalPunishment     08-18 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Corporal Punishment,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conference: `Time is Now' To End Corporal Punishment In Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition calling for an end to corporal
punishment in the nation's schools says the most difficult obstacle
may be the attitude of parents who practice it at home.
   ``A study several years back found that 90 percent of parents
use corporal punishment in their own homes. That tells us we've got
a lot of educating to do,'' Adrienne Haeuser of the National
Association of Social Workers said Wednesday as educators, lawyers
and doctors gathered for the first conference of its kind in a
decade.
   More than a million incidents of corporal punishment are
reported in the nation's public schools each year, ranging from
paddling to confining students in small spaces such as closets,
according to U.S. Department of Education figures.
   ``In large part, the parents don't quite understand the
consequences (of corporal punishment at home),'' Ms. Haeuser said.
``They learn from their parents, and they figure if they got hit,
it's OK to hit their own children.''
   Keynote speaker Bob Keeshan, known to millions of children as
TV's Captain Kangaroo, called corporal punishment a failed practice.
   ``It rates an `F' because it does not meet its stated purpose of
maintaining discipline, and because it treats the symptoms and not
the cause of the underlying unruly behavior,'' Keeshan said.
   ``With that behavior a child is crying out, `Help me, help me.'
And we answer with the compassion of the paddle.''
   The theme of the three-day conference, which brought together 23
prominent medical, legal and educational organizations, is ``The
Time is Now.'' Organizer Robert Fathman said the groups are banding
into a coalition to capitalize on a growing movement by state
legislatures to outlaw corporal punishment.
   Eleven states and a number of school districts, ranging in size
from Chicago's to that of Seaford, Del., which has a population of
5,250, have outlawed corporal punishment in schools since New
Jersey became the first state to do so in 1867.
   But, Fathman said, five states have passed measures banning the
practice since 1984, six state legislatures have similar bills
pending and another six will face the issue during their 1989
sessions.
   The purpose of this week's conference, Fathman said, is to
provide organizational skills and information to parents, educators
and other interested people so they can campaign to eliminate the
practice in schools.
   Fathman said black children, who represent 16 percent of the
country's school-age population, make up a disproportionate 32
percent of those punished, and that children ``in the Deep South
are 4,000 times more likely to be paddled than their counterparts
in the Northeast,'' where Connecticut is the only state without a
law barring the practice.
   In a joint statement preceding the opening of the conference,
the American Medical Association, the American Bar Association, the
American Academy of Pediatrics and the American Psychological
Association denounced corporal punishment and called on legislators
to ``enact laws accordingly.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
