<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Schools-Weapons     08-18 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Schools-Weapons,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hand-Held Metal Detectors To Be Used In Five Schools</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Worried by an increase in weapons found in city
schools, Schools Chancellor Richard Green has proposed buying
hand-held metal detectors and hiring new guards to make unannounced
checks in five high schools.
   The plan would cost $2.8 million, far less than the $9 million
estimate for an earlier plan calling for walk-through metal
detectors, Green said at a news conference Wednesday. The first
proposal was deemed too costly, he said.
   Green said more than 150 students were found carrying guns
during the past school year. The total number of weapons possession
incidents last year was 1,960, compared with 1,495 in the 1986-87
school year.
   If the plan is approved by the Board of Education, students who
carry weapons or assault staff will be transferred to one of five
Outreach Centers, currently used for counseling dropouts. The metal
detectors will also be used there.
   Students now can only be suspended for five days twice in a
school year, and then usually transferred to another school,
returned to their home school or occasionally placed in an
alternative program.
   ``It's going to go a long way in getting rid of guns and ending
assaults on teachers,'' said Sandra Feldman, president of the
teachers union.
   But Rob Levy, staff counsel to the New York Civil Liberties
Union, said the metal detector policy was wrong. ``Searches should
be based on individualized suspicion,'' he said.
</TEXT>
