<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Mandela     08-18 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mandela,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Botha Says Mandela May Not Have To Return To Prison From Hospital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DURBAN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha said today that
African National Congress leader Nelson Mandela may not have to
return to prison from the hospital where he is being treated for
tuberculosis.
   Botha said Mandela had been cooperating with the government and
he now expects ``positive results'' from his standing offer to free
the 70-year-old black leader in return for renunciation of violence.
   In his speech to the provincial National Party congress in
Natal, Botha did not explain what he meant by cooperation. However,
it was seen as a strong suggestion of a change in the way Mandela's
case is being viewed, possibly because he is being treated for
tuberculosis at Tygerberg Hospital in Cape Town.
   The outlawed African National Congress is the major guerrilla
group fighting the while-ruled government and apartheid, its policy
of racial segregation. Mandela has been in prison since 1962 and is
serving a life term for sabotage and conspiracy to overthrow the
government.
   ``The government, in a responsible way, will consider the matter
and if we get the cooperation we have so far got from Mr. Mandela,
I believe we will get positive results,'' Botha said.
   ``Personally, I don't think that at his age and condition it
would be wise for him to choose to go back to prison and I hope he
will make it possible for me to act in a humane way so that we can
have peace in South Africa.''
   Botha's speech followed a meeting with Justice Minister Kobie
Coetsee, who visited Mandela at the hospital on Wednesday.
   ``He appears to be comfortable and appears to have taken the
first steps towards recovery. He appears to be satisfied with his
treatment and surroundings,'' Coetsee said of Mandela.
   ``He looks as though he is almost his old self and he is already
enjoying jokes. I think it will be in his own interest to remain in
the medical care of the specialists who are attending him at the
moment.''
   Asked what cooperation Mandela had given, Information Minister
Stoffel said: ``For example, Mandela did not try to use the
occasion (of his hospitalization last week) as a propaganda stunt.''
   He said it was not Mandela, but his lawyer and friends, who
demanded outside medical attention and revealed the nature of his
illness.
   Stoffel Van der Merwe, the information minister, said the
government was not expecting Mandela to sign anything, or even
publicly disavow the guerrilla group's policy, but it expected that
he would not participate in or promote violent activities.
   Tom Lodge, a University of the Witwatersrand academic who is
South Africa's foremost expert on the congress, said in a radio
interview: ``I don't think Mandela will accept anything other than
unconditional release.'' But he said that ``if he is ill, it is
unlikely that he would be involved ... in violence.''
   Van der Merwe said last month that Mandela already had served
enough time for his crime and security was the the only reason he
was still in prison.
   The government ``would like to see old men like him go out of
jail,'' van der Merwe said today. ``It cannot do that if the result
will be lives lost in South Africa.''
   Mandela has rejected previous offers by Botha to free him if he
renounces violence, responding that the government must end
apartheid and legalize the African National Congress.
   In a major policy speech today, Botha said he was unwilling even
to discuss the possibility of a black majority government in South
Africa.
   ``We don't want to be a second Rhodesia, we don't want to be a
second Zaire. We are standing here in a firm way,'' he said to loud
applause from the crowd of about 500.
   Last year, the government unconditionally freed Govan Mbeki, 77,
an elderly African National Congress official who was imprisoned
for life at the same time as Mandela.
   Mbeki said he had not renounced violence or the congress. After
a few public appearances, the government banned him from addressing
audiences, giving newspaper interviews or leaving his home of Port
Elizabeth.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote
in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
