<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SexRuling     08-18 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sex Ruling,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legal Ruling Helps Problem of Dual Sexuality</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hermaphrodite who had undergone
extensive surgery to correct his condition has been declared a male
in an unusual court ruling, a move he hopes will end a lifetime of
sexual harassment.
   ``I've always known inside that I was male, but I wanted
something tangible,'' said Scott Brenatelli, 28, who spent one
month as a policewoman and was once sent to a female prison.
   Circuit Judge Nath Doughtie issued the ruling Tuesday, based on
medical evidence and testimony.
   According to records, Brenatelli was born with hermaphroditism,
a condition in which a person has both male and female reproductive
organs.
   He said he was taunted as a child and tormented as an adult
because of his birth defect. Because his gender was incorrectly
listed as female on his birth certificate, Brenatelli spent much of
his life as Linda Schaefer, an unpopular and unruly girl who
dressed in boy's clothing.
   ``Now maybe I can finally get my birth certificate and my life
straightened out,'' said Brenatelli, who has served prison time for
convictions of insurance fraud, grand theft and failing to appear
in court. He was released from prison in May and has lived near
Gainesville since then.
   Bernatelli was hired as a police officer in Cocoa in 1980 under
the name Linda Schaefer. He was fired a month later and sued the
department, claiming he was dismissed because officials learned he
was taking male hormones and planning to have corrective surgery.
   Police officials said he was fired because they learned he had
been arrested in Orlando on charges involving the improper transfer
of a car title. The lawsuit was settled out of court in 1983 for
$1,500.
   After several operations to correct his defect, Brenatelli
married as a male. The couple paid another man $2,500 to impregnate
the wife, and she bore a son, according to court records.
   Brenatelli said he hopes the court ruling will help him gain
joint custody of his son and correct past news accounts that refer
to him as a transsexual.
   He is now suing the Orange County Sheriff's Office in Orlando
for allegedly sending him to a female prison after his 1987
convictions. He was later transferred to Lawtey Correctional
Institution for men.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
