<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Leno     08-18 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Leno,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jay Leno Doesn't Want to Go Up Against Johnny Carson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Jay Leno says he has rejected
offers to become the host of late-night comedy talk shows on
television because he doesn't want to compete with Johnny Carson.
   Carson's network, NBC, recently made Leno the official vacation
replacement for Carson on ``The Tonight Show.''
   The comedian, appearing here this week, acknowledged his debt
and loyalty to NBC and ``The Tonight Show.'' ``It's kind of like
your first girl,'' he said. ``You usually remember that.''
   Mindful of Joan Rivers' ill-fated defection to the Fox Network
after years as Carson's backup, Leno said, ``I've already been
offered shows on other networks, and I've turned them down. I don't
want to go up against Johnny.''
   But he wouldn't mind sitting behind Carson's desk permanently
someday.
   ``Sure, I'd take the job if it were offered to me, but Johnny
isn't going anywhere. He likes doing it, and his ratings are
high,'' Leno said.
