<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Police-Robberies     08-18 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Police-Robberies,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officers Suspected in Robberies Return to Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two police officers accused in a spree of
robberies while off-duty were released after victims and witnesses
failed to identify them in a lineup, authorities said.
   About 14 victims and witnesses viewed the lineup, with none
picking out either officer, officials said Wednesday. All spoke to
The Detroit News and Detroit Free Press on condition of anonymity.
   During the spree, which took place late Monday and early
Tuesday, two gunmen dressed in police uniforms took part in at
least five street holdups.
   The officers were tied to the case when the patrol car they
drove Monday was reported missing while the robberies occurred
Tuesday morning. A driver's license belonging to one of the robbery
victims was found in the vehicle, officials said.
   Investigators say they are now considering other possibilities,
such as other officers committed the crimes, or Detroit police
reservists wearing officers' uniforms, or imposters using stolen or
phony uniforms.
   The two officers returned to duty Wednesday, officials said.
They will be confined to office work while the investigation
continues.
   No warrants have been issued in the case, said Wayne County
Prosecutor John O'Hair. Police Chief William Hart declined to
comment Wednesday.
   ``No one has been charged and, as far as I know, no one has been
suspended,'' said John Goldpaugh, lawyer for the Detroit Police
Officers Association.
</TEXT>
