<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BridgeError     08-18 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bridge Error,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Design Error Means Part Of New Minneapolis Bridge Must Come Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A design error will force workers to take
down and rebuild the center section of a partially completed $16
million bridge near downtown Minneapolis, the state Department of
Transportation has confirmed.
   The mistake will cost up to $200,000, take three to four weeks
to correct and force an overnight shutdown of interstate ramps
leading to Minnesota Highway 12, a department spokesman said.
   ``It's not that uncommon on a project this size, but correcting
it usually does not involve taking the steel down,'' said Al Pint,
state corridor manager for the I-394 project.
   The bridge will carry car pool, van and bus traffic between
I-394, downtown Minneapolis and I-94. Interstate 394, a freeway
running west from Minneapolis to Wayzata, is scheduled to be
completed in 1992. Construction began in 1984.
   A state survey crew discovered the design error Aug. 8 when it
conducted a required steel erection inspection.
   Pint said the state's design consultant, Edwards & Kelcey of
Edina, inadvertently included a rise in camber in a 30-foot section
of the bridge, which is more than a half-mile long. Bridge
specifications called for a lowered camber, or convex curve.
   Pint estimated that correcting the error could cost $100,000 to
$200,000, which the state might have to help pay because it
accepted the faulty design.
</TEXT>
