<HEAD>Video System Poses Shock Hazard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bell & Howell Co. is trying to contact
owners of its Showmate 2 Video Presentation system, which has been
recalled because a defective switch could pose a danger of
electrical shock, the Consumer Product Safety Commission reported
today.
   More than 3,000 of the units, model 6427, have been returned and
repaired, but several hundred remain in use, the agency said.
   No injuries have been reported, but Bell & Howell officials urge
owners of the machines to discontinue use until the defective
switches are replaced.
   The machines are a combination of seven-inch color television
and VHS format video recorder which were sold nationwide in 1985
and 1986 for about $500 each.
   Owners of the machines can contact Bell & Howell at
1-800-522-8969. Illinois residents should call 312-470-7656
collect. People needing more information can contact the Safety
Commission at 1-800-638-2772.
