<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0567 08-18 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0567,0531</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS item on White to CORRECT name to Kathrine sted
Katherine; PMs separates moved as a0415 for Zia and a0563 for
Roosevelt.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Mohammed Zia ul-Haq</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq, whose
11-year rule of Pakistan was the longest in that country's 41-year
history, died in a plane crash Wednesday at 64.
   The military transport in which Zia and 29 others, including
U.S. Ambassador Arnold L. Raphel, were flying exploded shortly
after taking off from Bahawalpur, 330 miles south of Islamabad.
   Zia overthrew Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto in a bloodless
coup July 5, 1977, and stamped Islamic law on his nation, including
practices such as public floggings. Bhutto was hanged in 1979.
   Under Zia, Pakistan was a strong ally of the United States,
particularly in support of the ``mujahadeen'' against the
Soviet-backed government in neighboring Afghanistan, following the
Soviet Union's 1979 military intervention in Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Arnold L. Raphel</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ambassador Arnold L. Raphel, one of the State
Department's most seasoned experts in the tumultuous southwest
Asian region, died in a plane crash Wednesday in Pakistan. He was
45.
   Raphel, the U.S. ambassador to Pakistan, was killed in a crash
that also claimed the life of Pakistani President Mohammed Zia
ul-Haq and 28 others.
   A 22-year veteran of the diplomatic corps, Raphel was appointed
ambassador to Pakistan in January 1987, having held senior
positions in the political-military affairs bureau and the Middle
East bureau of the State Department since 1967.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Kathrine K. White</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EMPORIA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kathrine K. White, editor of The Emporia
Gazette, died Wednesday. She was 85.
   Mrs. White became editor of the newspaper after the death in
1973 of her husband, William Lindsay White. His father, William
Allen White, was known as the ``Sage of Emporia'' and made the
Gazette into one of the best-known newspapers in the country.
   Mrs. White's son-in-law, Paul David Walker, is now the
publisher.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Franklin Delano Roosevelt Jr.</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Franklin Delano Roosevelt Jr., third
son of Franklin and Eleanor Roosevelt, died on Wednesday, his 74th
birthday.
   A Liberal-Democrat, Roosevelt entered politics in 1949, four
years after his father's death. He served three terms in Congress
for the 20th District before retiring in 1955.
   Roosevelt was a close friend of John F. Kennedy, campaigning for
him and serving as Kennedy's Undersecretary of Commerce. He was
also the first chairman of the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission under President Lyndon Johnson.
   Roosevelt, who served in the U.S. Navy during World War II, was
awarded the Navy Cross, Legion of Merit, a Purple Heart, a Navy
commendation medal and seven campaign ribbons for meritorious
service.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Bruno Mathsson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bruno Mathsson, a fifth-generation
carpenter who gained international fame as a creator of
Scandinavian-design furniture, died Wednesday in Varnamo, Sweden.
He was 81.
   Mathsson, breaking with traditional carved wood designs,
introduced functional chairs in the 1930s with burlap seats to fit
the body's shape.
   He became a teacher to generations of Swedes, and established a
fund to sponsor young designers.
</TEXT>
