<1ST_LINE>u p PM-CVN--Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0512 08-18 0838</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0512,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Ready With Thoughtful, Quiet And Personal Acceptance Speech</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Bush appearance in top 8 grafs, picking up in
5th graf pvs, Bush also</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, savoring victory after a
10-month quest for the Republican presidential nomination, said he
was ``upbeat and ready to go'' today, preparing an acceptance
speech billed as thoughtful, quiet and personal.
   Aides said Bush has been working on tonight's speech for weeks
and was expected to sandwich some last-minute practicing into a
full day of events at the Republican National Convention.
   Press secretary Sheila Tate characterized the speech as
``thoughtful, quiet, personal.''
   During the campaign, Bush said today at a breakfast for Texas
delegates, he will spell out differences between his views and
those of Democratic rival Michael Dukakis _ ``differences I think
are so fundamental that the American people will find them hard to
believe.''
   ``But that's only half the equation, putting his record in
shape,'' Bush said. ``The other half is spelling out with clarity
what I want to do as president of the United States.
   ``And yes I've been a loyal vice president but now the gears
shift tonight and I'm going to be the nominee of this party for
president and I'm going to set the agenda.''
   He told the cheering delegates, ``I'm upbeat and ready to go.''
   Bush had been expected to appear at the breakfast with his new
running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana, but he said Quayle was
elsewhere in the hotel, working on his own acceptance speech.
   Bush also planned to attend a rally for his wife, Barbara, and
then a $1,000-per-plate luncheon at the Convention Center expected
to raise $4 million for the Republican National Committee.
   The vice president watched the tally that handed him the
nomination on television in his hotel suite with Barbara and other
family members, including six of his 10 grandchildren.
   ``It is a special moment. The conclusion was foregone, but it's
special,'' Bush told reporters as his oldest son, George W. Bush, a
Texas delegate, announced the vote that clinched the nomination.
   All five of Bush's adult children are delegates to the
convention and Wednesday night's session _ looking at times like a
Bush family production _ included a seconding speech in Spanish
from his Mexican-born daughter-in-law, Columba.
   Asked about his acceptance speech, Bush said, ``All ready. Feel
comfortable about it. Ready to go.''
   It will be Bush's first appearance before the convention,
although he spent about 30 minutes Wednesday morning testing the
equipment on the podium while the Superdome convention hall still
was empty.
   ``I'd like to do it without my specs,'' Bush said, claiming he
planned to remove the wire-rimmed glasses he usually wears for
speaking engagements as he reads from the TelePrompTer on the
podium.
   ``We'll do all right. I'll do OK,'' Bush said of the speech.
   Aides appeared intent on lowering expectations for what could be
the most important speech of his life.
   ``We're a little nervous about the TelePrompTer. He's not used
to it,'' said media adviser Roger Ailes.
   Added press secretary Tate: ``He says he's not William Jennings
Bryan,'' the fiery late 19th century orator and three-time
presidential candidate.
   However, she said, ``he will give a good speech. The (Michael)
Dukakis speech lacked any specifics. George Bush feels strongly
that he needs to lay out where he will lead.''
   Speechwriter Peggy Noonan, who has been working on the speech
with Bush since mid-July, said that Bush was continuing to
fine-tune the speech _ which so far has been through at least four
drafts.
   Bush aides said Wednesday that after the convention, Bush and
Quayle would set out together on a campaign trip through Indiana,
Ohio and Illinois _ the latter two states key industrial
battlegrounds in the fall election. Bush will go on alone for
campaign stops in the Pacific Northwest, followed by a mid-week
appearance with President Reagan in southern California.
   At a news conference with Quayle on Wednesday, Bush said they
were ``going to tell the truth, and it's going to seem like you've
engaged a couple of pit bulls. ... We will be telling the truth
about where we want to lead this country, spelling out my
priorities.''
   Meanwhile, the Bush campaign disclosed the complete list of 12
also-rans for the No. 2 spot on the ticket.
   They included Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas and his wife, former
Transportation Secretary Elizabeth Dole; New Hampshire Gov. John
Sununu, California Gov. George Deukmejian, South Carolina Gov.
Carroll Campbell, Gov. Jim Thompson of Illinois, Sens. John
Danforth of Missouri, Alan Simpson of Wyoming and Pete Domenici of
New Mexico, Rep. Jack Kemp of New York, and Attorney General
Richard Thornburgh.
   Bush called those 11 on Tuesday before talking with Quayle, Bush
chief of staff Craig Fuller told a group of reporters.
   The 12th person on Bush's list, Sen. Nancy Kassebaum of Kansas,
was not called because she had removed herself from contention,
Fuller said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
