<HEAD>Marilyn Quayle Upset By `Low Blows'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with interview, picks up 6th graf pvs, Her
father</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marilyn Quayle, the wife of Indiana Sen. Dan
Quayle, today defended her husband's conduct and said she gets
upset when ``people hit the low blows'' at him.
   ``Any wife would get upset when someone they love is being
attacked in a way that you feel is very unfairly,'' Mrs. Quayle
said on CBS-TV.
   Mrs. Quayle, a 38-year-old attorney and the mother of three
children, said there was nothing unusual about her husband's
decision to join the National Guard during the Vietnam War. ``He
wasn't a draft dodger,'' she said.
   She also dismissed ting weekend that her husband
and two other congressmen spent in Florida at a condominium where
lobbyist Paula Parkinson stayedalk about a golf eight years ago.
   ``Any one who know Dan Quayle knows that when he gets near a
golf course that is all he thinks about,'' she said. ``When he's
home with me, that is something else, but on a golf course, it is
golf.''
   While she expected her husband would be put under the microscope
after George Bush tapped him as his running mate on the GOP
presidential ticket, Mrs. Quayle said she doesn't like some of the
questions that have been asked.
   ``I don't have anybody.
   She later attended Indiana University's law school in
Indianapolis and worked for the state attorney general's office and
judicial disciplinary commission.
   In 1972, fellow law student William Neale introduced her to Dan
Quayle, also a law student. They were married 10 weeks later in
November 1972.
   Neale remains a close friend of the Quayles.
   ``The thing I like so much about the two of them is they haven't
lost their perspective,'' said Neale. ``They're still the kind of
people you would like to have as your neighbors.''
   After law school, the Quayles moved to Dan's hometown of
Huntington where they opened a law practice. James Tucker said
Marilyn did most of the legal work because her husband also was
working as associate publisher of the Huntington Herald-Press,
owned by his father, James C. Quayle.
   The couple's first child, Tucker, was born in 1974. Their two
other children, 12-year-old Benjamin and 9-year-old Corinne, were
born after Quayle launched his political career in 1976.
   The family now lives in McLean, Va., outside Washington. Mrs.
Quayle has suspended her legal career to rear the children just as
her mother interrupted her professional career to rear a family,
James Tucker said.
   During the Quayles' years in politics, Mrs. Quayle has been an
active campaigner for her husband. Often, she and her sons will
make a series of appearances at fairs and parades while Quayle and
his daughter campaign at other events.
   Mrs. Quayle said her family has not yet adjusted to the national
attention they are receiving.
</TEXT>
