<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 1106EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica     08-18 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says No Majority Rule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DURBAN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha vowed today to
oppose black majority rule as long as he is in power and said 80
percent of white voters would support segregated residential areas
in a referendum.
   In a policy speech at the governing National Party's congress in
Natal province, Botha said he was prepared to hold a referendum
among whites to determine whether they wished to retain segregated
residential areas. He said 80 percent would vote in favor.
   ``Equally, I have reason to believe that if such a referendum is
held among the Indian and colored (mixed-race) communities, some 70
percent will favor the protection of their own residential areas,''
Botha said. ``I invite the coloreds and the Indians to prove the
opposite.''
   When Parliament reconvenes next week, it is expected to take up
three new bills relating to segregation. They would allow the first
legal multiracial areas, but at the same time strengthen
enforcement of existing apartheid laws and make it easier for
authorities to evict blacks from squatter camps and whites-only
areas.
   Parliament has chambers for whites, Indians and people of mixed
race. The leader of the mixed-race chamber, Alan Hendrickse, says
his Labor Party will oppose the new apartheid laws.
   The 26 million black majority has no representation in
Parliament.
   ``I'm not even considering to discuss the possibility of black
majority government in South Africa,'' Botha told the party
congress. ``That won't happen under my leadership.''
   He said if black leaders have suggestions for increasing their
share of power in their own communities or in regional governments,
``they should come forward with practical proposals.''
   Most black leaders say they are unwilling to have discussions
with the government on a new constitution until all blacks,
including members of banned groups, are free to choose whether they
would participate. Most say they are not interested in negotiating
reforms which will leave ultimate power in the hands of the white
minority.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's black majority has no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
