<HEAD>Man Shot To Death In Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with parcel bomb. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two masked gunmen shot and
killed a Roman Catholic workman today in a house in north Belfast,
police said, and authorities defused a parcel bomb sent to a
leading Protestant politician.
   A police spokesman said the gunmen walked into a house in
Cliftonville Road and opened fire at close range, striking the
workman in the head and chest.
   The victim's identity was not immediately released, but he was
in his 20s and lived in County Tyrone in the center of the British
province, said the spokesman, speaking on condition he was not
identified.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility.
   On Monday, two gunmen entered a grocery store on the Shankill
Road, a Protestant enclave in west Belfast, and shot and fatally
wounded its 44-year-old owner, Frederick Otley.
   The Irish Revolutionary Brigade, a group previously unheard of
in Northern Ireland, claimed responsibility for that killing.
   Elsewhere, police said a parcel bomb was delivered today to the
home of a leading Protestant politician, Ken Maginnis, in
Dungannon, 40 miles west of Belfast, but was defused by British
army bomb disposal experts.
   Maginnis, the Official Unionist Party's security spokesman,
became suspicious of the cigar-box-sized parcel and called police
instead of opening it, the spokesman said. The parcel contained an
unspecified amount of explosives, he said.
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army has been fighting to drive
the British from the predominantly Protestant province and unite it
with the overwhelmingly Catholic Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
