<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign Abroad,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campaign Abroad: Comment on the Republican Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is some of what newspapers abroad had to say this week on
Republican presidential nominee George Bush's choice of Sen. Dan
Quayle as his running mate in the November presidential election:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ITALY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Corriere della Sera of Milan (moderate): ``(Quayle) has
satisfied a strong and restless right wing with a man who has the
energy of a 40-year-old and the ideas of an 80-year-old.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Il Messaggero of Rome (moderate): ``(Quayle) adds a touch of
youthful energy to Bush's fortunes in the Midwest ... (he is)
``strikingly telegenic and his impetuous oratory is accompanied by
wide and vigorous gestures which have earned him many admirers, but
also ironic smiles from those who contest his inexperience and his
ambition.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FRANCE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Le Monde (liberal) _ ``In his appearances on television, Sen.
Quayle showed that he knows very well how to use his blue eyes and
his natural ease to impose his presence.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BRITAIN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The Guardian (liberal) _ ``The younger one, (Michael) Dukakis,
went for the old man, (Sen.) Lloyd Bentsen, 67, while the older
one, Bush, has gone for the boy ...
   ``Dan Quayle's right-wing politics seem likely to count for more
than his youth on the campaign trail. Bentsen is there to do that
for Dukakis, but that makes more sense. George Bush clearly
assesses the mood of America as still Reaganite, seeking
continuity, not movement towards the center.
   ``He feels his best hope of `making it one more for the Gipper'
is to offer more of the same, but with added youthful good looks.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Daily Telegraph (Conservative): ``By passing over better
known and more powerful Republican figures and choosing a young,
brash 41-year-old senator of limited experience as his election
partner, George Bush has taken a gamble.
   ``Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, Dukakis's running mate and 26 years older
than Quayle, has said drily that he looks forward to comparing
their respective records of accomplishment. Well he may ...
   ``In reality the Reagan years have been distinguished not so
much by their conservatism as by the force of new ideas. Mr. Bush
has not so far shown himself to be gifted in this respect, and it
is a main weakness. It is very hard indeed to see this weakness
being redeemed by the amiable but light-headed senator from
Indiana.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Financial Times (independent): ``The Midwest is going to be
decisive and Mr. Quayle is a proven local vote getter... His youth
and good looks might help close Mr. Bush's large gender gap with
women, though his opposition to abortion will not, nor will the
party platform, if it is promoted seriously.
   ``It is possible that Mr. Bush has come up with a clever choice,
but it is a gamble and one wide open to counterattack. Mr. Quayle's
public record is very thin ... and it is impossible to say with any
confidence that he is qualified to be the proverbial heartbeat away
from the presidency, let alone to sharpen the blurred image Mr.
Bush himself conveys to the public at large.''
</TEXT>
