<DOCNO> AP880818-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 1126EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalCartoons 1stLd-Writethru a0578 08-18 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Cartoons, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0578,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Originality of Ohio GOP Cartoons Questioned</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `The similarities ...' to CORRECT spelling of
MacNelly.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cartoonist hired by the Ohio Republican
Party to lampoon Democrats says any similarity between his cartoons
and those published by Pulitzer Prize-winning cartoonist Jeff
MacNelly is strictly coincidental.
   But MacNelly, who draws for the Chicago Tribune, said he might
turn the matter over to an attorney.
   ``It concerns me enough that I think I'm going to call the
Tribune lawyer and have them call the Ohio Republican Party and see
what the deal is,'' MacNelly told the Dayton Daily News.
   The Daily News reported today that four cartoons drawn by Ed
Wilson for the Ohio GOP are virtually the same as the MacNelly
drawings published four years ago, except that the political
figures have been changed. In two others, the artwork is strikingly
similar but the subject matter is different, the newspaper said.
   The similarities were found by Daily News staff artist Randy
Palmer, who saw some of Wilson's cartoons last weekend and compared
them with panels he saw in a book of MacNelly's cartoons, the
newspaper said.
   Wilson, who is in New Orleans for the Republican National
Convention, expressed disbelief when told of the similarities and
said they are coincidental.
   ``Oh, I don't think that's (plagiarism) the case,'' Wilson told
the Daily News. ``Why would I do that?''
   MacNelly has not seen Wilson's cartoons, but they were described
to him by an editor of the Tribune who received copies of the
drawings from the Daily News.
   One of MacNelly's cartoons shows President Jimmy Carter standing
in a trash can while he speaks at a lectern. An adviser is saying,
``No. No. No. Stand ON your record, not IN it. Now you've got it
all over your suit.''
   Wilson's cartoon features Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis,
the Democratic presidential nominee, also standing in a trash can
behind a lectern. A voice from the auditorium is saying, ``No. No.
No. Stand ON your record. Not IN it.''
   MacNelly's cartoons are syndicated by the Tribune Syndicate Co.
and were published in his 1984 book ``Directions.''
   Wilson, who also worked for Ohio GOP in the late 1970s, said he
has seen MacNelly's work but not the cartoons in the book.
   ``I didn't even know he (MacNelly) had a book out, to be honest
with you,'' Wilson said.
   Wilson, 41, who has been drawing cartoons for 10 years and was
hired by the Ohio GOP six weeks ago, has drawn about 30 cartoons
for the Republicans. The cartoons have been attached to press
releases and, on at least two occasions, handed out to the public.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
