<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0582 08-18 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0582,700</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<HEAD>Dukakis In Miami To Address Greeks; Chides `Desperate' Republicans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis today congratulated George Bush for
winning the Republican presidential nomination but then quickly
criticized his fall rival as a leading player in the Reagan
administration's ``non-existent'' war on drugs.
   The Democratic presidential nominee refused to answer directly
when asked whether he thought Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle, Bush's
running mate, should have served in Vietnam instead of joining the
National Guard.
   ``For them as for us this has been a long marathon,'' Dukakis
said in congratulating Bush and his wife, Barbara. ``Now we have
the official nominees of both parties. The fat is in the fire; the
campaign lies ahead.''
   Dukakis then said that he was eager to debate Bush and that one
of the topics should be the federal government's anti-drug efforts.
   He criticized a White House order reportedly issued Wednesday
that told federal agencies not to cooperate with a congressional
investigation into why suspicions that Panama's Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega was involved in drug trafficking were not passed on to
Congress and other federal agencies.
   Dukakis accused the Reagan administration of ``stonewalling''
the investigation.
   ``I think the White House does not want to cooperate ... because
they are embarrassed by this. They should be embarrassed by this,''
Dukakis said.
   He promised tough drug-law enforcement and drug education in
early elementary school grades and said Reagan's anti-drug effort
has failed because there is no drug czar directly accountable to
the president and that an administration committee set up to
coordinate anti-drug programs has done little constructive work.
   ``The vice president is on the committee. He doesn't show up at
meetings,'' Dukakis said. ``This war against drugs is
non-existent.''
   Dukakis has indirectly criticized the 41-year-old Quayle by
listing the accomplishments of his running mate, Texas Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen. But Dukakis chose his words carefully today when asked at
a morning news conference about reports Quayle may have used family
influence to get into the National Guard.
   ``I can only speak for myself,'' Dukakis said. ``I served my
country. I did so proudly.'' Dukakis was an Army private in Korea.
   Dukakis told a friendly audience of Greek-Americans that, if
elected, he would ``restore pride and competence and respect for
the law.
   He attributed GOP convention attacks on him to a ``pretty
desperate Republican Party.''
   ``I don't think the American people are interested in this kind
of thing,'' the Massachusetts governor said. ``I think they want a
president who is going to be strong and optimistic and confident
about this country. That's the kind of person I am.''
   Then, as he did earlier Wednesday in Minnesota, Dukakis touted
the 18-year Senate experience of his running mate, Texas Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen, and implied Quayle was not ready to be the nation's No. 2
leader.
   ``Nobody has questioned whether Lloyd Bentsen is qualified for
the job or ready to step into the presidency if that became
necessary,'' Dukakis said.
   He used that tack repeatedly to promote Bentsen over Quayle
while Dukakis aides were more direct in characterizing Quayle as
too inexperienced for the vice presidency.
   Today, Dukakis delivered his standard stump speech to a
convention of Greek-Americans, invoking the ancient Athenian oath
of public service he frequently adds to his speeches and promising
if elected to strengthen NATO and work for peace in Cypress.
   Dukakis, as he often does before Greek-American audiences,
devoted a significant portion of his speech to the issue of
government ethics.
   ``Respect for the law is the most basic, the most conservative
and the most important principle of our democratic society,''
Dukakis said. ``And it's why I want to restore pride and competence
and respect for the law to the highest office in the land.''
   Dukakis was heading from Miami to Alabama, where he was to tour
the Marshall Space Center in Huntsville and then a Baptist church
in Birmingham. It is unusual for the nominee of one party to
campaign during the other party's convention, but Bush broke
tradition by campaigning during the final two days of the
Democratic convention.
</TEXT>
