<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Brazil-Blackout     08-18 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brazil-Blackout,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Girl Climbs Electric Pylon, Blacks Out Brazilian City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old girl who climbed an
electric pylon caused a blackout for more than an hour in one of
Brazil's largest cities, police said today.
   The blackout Tuesday night hit the entire metropolitan area of
Porto Alegre, a city of 1.1 million people 960 miles southwest of
Rio de Janeiro, police Inspector Laureci Nunes said by telephone.
   Nunes said Jenicia Henrique da Silva, 12, was running away from
a group of boys who threatened to rape her when she climbed a
high-tension pylon near her house in Cachoeirinha, an industrial
suburb of Porto Alegre.
   The girl climbed to the top of the 130-foot-tall tower and hung
on to one of the wires carrying 230,000 volts, Nunes said.
   ``She grabbed the negative wire. If she had closed the circuit
she would have caused incalculable damage and turned into a
cinder,'' he said.
   The government electric company ordered power shut off while
firemen persuaded her to climb down, Nunes said.
   The blackout lasted from 7 p.m. until nearly 8:30 p.m. and
caused tremendous confusion throught greater Porto Alegre, the
police inspector said.
   ``People were trapped in elevators, traffic was tied up,
hospitals were operating on one-third power, and steel mills
suffered fantastic losses,'' he said. Nunes said it was the third
time the girl had climbed an electric pylon and that she was sent
to a juvenile hall.
</TEXT>
