<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Pakistan, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0564,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Reported Killed In Unrest Following Zia's Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Pakistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with officials saying three
killed, nine injured, army troops patrolling three towns, other
details. Pickup 7th graf pvs, ``The government...'' TRIMS to
tighten.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces today killed three
people and wounded at least nine when they opened fire on Moslem
crowds who defied a curfew imposed after the death of Pakistan's
president, officials said.
   Army troops also patrolled the streets of three Indian border
towns to control Moslem violence caused by the death of Mohammed
Zia ul-Haq, who led Pakistan _ India's main adversary _ for 11
years.
   Moslems are a minority in mostly Hindu India. Pakistan is a
Moslem-dominated state where Zia had declared the superiority of
Islamic law.
   The two nations have fought three wars since both gained
independence from Britain in 1947. Nevertheless, India's government
declared three days of mourning as a show of respect for Zia.
   At a special meeting in New Delhi, Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi
and his Cabinet observed a minute's silence in memory of Zia, who
died in a fiery plane crash Wednesday in eastern Pakistan.
   In Srinagar, the summer capital of Jammu and Kashmir state,
authorities imposed an indefinite curfew when Moslem crowds tried
to set fire to two bridges after Zia's death was announced
Wednesday night.
   Police were ordered to shoot at violators.
   A pro-Pakistani crowd defied the curfew and tried to set fire to
Hindu shops, said District Commissioner Shafi Pandit, a senior
civil administrator in the state. Police fatally shot three people
and wounded nine, he said.
   Troops also were sent to the nearby towns of Baramulla and
Anantnag after rampaging crowds tried to set fire to Hindu homes,
shops and temples, Pandit said.
   Police and unruly mobs also battled in the city of Tankipora,
and several were reported injured, according to news reports.
   Security forces in many towns in Gujarat, another state along
the India-Pakistan border, also were placed on alert.
   In New Delhi, the federal capital, police stepped up security in
Moslem-dominated Old Delhi and around embassies. Riots between the
Moslems and Hindus often break out in the congested lanes in Old
Delhi that surround Jama Masjid, Asia's largest mosque.
</TEXT>
