<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 1203EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-ArmsTalks     08-18 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Arms Talks,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiator Urges U.S. Moves On Sea-Launched Missiles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's chief arms negotiator today
accused the United States of refusing to discuss ways to monitor
long-range, sea-launched cruise missiles, a main issue at strategic
arms talks.
   The envoy, Alexei Obukhov, said ``necessary prerequisites'' have
been reached for completing a draft treaty halving both sides'
strategic nuclear arsenals, but he again linked progress to limits
on the sea-launched missiles.
   A U.S. official termed the Soviet proposals ``quite
unrealistic'' and Obukhov's account misleading. ``Neither side has
come up with adequate procedures for verifying this class of
weapons,'' said the official.
   He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Both sides still disagree over U.S. plans for a space-based
missile defense system in the latest round in the strategic arms
limitation talks, which began July 12, Obukhov told reporters.
   Washington wants to keep the sea-launched missiles outside the
strategic arms treaty limits, saying it is too hard to guard
against cheating.
   But Obukhov said the verification issue is ``quite solvable''
and added, ``This channel for continuation of the race in strategic
offensive arms must also be reliably blocked.''
   He said the Soviets have proposed several ways to monitor the
missiles, including inspections of ships and production sites.
   ``We wait for the American side to participate in a businesslike
discussion of these proposals,'' he said. ``As of now, we still
haven't had this discussion because of the unwillingness of the
American side.
   ``Tempo is important. We shouldn't lose the high pace of the
talks,'' he said. ``Simply declaring one's readiness to work
constructively is not enough.''
   Obukhov reiterated the Soviet position that a new commitment by
both sides to the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty must be part
of a strategic arms treaty.
   Moscow says the planned U.S. space-based missile defense, the
Strategic Defense Initiative, violates the ABM treaty. The Reagan
Administration has a more lenient view of the initiative, popularly
known as ``Star Wars.''
   Obukhov said Soviet officials will emphasize Moscow's rejection
of that ``broad'' ABM interpretation when the two sides meet for a
regular review of the pact in Geneva starting on Wednesday.
   The superpower arms negotiations began in March 1985. Both sides
agree that the strategic arms treaty should reduce each country's
long-range nuclear arsenal by half over seven years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
