<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 1230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Uganda-Diplomats     08-18 0151</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Uganda-Diplomats,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Uganda Recalls 19 Commercial Attaches For Lack Of Funds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is recalling all but four
commercial attaches in its 23 diplomatic missions for lack of
funds, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs said Thursday.
   ``Heads of missions have been instructed to recruit account
clerks locally,'' said Ernest Rusita, the ministry's permanent
secretary. The change will cut costs by eliminating the travel,
housing, education and medical expenses for the attaches and their
families.
   Rusita declined to say how much the government spends on the
current 23 commercial attaches and their 96 dependants.
   He said commercial attaches will remain in New York, London,
Rome and Nairobi because those missions generate enough revenue to
cover the costs.
   New Vision, the government-owned newspaper, said the staff
reductions stemmed from a 30 percent budget cut at Uganda's foreign
missions.
   The returning attaches will be given new jobs in Uganda.
</TEXT>
