<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--China-Illiteracy     08-18 0143</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--China-Illiteracy,0146</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Has 884 Million Illiterates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world has 884 million people over the age of
15 who can't read or write, with one out of every four living in
China, according to a United Nations report.
   The communist government has made significant progress in
teaching Chinese to read, reducing illiteracy from about 80 percent
in 1949 to 20 percent of its 1 billion people today. It seeks to
teach the rest to read within five years, but there is resistance
in rural areas where many still find little use for schooling,
particularly for girls.
   Figures released in 1985 showed that more than 10 percent of the
Communist Party's then-40 million members couldn't read.
   The report of the United Nations Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization, was delivered at a regional meeting in the
northeast China city of Harbin.
</TEXT>
