<DOCNO> AP880818-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 1346EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan-Reaction     08-18 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Reaction,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Mourns Death Of Pakistani President</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pakistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Islamic nations on Thursday mourned the death of Pakistan
President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq, and world leaders called for
stability in the nation he led for 11 years.
   Western allies praised his strong support for guerrillas
fighting the Soviet-backed government in Afghanistan.
   Even India, Pakistan's longtime adversary, expressed its grief
and declared a three-day mourning period. Moslems demonstrated in
Indian states along the Pakistani border after his death was
announced, resulting in fatal clashes with security forces.
   Zia, U.S. Ambassador Arnold Raphel and 28 others were killed
Wednesday when Zia's military transport plane crashed in
southeastern Pakistan. Investigators have not determined its cause,
and caretaker President Ghulam Ishaq Khan ordered a state of
emergency.
   China, an ally of Pakistan, expressed shock over the
``tremendous loss,'' the official Xinhua News Agency reported.
Chinese Premier Li Peng and President Yang Shangkunremi said they
``sincerely hope that the Pakistan government and people ... will
remain united and maintain stability and continue to make concerted
efforts for the preservation of peace and the development of the
economy.''
   The Soviet Union also sent condolences and said it hoped for
improved relations with Pakistan. The two countries were on
opposite sides of the Afghan conflict, and both joined the United
States and Afghanistan in signing agreements in Geneva calling for
the withdrawal of more than 100,000 Soviet troops from Afghanistan.
   Afghan President Najib expressed condolences to Ishaq Khan but
did not mention Zia by name, Radio Kabul said. Najib said he hoped
the new president will end the ``violence in (the) relationship''
between the south Asian neighbors.
   Hungary, however, said Zia had obstructed peace in Afghanistan.
   The United States, one of Pakistan's strongest supporters,
reaffirmed its backing for the country. ``At this moment of extreme
trial, I want to reiterate our commitment to Pakistan and our full
support for the acting president and his government,'' said State
Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley.
   Islamic nations mourned Zia, a devout Moslem who earlier this
year put the country under Islamic law.
   Iranian President Ali Khamenei called Zia a ``competent leader
and a good friend'' and expressed confidence that ``the strong will
of the Pakistani people will fill the vacuum created by (Zia's)
death,'' according to Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency.
   Individual cables expressing ``deep grief and sorrow'' were sent
by Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, Sultan Qaboos of Oman and
President Ali Khamenei of Iran.
   The United Arab Emirates, Bahrain, Qatar and Kuwait also called
for official mourning periods, with flags throughout the region
lowered to half- staff. Other nations with periods of mourning
included Nepal and Bangladesh, which was created in a 1971 civil
war that split Pakistan.
   In Britain, mourners visited the home of Zia's brother, Mohammad
Inam ul-Haq, a physician who lives near Manchester. His son said
the family was ``devastated.''
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher praised Zia's support for the
Afghan guerrillas. British newspapers warned of instability in
Pakistan.
   ``It is a measure of President Zia's shrewdness as a political
operator that he started by being underestimated and ended by being
overestimated. A truer measure of his stature is that his sudden
death leaves Pakistan in a mess,'' The Independent said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
