<HEAD>Paula Parkinson Says She Never Had Affair With Quayle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paula Parkinson, the woman who held center
stage in the sex-and-influence scandal that briefly touched Dan
Quayle, says she never had an affair with the senator and is tired
of talking about it.
   ``She didn't sleep with Quayle,'' said society columnist Rudy
Maxa, Mrs. Parkinson's longtime confidant. He is now acting as an
informal spokesman for Mrs. Parkinson, who once worked as a Capitol
Hill lobbyist for an insurance industry group.
   Quayle, tapped by George Bush for the No. 2 spot on the
Republican ticket, was one of three congressmen who shared a
cottage with Mrs. Parkinson during a January 1980 golfing vacation
in Atlantis, Fla. Quayle has said he did not have an affair with
her.
   ``That has been covered and there is nothing to it,'' Quayle
told a news conference Wednesday at the Republican convention in
New Orleans.
   Maxa said Mrs. Parkinson ``has no particular feelings one way or
another'' about the Quayle candidacy.
   She also was pictured in a November 1980 Playboy article on the
Women of Washington wearing only a garter belt and a sash across
her midriff. She later claimed she had a videotape of herself
having sex with an unidentified member of Congress.
   In 1981, the Justice Department investigated Mrs. Parkinson's
activities but uncovered no criminal activities.
   Since the incident, Mrs. Parkinson has divorced her first
husband. She remarried several months ago and now lives in a small
town near her native Dallas, Maxa said in a telephone interview.
   He said she will not reveal her new married name or speak with
reporters.
   As for interviews, he said, `She has, for the longest time, been
tired of the press.'' But he said she might be willing to tell her
story if she is paid.
</TEXT>
