<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Houstonin1992     08-18 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Houston in 1992,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Houston Already Campaigning _ For Next Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even before the Republican National
Convention ended Thursday, Houston began campaigning to persuade
GOP officials to hold their next quadrennial gathering in Texas'
largest city.
   Donald Ward of the Houston Convention and Visitors Bureau was
making the rounds this week distributing red, white and blue
stickers that read ``Houston '92 Convention'' and talking with
various Republican groups.
   ``I think Houston will host one of the national political
conventions in 1992, I really do,'' said Ward, who made a similar
recruiting trip to Atlanta for last month's Democratic convention.
   Ward said Houston has one big thing going for it: No matter who
wins the November election, a Houston resident will be at the White
House.
   Republican presidential nominee George Bush calls Houston home,
even if his current address is a hotel room. And Democratic vice
presidential candidate Lloyd Bentsen's residence is a Houston
condominium.
   Surely the hometown factor gives Houston a leg up, Ward said.
   ``We are in a very unique position. Either way it goes, the
president or the vice president will be from Houston,'' he said.
   Houston made a determined pitch to win this year's Democratic
convention, although it was passed over for Atlanta by Democratic
National Committee Chairman Paul Kirk.
   Ward said the city has several advantages to offer in trying to
lure a convention.
   First, the new George R. Brown Convention Center is massive,
with 43 permanent meeting rooms and enough temporary rooms to give
each state delegation its own, he said. Both state party
conventions were held there this year, with the Democrats sending
some 10,000 delegates and alternates.
   In addition, Ward said Houston has more than enough hotel space,
so no delegate would be more than 30 minutes from the hall.
</TEXT>
