<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Pakistan-USHelp     08-18 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan-US Help,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Pakistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>2 Teams Sent to Aid Pakistani Crash Investigators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has ordered two teams of
specialists to Pakistan to assist authorities investigating the
cause of a plane crash that killed the country's president and the
U.S. ambassador, the Pentagon said today.
   Dan Howard, the Defense Department's chief spokesman, said one
team of eight accident investigators had already left the United
States and will arrive in Pakistan on Friday.
   That team includes military and civilian experts and will help
search for the cause of Wednesday's crash.
   ``We expect them to be there for about two weeks,'' Howard said.
   The second team will include six U.S. military forensic
specialists who will assist the Pakistanis in identifying the
victims of the crash. That team is being sent from West Germany,
Howard said.
   The Pentagon spokesman said he was aware of reports speculating
that the plane crash was not an accident, but had seen nothing to
indicate sabotage or a military attack.
   ``My answer to all these questions is we just don't know,'' he
said. ``That's why we offered an investigating team. I don't think
I can offer any useful commentary on the causes of the crash until
they've conducted their investigation.''
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said, meanwhile,
that the declaration of a state of emergency in Pakistan had not
interfered with civil liberties and that the situation in the
country was calm.
   She praised a speech Wednesday night by Acting President Ghulam
Ishaq Khan reafirming the tenets of Pakistan's foreign policy and
``its continuing steps toward democracy'' along with a decision to
proceed with elections scheduled for mid-November.
</TEXT>
