<DOCNO> AP880818-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 1435EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-CVN--Quayle-Commander     08-18 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Quayle-Commander,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Questioned Commander About Possibility of Active Duty,
Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential candidate Dan
Quayle questioned a former Indiana National Guard commander about
the service and whether the Guard would be called to active duty in
the Vietnam War, the Indianapolis News reported today.
   Retired Maj. Gen. Wendell C. Phillippi _ who was managing editor
of The News and worked for Quayle's grandfather, Eugene C. Pulliam
_ told the newspaper that the Indiana senator questioned him about
aspects of the guard.
   Phillippi said he does not recall details of conversations that
took place surrounding Quayle's enlistment in the Guard _ a move
some observers have criticized as an attempt to avoid combat in
Vietnam.
   ``I imagine I was talking to Danny one day,'' Phillippi said.
``He was a newspaperman, you know. We got to conventions together.
I'd known him and his parents and his wife's parents for many, many
years.''
   ``He wondered if it was subject to call,'' Phillippi said in a
telephone interview with the newspaper.
   Phillippi, who retired from The News in 1984, said he called on
his ``multitude'' of friends within the guard when Quayle applied
in 1969 _ even though he had relinquished his command five years
earlier.
   Later, when personnel from the adjutant general's office sought
his advice, Phillippi suggested that Quayle should be given
consideration.
   ``I was asked about Dan Quayle's abilities and capabilities, and
I recommended him very highly for acceptance in the National Guard
after I left the National Guard _ as I did with many other men,''
Phillippi told the newspaper. ``That's about all I know about it.''
   Phillippi said he never talked to Pulliam about his grandson's
military service, but the topic did arise in conversations with
Eugene S. Pulliam, the son of Eugene C. Pulliam and Quayle's uncle.
The younger Pulliam was then assistant publisher of The News and
The Star; he now serves as publisher of The News and The Star.
   ``Lord, I talked with Gene every day,'' Phillippi said. ``We
discussed many people (interested in guard duty). If anyone was
interested, they were sent to me. Obviously, we were interested in
recruiting the best people _ and (Quayle) was one of them.''
   Eugene S. Pulliam said he does not remember any such
conversation.
   ``Well, I don't have any recollection at all of talking to
Wendell about that,'' Pulliam said. ``I know he was very active in
the guard ... but I have no recollection of mentioning Danny or
anybody else.''
   Jeff Nesbit, Quayle's press secretary, said today that ``phone
calls may have been made'' on behalf of the senator. Top aides in
George Bush's campaign said they were still looking into the
controversy.
   Quayle will be nominated tonight as Bush's running mate.
   Two ex-adjutants general disagreed on whether Quayle would have
even needed any help in getting into the National Guard.
   John S. Anderson, a Democrat and adjutant general immediately
before Quayle joined the guard, said there was a waiting list for
guard service. John N. Owens, a Republican who assumed the position
in January 1969, said there was room for anyone who wanted to join.
   Quayle, born on Feb. 4, 1947, drew number 210 for the year 1970
draft. The ceiling for the draft that year was 215, Col. Billie
Holmes, deputy director of the Indiana Selective Service told The
News on June 15, 1970.
</TEXT>
