<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Playboy founder Hugh Hefner, 62, who had a
palimony suit slapped on him earlier this year, intends to have
January Playmate of the Month Kimberley Conrad sign a prenuptial
agreement before the two head for the altar.
   The couple announced their engagement in July and are expected
to wed next year. Hefner has been single since his first marriage
ended in divorce in 1952.
   Robyn Radomski, spokeswoman for Playboy Enterprises Inc.,
wouldn't divulge details of the agreement, but said Ms. Conrad, 26,
``won't get control (of the company) in the event of a divorce of
if anything happens to Hef.''
   Employees and shareholders apparently expressed concern after
Hefner's former lover, Carrie Leigh, filed a palimony lawsuit,
which she later dropped.
   Hefner's daughter, Christie, runs Chicago-based Playboy as
president and vice chairwoman. Although Ms. Hefner has been praised
for improving operations at the publishing and entertainment
company, Playboy on Wednesday announced a $5.1 million loss in the
fourth quarter.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: For release after 6 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The secret to a good marriage, says actor Jeff
Bridges, is to not have sex _ with his co-stars, that is.
   ``Kissing all those pretty girls up on the screen has got to be
tough on (my wife), though she says it's not so bad,'' said
Bridges, who has worked with Jessica Lange, Rachel Ward, Kim
Basinger and Karen Allen among others.
   ``I really like to get as close as I can to the people I'm
working with,'' the actor said in an interview in the Sept. 5 issue
of US magazine. ``I like to even get intimate with my co-stars, but
not sexually.''
   Bridges, 38, who is starring in ``Tucker: The Man and His
Dream'' about maverick automaker Preston Tucker, has been married
11 years to photographer Susan Geston.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WACO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Willie Nelson concert to benefit the
depositors of a failed bank has been rescheduled for another stage
after a university president canceled the original show.
   Plans for the singer to perform at Baylor University were
scrapped after University President Herbert Reynolds, citing
``concern for the health and well-being of the American people,''
canceled the program Tuesday.
   Although Reynolds didn't elaborate, Eugene Baker, a spokesman
for the Southern Baptist university, said the cancellation
concerned the country star's personal behavior. Although Baker
wouldn't go into detail either, Nelson has been married three
times, sports shoulder-length hair and an earring and drinks on
stage.
   Promoter Tom Gresham said Wednesday from Austin that Nelson
authorized him to proceed with plans for a Nov. 14 concert at the
Heart O' Texas Coliseum to benefit the depositors of the failed
Leroy Bank, a private bank northeast of Waco.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: For release after 6 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Before he took up residence at ``Frank's
Place,'' actor Tim Reid was ready to live as a hermit in Nevada.
   ``I had bought 200 acres of land near Tahoe and severed all my
other relationships _ and there had been many _ and figured I would
just club a woman and drag her off to the mountains for a
weekend,'' Reid said in an interview in Sunday's Parade magazine.
   But after meeting Daphne Maxwell, Reid said he decided to forgo
the cloistered existence. She went on to become his second wife and
co-star in the series.
   His new focus is to bring his view of black life to television.
``It's not enough anymore for a black to be able to play parts
written for whites,'' Reid said. ``Too often, I've seen talented
blacks gain some power only to lose it because they are afraid they
won't be hired again if they write their kind of stories.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Jay Leno said he has
tremendous loyalty to both NBC and ``Tonight Show'' star Johnny
Carson for giving him national recognition.
   Leno, who was recently made the official vacation replacement
for Carson, said he has been offered shows on other networks but
has turned them down. ``I don't want to go up against Johnny,'' he
said.
   But he wouldn't mind sitting behind Carson's desk permanently
someday.
   ``Sure, I'd take the job if it were offered to me, but Johnny
isn't going anywhere. He likes doing it, and his ratings are
high,'' said Leno, who is appearing in Albuquerque this week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Philharmonic Orchestra
arrived Thursday to play two concerts that music director Zubin
Mehta said were three years overdue.
   The Philharmonic canceled a planned visit to Athens at the last
minute in June 1985 when the United States warned travelers to
avoid Athens Airport after a TWA jetliner was hijacked shortly
after takeoff from there.
   ``We are three years late and we hope that our performance will
fill in this void,'' Mehta said at a news conference.
   The Philharmonic will perform this weekend at the 1,800-year-old
Herod Atticus theater at the foot of the Acropolis hill to start an
11-country European tour.
</TEXT>
