<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 1442EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RevengeBackfires     08-18 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Revenge Backfires,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Phone Spree Backfires On Man Who Sought Revenge On Ex-Roommates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager who sought revenge on two
roommates who stiffed him for the rent is facing a possible prison
term for his scheme of revenge.
   Michael Gist went on a spree of overseas dialing that he figured
his roommates would have to pay for. The call he will pay for,
perhaps with a prison term, is a bomb threat to the U.S. Embassy in
Beirut, Lebanon.
   Michael Gist, 18, originally of Canoga Park, Calif., pleaded
guilty Wednesday in U.S. District Court in Minneapolis to one count
of making harassing telephone calls, a misdemeanor. Magistrate
Floyd Boline ordered a presentence investigation and released Gist
on a $5,000 unsecured bond.
   The telephone harassment charge is punishable by up to six
months in prison and a $50,000 fine. However, under a plea bargain
with the U.S. Attorney's office, Gist would serve a maximum
sentence of three months if Boline approves.
   Gist moved to Minnesota from California in July, according to
Assistant U.S. Attorney Richard Vosepka.
   During Wednesday's court appearance, Gist told Boline that he
was angry with his friends for moving out without paying the rent
on their apartment in the Twin Cities suburb of Fridley.
   Since the apartment telephone was still in the other roommates'
names, Gist said he and his girlfriend decided to spend the night
of Aug. 5 making overseas calls.
   In his call to the U.S. Embassy in Beirut, Gist spoke with the
embassy switchboard operator. Gist said he asked to speak with
someone ``higher up,'' but was told no one else was available
because it was 4:10 a.m. in Beirut. Gist said he then told the
operator that a bomb would go off at the embassy at noon.
   ``Then he asked me what my name was,'' he said. Gist hung up.
   The long-distance operator came back on the line to ask the
embassy if the call had been completed and the switchoard operator
described the call as a bomb threat, Vosepka said.
   The operator immediately gave Gist's telephone number to the
embassy, which notified the State Department in Washington. The
State Department called the FBI, which had agents staking out
Gist's apartment in about an hour, Vosepka said. FBI agents
arrested Gist the following evening.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
