<1ST_LINE>u p PM-CVN--ConventionRdp 5thLd-Writethru a0663 08-18 1060</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Convention Rdp, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0663,1110</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Says ``Gears Shift Tonight,'' Staff Faces Quayle-Guard Issue</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 8 grafs with Bush, Quayle remarks, former
Indiana guard official, campaign official's comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush today polished a speech to accept
the Republican presidential nomination as campaign aides tried to
defuse a controversy about whether newly picked running mate Dan
Quayle had used influence to get into the National Guard during the
Vietnam war.
   Brushing aside the issue, Bush declared at a fund-raising
luncheon, with Quayle at his side, ``I don't think I could have
selected anybody that'll do more to help the election than Dan
Quayle of Indiana. He is going to be outstanding on this ticket.''
   Quayle told the enthusiastic crowd, ``I'm darn proud to have
George Bush as our presidential nominee. I can't wait to get out
there. ... I can't wait to take this campaign to the American
people.''
   Neither mentioned the controversy.
   Bush campaign chief James A. Baker III said his staff was
``continuing to explore'' the issue with Quayle. Marilyn Quayle
said her husband, who was 22 at the time, ``wasn't a draft dodger.''
   Jeff Nesbit, Quayle's press secretary, said it was the
``collective recollection'' of Quayle and his father, newspaper
publisher James Quayle, ``that phone calls may have been made on
his behalf.''
   A retired executive of the Pulliam family newspaper empire,
Retired Maj. Gen. Wendell C. Phillippi, who worked for Quayle's
grandfather, said he had contacted a ``multitude'' of guard
acquaintances on behalf of Quayle, The Indianapolis News reported
today.
   Bush campaign spokeswoman Alixe Glen said, ``Not a single
thought is being given'' to dropping Quayle from the ticket.
   Tonight, Bush goes before the Republican National Convention
with a 20-minute speech that he calls the most important one he's
ever given. Senate Republican leader Bob Dole, himself a war hero,
was to nominate Quayle, a conservative, 41-year-old senator as
Bush's running mate.
   ``I'm upbeat and ready to go,'' Bush told cheering Texas
delegates at a breakfast gathering on the final day of the
Republican National Convention.
   ``I've been a loyal vice president, but now the gears shift
tonight, and I'm going to be the nominee of this party for
president and I'm going to set the agenda,'' he said.
   Recently revived in the polls, Bush still faces the challenge of
defining his vision of the nation's future and dealing with voters'
remaining questions about his ability to lead and what he stands
for.
   Less than 24 hours after Bush picked Quayle, questions were
raised about his service in the guard.
   Quayle told NBC-TV that in 1969 he had ``let a number of people
know I wanted to get into the National Guard,'' and added, ``If
phone calls were made, I can't answer, I don't know the specifics
of that.''
   Bush campaign chief Baker, appearing on ABC-TV today, said
Quayle ``basically said, `Look, I really wanted to serve in the
guard. I was anxious to do that. ... I wanted to go to law school,
I was anxious to do that, and if some people helped me, they helped
me.''
   Added Baker: ``I think, frankly, he's talking about help from
his family, which really wasn't particularly unusual, given the
circumstances of the time, given the attitude, if you will, of many
baby boomers at the time, toward that situation.''
   Bush pollster Robert Teeter said Quayle, during the search for a
running mate, had said no one helped him get into the guard.
   John Owens, adjutant general of the Indiana National Guard from
January 1969 until August 1972, said Indiana ``had vacancies
galore'' in its guard units during his years. However, John S.
Anderson, adjutant general immediately before Owens, told the
Indianapolis News there was a waiting list for Guard service.
   Reacting to the news, Rep. Tom Tauke, R-Iowa, said, ``If they
pulled strings to get him out of going (to Vietnam), he's got a
problem. It happened 20 years ago, but it is still a problem.''
However, Senate Minority Leader Alan Simpson of Wyoming said,
``It's a bunch of crap. There's about 10 million people in the
National Guard who should be offended by all of this.''
   Amid the final day convention celebrations, Bush attended a
rally for his wife, Barbara, before going to a $1,000-a-plate
luncheon expected to raise $4 million for the Republican National
Committee.
   Introducing his wife earlier, Bush said strategists had told him
he had to be more dynamic. ``So here we go, the introduction, with
feeling, with demonstrable emotion, the next first lady of the
United States,'' Bush said.
   Acting like a television game show host, he called out, ``Come
on up, sweetie pie. Come on up.'' The audience laughed and
applauded.
   Meanwhile, there was encouraging news for him in a new public
opinion poll. Several polls after last month's Democratic National
Convention gave Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis
leads of 17 points or so, but recent surveys have suggested the gap
has narrowed to next to nothing.
   The latest, published today by The Washington Post, showed a
Dukakis lead of 49 percent to 46 percent _ within the poll's
3-point margin of potential sampling error. The survey was
conducted from Aug. 11 through Tuesday, the day Bush named Quayle,
among 1,119 likely voters nationwide.
   Bush swept uncontested to the GOP presidential nomination
Wednesday night in a balloon-filled celebration that ran past
midnight. Before it was over, thousands of people had already left
the Louisiana Superdome.
   For Bush, it was a family affair. All five of his now-adult
children were delegates to the convention, and his Mexican-born
daughter-in-law, Columba, delivered the final seconding speech for
his nomination in Spanish.
   By design, Bush's oldest son, George W. Bush, delivered the 111
votes of the Texas delegation that put the state's ``favorite son
and the world's best father'' over the 1,139 delegates needed for
nomination.
   From a hotel suite nearby, Bush watched the proceedings on
television, surrounded by grandchildren and other relatives.
   ``It is a special moment,'' he said. ``The conclusion was
foregone, but it's special.'' All of his children and his 10
grandchildren will be on stage with Bush tonight to share in his
moment of triumph.
   The convention's first order of business will be to ratify
Quayle as the vice presidential nominee and applaud his acceptance
speech.
</TEXT>
