<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--JockeyingForJobs     08-18 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Jockeying For Jobs,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Election Would Set Off Republican Job Scramble</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A George Bush victory in November would
likely pit Bush loyalists against Reagan administration
officeholders in a mad scramble for government jobs, Republican
Party analysts say.
   While the competition for such high-ranking jobs wouldn't be
nearly as publicized as the scramble for the No. 2 spot on Bush's
ticket, the jockeying would be fierce.
   The face of the Cabinet would change, as it does with any new
administration, but the most grisly competition would involve
sub-Cabinet-level jobs, like assistant secretaries and agency heads.
   Even before Bush came to this city to claim the presidential
nomination, two longtime vice presidential associates _ former
Pennsylvania Gov. Richard Thornburgh and Wall Street investment
banker Nicholas F. Brady _ were put in the Cabinet, although Brady
is still awaiting confirmation.
   The Bush influence also was seen in President Reagan's
nomination of Texas Tech University President Lauro F. Cavazos as
secretary of education, since the vice president had promised a
month earlier that he would put a Hispanic in the Cabinet.
   Both Reagan and Bush scoffed at suggestions the president was
helping the vice president get off to a quick start on Cabinet
formation. But it is not expected that Thornburgh, Brady and
Cavazos would be asked to relinquish their jobs in a Bush
administration.
   Ed Mahe, a veteran Republican Party consultant and activist,
said Cabinet changes are automatic when administrations change,
even if the incumbent party wins.
   But he said the real battle lines will be drawn in the
sub-Cabinet positions such as deputy secretary agency chairman and
so forth.
   Mahe said that, for the most part, it is ``standard operating
procedure'' for such senior political appointees to offer their
resignations _ and then let the president decide whether they
remain.
   In Bush's case, he said, ``I would expect for him to have that
opportunity to start from scratch. He has every right to expect
them to submit them (resignations) and even demand it.''
   Mahe said the most intense competition will likely be between
longtime Bush loyalists and conservative Reagan administration
figures who started government services in lesser jobs but moved to
key top-level posts during the course of Reagan's two terms.
   ``So I think there will be intense jockeying by Bush-type people
trying to get in, and Reagan-type conservatives trying to stay
in,'' he said.
   Former Attorney General William French Smith, a longtime Reagan
friend who is attending the convention as a delegate from
California, said, ``There is always jockeying for jobs, and there's
not always rationality to it. It's a strange process.''
   ``It turns not just on the connection with the candidate, it may
turn on something entirely different,'' such as the Senate
confirmation process, he said.
   Alan ``Punch'' Green, a convention delegate from Portland, Ore.,
said he expected that ``there would be major changes in the Cabinet
to match the Bush personality.''
   ``You see it now in Nick Brady at Treasury and Dick Thornburgh
at Justice, and you'll see it in Jim Baker'' going to the State
Department, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880818-0144 </DOCNO>
