<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Rape-MurderCase     08-18 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rape-Murder Case,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Throws Out Conviction, Saying Victim May Have Been Dead
Before Rape</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A security guard convicted of raping
and killing a woman will get a new trial because of insufficient
evidence that the rape occurred while the victim was alive, a state
appeals court has decided.
   In a ruling filed this week, the 4th District Court of Appeal
said the 1979 bludgeoning and strangling of 22-year-old Savannah
Anderson was ``a most heinous murder.'' But it reversed the
conviction of Robert Lloyd Sellars, saying that jurors in his 1986
trial were not instructed properly on the law regarding rape.
   ``Unfortunately, the failure to properly instruct on rape
tainted the first-degree murder verdict as well,'' Presiding
Justice Harmon Scoville wrote in the opinion.
   County Deputy District Attorney Richard King said Wednesday that
he will challenge the ruling in higher courts and take Sellars to
trial a second time if necessary.
   ``We are shocked and we are confused,'' King said. ``We feel
this decision was clearly erroneous as a matter of law.''
   Attorney Jennifer Keller, who represented Sellars, said she
believes the justices acted properly in overturning the conviction
because the rape allegation was not supported by the evidence.
   Sellars, who worked at the Irvine apartment complex where Ms.
Anderson lived, was arrested in 1984, five years after she was
killed.
   An Orange County Superior Court jury found Sellars guilty of
first-degree murder along with a special-circumstance allegation _
that the offense was committed during the commission of a rape.
Sellars was sentenced to life in prison without possibility of
parole.
</TEXT>
