<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 1602EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NASAImage     08-18 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NASA Image,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Challenger Accident Led To `Clam-Up' In NASA, Spokesman Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many in NASA responded to the Challenger
shuttle accident with a ``massive clam-up'' that led to a feeling
of mistrust by the news media toward the space agency, a spokesman
said Thursday.
   James McCulla, director of media services for the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration, said in a speech that
following the Jan. 28, 1986 Challenger explosion, there were orders
from agency administrators that no one was to talk to the media
about the possible causes of the accident.
   ``This caused some of our NASA people to desert their usual
openness with the press,'' said McCulla. ``You had a massive
clam-up, like never before. Our reputation with the mass media was
hurt.''
   He said there were stories alleging that NASA was attempting to
cover up the causes of the Challenger accident and there arose a
feeling of mistrust toward NASA.
   Before the accident, he said, NASA enjoyed the reputation of a
``Mission Impossible'' organization, an agency that could tackle
the difficult assignments and accomplish success because it had
``the best and the brightest'' engineers and leadership.
   But after Challenger exploded and killed seven crew members, the
agency came under close scrutiny of the press, a presidential
commission and Congress, and ``you could see how the image (of
excellence) disintingrated,'' McCulla said.
   Some scientists and engineers in the agency were confused by the
media spotlight and resented the criticism, he said. Some of the
technical leaders were proud of the job NASA had done in the Apollo
lunar program and the agency's other accomplishments, he said, and
``they couldn't understand why it (NASA) was being torn down and
raked over the coals'' after the accident.
   With NASA now in the final stages of preparation for returning
the shuttle fleet to flight, McCulla said the era of what he called
``NASA bashing'' news stories is over.
   ``The stories now look toward the future,'' he said.
   McCulla said the space agency has not abandoned its plans to fly
ordinary citizens in space. One of the seven who died aboard
Challenger was Christa McAuliffe, a Concord, N.H. school teacher
who had been selected as the first to fly in the citizen-in-space
program.
   NASA public relations leaders ``fought hard'' for that program,
McCulla said, and there still are plans to fly a teacher in the
future, but not until there is ``total confidence'' restored in the
space shuttle.
   ``After we've got that sort of confidence, the teacher will go
for a ride,'' he said. ``How far down the road that will be, I
don't know.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
