<HEAD>Kids Arrive for California Fling Courtesy of Marathon Air
Passenger</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS two graf after graf 3, ``The 30-member,'' with
comments from kids; PICKS UP graf 4, ``First stop''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-five wide-eyed kids from Georgia,
beneficiaries of a man who took an airline promotion very, very
seriously, began a four-day Southern California fling Thursday with
a backstage look at Hollywood.
   Clark Howard, a retired travel agent, flew 26,338 miles on 68
flights in 48 days in a marathon-on-wings to earn the free ride
West in an Eastern Airlines promotion.
   The 30-member entourage, 25 youngsters and five chaperones that
included Howard, arrived at Los Angeles International Airport at
11:08 a.m. It was the first plane ride ever for many of the
youngsters, ages to 9 to 15.
   ``At first I was nervous, but after the plane settled down it
didn't feel like it was moving. It felt like it was just sitting
there,'' Marcus Williams, 12, said inside the airport terminal.
   ``I want to see all of the beaches and the ladies and Disneyland
and Hollywood and the mansions and Beverly Hills,'' said Donald
Cunningham, 11.
   First stop on the tour was Universal Studios, where Frankenstein
and Woody Woodpecker are the official greeters at the VIP entrance.
   ``We are giving them a very special day here at the tour,'' said
Universal spokesman Jim Yeager, adding that the tour includes
backstage views of movie making and the Miami Vice, Star Trek, King
Kong and Conan the Barbarian action shows.
   From there, a caravan through Hollywood and Beverly Hills and a
swim at Venice Beach round out their first day West. None of the
youngsters had ever seen the ocean.
   A day-long tour of Disneyland on Friday, a trip to the San Diego
Zoo on Saturday and a visit to Manhattan Beach on Sunday completes
the excursion. They leave for home Sunday afternoon.
   Eastern offered 60 free tickets to anyone making at least 60
flights totaling more than 25,000 miles in 60 days as part of its
60th anniversary celebration, said Paula Musto at the airline's
Miami headquarters.
   ``We sort of forgot about it. We didn't think anybody would take
us up on it,'' she said. The 30 round trip tickets would have cost
about $9,000, she said.
   The children, wearing ``Partners Against Drugs'' T-shirts, were
selected on the basis of their participation in the ``Just Say No''
anti-drug program.
   The entourage included 12 youngsters from Big Brothers-Big
Sisters of Metro Atlanta and 13 children from the Super program
sponsored by the Boys Clubs of Metro Atlanta and the Metro Atlanta
Council on Alcohol and Drugs.
   ``This trip may not change their entire lives,'' said Judy
Weisberg of the Big Brothers program. ``But if it makes them feel
good about themselves, it's worth every penny.''
   Howard, 33, said he decided to earn the free tickets as soon as
he heard of the promotion because he wanted children to use them.
   ``I want the kids to have a good time,'' he said. ``but what I
think is much more important than that is that I want the kids to
have a much greater feel for what this country is and what's out
there for them.''
   Howard describes himself as ``mostly retired,'' although he does
work as a consultant for a publishing house and as host of a travel
show on WGST radio in Atlanta.
   ``I can't think of an air travel deal that occurred that I
didn't do over the years,'' he said.
   The most intense period of travel for Howard on this particular
odyssey was eight flights a day between Atlanta and Columbia, S.C.,
or Charlotte, N.C., for four consecutive days.
   WGST will pay for the children's hotel rooms in California, but
Howard paid the $2,110 for the 68 flights he took between May 6 and
June 25 out of his own pocket. He chose most of them for their low
pricetags.
   Flight attendants who served Howard going one way would do a
double take when they saw him on a return flight a few moments
later.
   ``They don't know whether you're a company inspector, a spy from
a competitor or a drug courier,'' Howard said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
