<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 1530EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>b a PM-SpaceShuttle 1stLd-Writethru a0490 08-18 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Space Shuttle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0490,0695</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Cape Canaveral, Fla.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Technicians Plan Repair Of Space Shuttle Gas Leak As Test Firing
Set</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with successful test firing;
picks up 3rd graf, `Kennedy Space...'; SUBS grafs 11-13, `In
Brigham...' with 1 graf to delete outdated material; picks up 14th
graf, `The Challenger...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An intentionally flawed space shuttle
booster rocket was successfully fired today in the last of a series
of tests for Morton Thiokol's redesigned booster before resumption
of manned U.S. space flights.
   The two-minute horizontal test firing, the fifth full-scale test
of the booster, sent clouds of dust billowing thousands of feet in
the air as hundreds of NASA and company observers cheered.
   ``Fantastic! It looked really good. This is it,'' said John
Thirkill, vice president of space operations for Morton Thiokol.
   If engineers deemed the test a success after inspecting the
prone rocket, and National Aeronautics and Space Administration
workers can plug a tiny fuel leak in Discovery, NASA officials will
be able to set a firm date in late September or early October for
the first shuttle launch in 32 months.
   Kennedy Space Center workers today planned to clamp a
4-inch-long clamshell-like device over the gas leak and fill it
under pressure with a sealing compound while Discovery remained on
the launch pad.
   To reach the leak, workers used a routing tool Wednesday to cut
two holes in the rear wall of Discovery's 60-foot-long cargo bay
and two more in the adjoining hull of the steering engine
compartment.
   The holes, separated by structural supports, enable a technician
to put both hands into the compartment.
   The tiny leak of nitrogen tetroxide gas was 12 inches from the
newly drilled access panels, on a fitting in a vent line. The leak
was detected more than a month ago and has been stopped by putting
pressure on the line. However, it must be plugged before launch to
prevent additional leakage.
   Because Discovery is standing vertically on the launch pad, the
rear wall of the cargo bay is parallel to the ground, forcing the
technicians to work on their hands and knees or on their stomachs.
   The repair and subsequent testing are expected to take about a
week, said NASA spokeswoman Lisa Malone.
   When the leak was discovered last month, officials at first
feared they might have to move Discovery to a hangar for repairs,
which could have delayed the launch as much as two months. But
engineers came up with the innovative idea for making the fix on
the pad.
   The repair was delayed until the launch team conducted a
successful test firing last week of Discovery's three main engines,
powered by liquid fuel. The leak is in a separate engine system
used to steer the shuttle in orbit.
   Scores of improvements have been made to Thiokol's 126-foot-long
booster, but the main emphasis has been on reworking the field
joints that hold together the rocket's cylindrical segments.
   The Challenger explosion was blamed on a faulty joint that
allowed a plume of super-hot gas to burn through an O-ring seal and
ignite the main liquid fuel tank.
   For today's booster test, two of the three field joints _ the
case-to-nozzle joint and the igniter-to-case joint _ were riddled
with 11 intentional flaws to test the joints to their limits as the
rocket burned 1.1 million pounds of propellant in 120 seconds. The
unflawed joint was a control.
   Among the defects were separations in the bonded adhesive
insulation that helps hold the joints together, and channels that
would allow the fiery gas to reach the joint's middle O-ring, one
of three designed to contain heat from the burning fuel.
   The joints also are equipped with heaters to keep their
temperatures at a minimum of 75 degrees. Freezing air the night
before the doomed Challenger launch were found to have contributed
to the joint's failure.
   With the exception of the flaws, the rocket is virtually
identical to a version Morton Thiokol successfully test-fired on
June 14 and to those now attached to Discovery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
