<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--Drought-Illinois     08-18 0131</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Drought-Illinois,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Illinois Farmers Eligible for Drought Loans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers throughout Illinois are eligible to
apply for Farmers Home Admininstration emergency loans to help
cover part of their crop losses from the drought, Deputy Secretary
Peter C. Myers announced Thursday.
   Myers said farmers in all of the state's 102 counties have eight
months in which to apply for the loans to cover part of their
actual losses.
   To be eligible, he said, they must be able to repay the FmHA
loans and any other loans, must be unable to get credit elsewhere
and must have adequate security.
   Illinois is the 13th entire state designated eligible for FmHA
emergency drought loans. Others are Alabama, Delaware, Indiana,
Iowa, Maryland, Missouri, New Jersey, North Dakota, Ohio,
Pennsylvania, Wisconsin and West Virginia.
</TEXT>
