<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 1700EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GoneFishing     08-18 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gone Fishing,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Platter And Lots Of Chatter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. HACKETT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every Wednesday, summer and winter, Joe
Bailey pulls down the shade on the front door and hangs a sign in
the window _ ``Gone Fishing.''
   He's gone from the store, and off the air.
   Wednesdays off have been a tradition since Bailey's Country
Store opened for business and later developed a sideline into the
longest-running radio talk show in Kentucky.
   For 41 years, the program dispensed advice, humor, announcements
and commentary, but little music, from 8:30 to 9 a.m. every day
except Sundays and Wednesdays .
   ``I play only one record. Usually, it's an oldie, something out
of the 1930s, and stuff you won't hear anywhere else,'' said
Bailey, who took over the microphone six years ago from his
brother, Bart.
   Bailey broadcasts from one corner of the store at Williamsburg.
Just a few feet away are racks of clothing, including bib overalls,
washboards and tubs, nails, lanterns and dozens of items that would
be difficult to find in big city discount houses.
   ``I can look around and see what bargains are available and tell
people about them. We don't sell groceries because we'd probably
eat up the profits,'' said Bailey, whose show has five sponsors.
   While he is on the air, Bailey may be interrupted by telephone
calls from listeners with such questions as:
   ``I want to buy a cow. You know where one's for sale?''
   ``When's the best time to make sauerkraut?''
   Other callers, interested in astrology, will telephone in
advance to ask ``if the signs are right for weaning a baby or
setting a hen to hatch.''
   Bailey also handles announcements of yard sales and church
meetings. ``I receive lots of queries about lost dogs. In fact, I
get everything you get in a newspaper's classified ads column, and
then some.''
   There is no broadcast on Sunday when the store is locked because
``that's a day of rest,'' Bailey said. ``I need it.''
   The store was started by his father, Virgil, after the former
Harlan County coal miner moved to Whitley County in 1936.
   ``Dad also came up with the idea for the radio program and used
to drive to Corbin every day to broadcast live over station WCTT.''
   When the four sons _ Joe, Bart, Ed and Bob _ took over, they
decided to have remote broadcast facilities installed at the store.
   ``My brothers have retired and I'd like to join them but
somebody's gotta work,'' said Bailey, now 39.
   The practice of closing on Wednesdays is nothing new, he said.
``It's an old mountain tradition. People who own a business often
do a little farming and that seems to be a good day for it.''
   Bailey does break the rule on the last Wednesday before
Christmas. ``We stay open as a courtesy to last-minute shoppers.''
   He describes the radio program as a community service.
   Asked why the show is so popular, he will grin and reply: ``It's
free and probably overpriced at that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
