<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp     08-18 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Says Iran Would Retaliate If Iraq Delays on Truce Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Any attempt by Iraq to delay
implementation of a U.N. peace resolution would force retaliation
by Iran, President Ali Khamenei of Iran said Thursday.
   Also on Thursday, the commander of the U.N. observer force that
will monitor a cease-fire arrived in Tehran from Baghdad for talks
with Iranian officials, the official Islamic Republic News Agency
said. The truce in the 8-year-old war is set to begin Saturday
morning in the Persian Gulf.
   Another 24 U.N. truce observers arrived in Baghdad, joining
about 100 others already there.
   In another development, anti-government Mujahedeen Khalq rebels
claimed that thousands of political prisoners have been executed in
Iran in recent weeks.
   Khamenei made the statement during an inspection tour of the
southern war fronts, IRNA reported in a dispatch monitored in
Cyprus.
   The Iranian agency quoted Khamenei as saying Iran takes the
various clauses of Security Council Resolution 598 as a whole.
   IRNA quoted him as saying any attempts to delay the withdrawal
of forces to international borders, or the demarcation of borders,
or the formation of a body to determine the aggressor in the war
would ``force us to strike back at the enemy with a stronger blow.''
   Iraq agreed to the U.N. resolution shortly after it was approved
in July 1987. Iran agreed to the resolution last month, clearing
the way for a cease-fire.
   The head of the 350-man U.N. observer force, Gen. Slavko Jovic
of Yugoslavia, flew to Tehran Thursday after talks with Iraqi
officials in Baghdad, U.N. officials in the Iraqi capital said.
   The Mujahedeen Khalq, or people's holy warriors, said in a telex
from its office in Baghdad that thousands of mujahedeen political
prisoners and hundreds of ``innocent residents'' have been killed
in mass executions in the past few weeks. It gave no precise
figures.
   The group, the largest of the exile movements battling Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini's government, said the bodies of those executed
were secretly buried in mass graves.
   Official Iranian media have reported that a dozen or so
mujahedeen were publicly hanged last month, but the numbers
reported by the rebel group are much higher.
   There was no immediate Iranian comment on the claims by the
mujahedeen, which could not be independently confirmed.
</TEXT>
