<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChavezFast     08-18 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chavez Fast,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Leader To Break Hunger Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DELANO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor leader Cesar Chavez plans to break
bread during Holy Communion on Sunday, ending what will be a 36-day
hunger strike, but his doctor doubts the United Farm Workers
president can last that long without food.
   Chavez plans to end the fast _ a protest of pesticide use on
California table grapes _ at an outdoor Mass in this town about 150
miles north of Los Angeles, First Vice President Dolores Huerta
said Thursday.
   Chavez, 61, suffered ``increasing problems with vomiting'' on
Wednesday, and his attending physician, Fidel Huerta, expressed
fear he might become dehydrated.
   ``Cesar's condition has deteriorated. He's increasingly
experiencing nausea, vomiting and cramping,'' Huerta said in a
statement.
   Chavez began the fast July 17.
   Chavez has lost 31 pounds and has been steadily weakening for
the last two weeks. He hasn't appeared in public since Aug. 11, but
allowed the media to briefly photograph a private meeting with the
Rev. Jesse Jackson on Sunday.
   Huerta and two other physicians who examined Chavez on Monday
said he runs the threat of possible irreversible damage to his
health by sustaining the hunger strike. Chavez has refused their
requests to enter the hospital.
   Chavez went 25 days without food during the 1968 grape boycott
to recommit himself to non-violence, and he conducted a 24-day fast
in 1972 to protest adoption of a right-to-work law in Arizona.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880818-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 1609EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mandela     08-18 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mandela,0794</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gov't Hints It Will Free Jailed Black Leader Soon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Thursday gave
its strongest hint yet that it soon will free jailed black leader
Nelson Mandela, reportedly suffering from tuberculosis.
   President P.W. Botha praised Mandela's cooperative attitude and
said he hoped the 70-year-old leader of the African National
Congress would not have to go back to prison from the hospital.
   Botha said he expects ``positive results'' from his standing
offer to free Mandela if Mandela renounces violence.
   Other officials indicated the government was considering
Mandela's release more seriously than ever before.
   The South African Press Association quoted unidentified
government sources as saying the release was imminent. The sources
suggested that militant supporters of the guerrilla movement might
start a campaign aimed at questioning whether Mandela, in the event
he renounces violence, was able to think for himself.
   The congress is the major guerrilla movement fighting for
black-majority rule. Mandela has been in prison since 1962 and is
serving a life term for sabotage and conspiracy to overthrow the
government. Surveys indicate he is the most popular leader among
South Africa's blacks.
   The Mandela family had no immediate statement, and the congress
said it would comment after studying the text of Botha's speech.
   A close associate of the family, speaking on condition of
anonymity, told The Associated Press that Mandela recently
reaffirmed his confidence in the congress and gave no indication he
was prepared to accept a conditional release. The source said Mrs.
Mandela was likely to visit her husband within the next day or two
to discuss the developments.
   Wynand Malan, an anti-apartheid member of Parliament, described
Botha's remarks as ``disturbing and regrettable'' and called for
the president's ouster. Malan said Botha ``wants to strip an ill
and ageing man of his credibility with his own people before he is
allowed to go free.''
   Information Minister Stoffel van der Merwe also said Mandela had
cooperated since he was transferred Aug. 12 from Cape Town's
Pollsmoor Prison to nearby Tygerberg Hospital.
   ``He did not try to use the occasion as a propaganda stunt,'' he
said. He noted that it was not Mandela, but his lawyer and friends,
who requested outside medical attention and disclosed the nature of
the illness.
   Another official, speaking on condition of anonymity, reported
progress in recent talks between Mandela and senior members of the
government. He declined to elaborate.
   Botha, addressing leaders of his National Party in Natal
province, said: ``The government, in a responsible way, will
consider the matter and if we get the cooperation we have so far
got from Mr. Mandela, I believe we will get positive results.
   ``Personally, I don't think that at his age and condition it
would be wise for him to choose to go back to prison, and I hope he
will make it possible for me to act in a humane way so that we can
have peace in South Africa,'' Botha said.
   Botha met before his speech with Justice Minister Kobie Coetsee,
who visited Mandela at Tygerberg on Wednesday.
   ``He appears to be comfortable and appears to have taken the
first steps toward recovery,'' Coetsee said of Mandela. ``He looks
as though he is almost his old self and he is already enjoying
jokes.''
   Doctors said Mandela probably will have a complete recovery.
   Van der Merwe said the government was not expecting Mandela to
sign anything, or even publicly disavow African National Congress
policy, but expected that he would not promote violent activities.
   However, Botha said in his speech, ``I am prepared to release
Mandela if he would say he rejects violence as a means for
political ends.''
   Tom Lodge, a University of the Witwatersrand academic who is a
leading expert on the ANC, said, ``I don't think Mandela will
accept anything other than unconditional release.'' But he added:
``If he is ill, it is unlikely that he would be involved ... in
violence.''
   Van der Merwe said last month that Mandela had already served
enough time for punishment of his crime and the only purpose in
keeping him in prison was national security.
   Mandela has rejected previous offers of freedom if he renounced
violence. He has said the government must end apartheid, legalize
the African National Congress and grant political rights to blacks.
   Last year, the government unconditionally freed Govan Mbeki, 77,
a congress official imprisoned for life at the same time as Mandela.
   Mbeki said he had not renounced violence or the congress. After
a few public appearances, the government banned him from addressing
audiences, giving interviews or leaving his hometown.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
