<DOCNO> AP880818-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 1717EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FastFood     08-18 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fast Food,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roy Rogers Pulls Ad After School Food Workers Complain It's
Demeaning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roy Rogers television commercial that school
cafeteria workers found demeaning for its portrayal of them as drab
and lazy servers of unappetizing food will be pulled, a spokesman
for the chain said Thursday.
   ``I think they've stooped to a new low by advocating that
children ought to eat junk food on a daily basis,'' said Charles
Hughes, president of Local 372 of the State, County and Municipal
Workers, AFL-CIO, which has more than 8,000 school cafeteria
workers.
   Hughes called the TV spot ``despicable'' and said he hoped
schoolchildren ``will not wind up over the years like Trigger, who
Roy Rogers has stuffed.'' Trigger was the screen cowboy's horse.
   The commercial starts with the tune, ``See You in September,''
and shows a series of cafeteria workers holding trays of
unappealing food close to the camera.
   ``The ad very clearly sends a message that one of the things you
ought to be dreading as Labor Day approaches is a return to the
school cafeteria,'' said City Councilwoman Ruth Messinger.
   Rick Sneed, public relations director for Marriott, which owns
the Roy Rogers chain, said the ad was intended to be a spoof of the
way cafeterias were years ago.
   Sneed said the company got calls from food service managers
complaining that ``that's not the way cafeteria workers look now
and it's also not the type of food served now _ macaroni and
cheese, sandwiches and so forth.''
   Sneed said the company does not feel that the commercial is
demeaning. ``Marriott has over 65,000 employees that work in
cafeterias and the last thing we're going to do is try and offend
somebody,'' he said.
   The ad began about 10 days ago and was to run until Sept. 9, but
Sneed said, ``It's our intent to pull it as soon as we can. It will
not run its full course.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
