<1ST_LINE>r w AM-China-Wheat     08-18 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Wheat,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Cleared to Buy US Wheat at Subsidy Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has been given approval to buy an
additional 2 million metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized
prices, the Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   Acting Undersecretary Richard W. Goldberg said the wheat will be
sold to China at competitive world prices under the department's
EEP or Export Enhancement Program.
   Under various authorizations or initiatives since Jan. 26, 1987,
China has bought about 7 million tons of U.S. wheat under the EEP
program. The previous authorization was for 2 million tons on April
5. Of that amount, only 10,000 tons remain for use, which is added
to the latest authorization.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat.
   Under EEP arrangements, exporters can sell U.S. commodities at
reduced prices to meet foreign competition and then collect free
government surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses or
subsidies.
   The Soviet Union also has been a big buyer of U.S. wheat under
EEP, with purchases totaling about 13 million tons since April 30,
1987.
</TEXT>
