<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon     08-18 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hard-line Christians Block Election of Syrian-Backed Candidate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanon postponed presidential elections
Thursday after hard-line Christians opposed to Syria's role in the
country missed a Parliament session where a Syrian-backed candidate
was favored to win election.
   Christian radio stations said two shells crashed near President
Amin Gemayel's palace in suburban Baabda after the session was
called off. They said there were no casualties.
   Police said they could not confirm the report and Gemayel's
spokesmen refused to comment.
   Interior Minister Abdulla Rassi accused the Lebanese Forces of
``forcefully preventing'' 15 members of Parliament from attending
the meeting. The military denied that.
   The Parliament lacked a quorum, preventing the election of
Suleiman Franjieh, a feudal lord opposed by the Lebanese Forces,
the main Christian militia.
   Only 38 Parliament members showed up, with 51 required for a
quorum.
   Gemayel's Phalange Party and the National Liberal Party of
Israeli-leaning Dany Chamoun, which back the Lebanese Forces,
boycotted the session.
   ``I shall set a date for a new session after speedy and
extensive consultations with parliamentary blocs,'' House Speaker
Hussein Husseini told reporters.
   The constitution stipulates that a president should be elected
before Sept. 23, when Gemayel's six-year term expires.
   In Washington, U.S. officials expressed regret at the
postponement and urged balloting before the constitutional deadline.
   ``We regret that a consensus candidate has not yet been found,''
said State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley.
   After the session was canceled, British Ambassador Alan Ramsey
told reporters: ``Some rethinking should be done in Damascus.''
   He appeared to suggest that Syria, Lebanon's main power-broker,
might reconsider its outright support for Franjieh in his bid to
seek a new term.
   Franjieh's campaign office said he would not drop out of the
race.
   Rassi accused the Lebanese Forces of ``forcefully preventing
more than 15 Christian Parliament members from reaching the
session'' to vote for Franjieh, 78.
   ``Some were forced by gunmen to go back home and at least two
deputies were detained,'' Rassi said, identifying them as Michael
Daher and Elias Hrawi, both Maronite Catholics like Franjieh.
   ``Daher was later released but I do not have any word about
Hrawi's fate yet,'' said Rassi, who is Franjieh's son-in-law.
   Kazem Khalil, a Shiite Moslem deputy who lives in east Beirut,
also said he was ``forbidden at gunpoint from leaving my house to
go to Parliament,'' he said.
   The Lebanese Forces commander, Samir Geagea, denied the charge,
saying ``Rassi is merely trying to cover up for his father-in-law's
failure'' to get elected.
   Franjieh, president from 1970 to 1976, alleges Geagea led a 1978
raid on his mansion that killed his eldest son and 30 bodyguards.
   The Lebanese Forces had vowed to block his return to power,
saying he would certainly seek to rekindle the dormant civil war.
   The Christian milita maintains good relations with Israel, which
controls a border enclave in south Lebanon.
   Franjieh, Syria's closest Christian ally in Lebanon, was the
leading contender among two dozen aspirants. The civil war erupted
in 1975 while he was in office and he is widely disliked for asking
Syria to use its military to intervene. Syria has 40,000 troops in
the country.
</TEXT>
