<2ND_LINE>AM-Police Truck,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Cruiser Shortage Puts Three In Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTAGE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three people have been hospitalized and the
town council split by arguments over a police car, which forced
officers to patrol in a dump truck when it broke down and made
headlines when it was replaced.
   Council President Bill Henderson collapsed Saturday in the
mayor's office upon hearing that a councilman got into a shouting
match with a Canadian disc jockey who helped raise money to buy a
new police car.
   Henderson was in satisfactory condition Thursday at Veterans
Medical Center in Altoona after being admitted for chest pains the
day before, said hospital spokesman Jim Mielnik.
   The disc jockey, Scruff Connors of CHTZ-FM in St. Catherines,
Ontario, had to be hospitalized for exhaustion after he arrived in
Portage two weeks ago to present the town with a new car. He had
raised about $12,000 from his listeners and contributed about
$4,500 himself.
   Connors was released from a hospital in nearby Johnstown last
week and was back in Portage when he encountered Councilman John
Mutsko on Main Street.
   Henderson said Wednesday that Mutsko, who had voted against
accepting the cruiser, made an obscene remark and told the disc
jockey to drive the car back to Canada.
   Connors returned Sunday to Canada, and Mutsko was charged with
harassment and disorderly conduct.
   Another councilman, George Calaba, has been in the hospital
twice since January for stress that Mayor Howard W. Smith says was
created by arguments over the cruiser.
   Police officers in this town of 3,510 people began using the
borough's dump truck in mid-July when their lone cruiser broke down.
   Connors began raising money for the car when he heard the news,
which made headlines in the United States and Canada. Medley, Fla.,
also donated an unmarked detective's car to Portage, which Smith
picked up last week.
</TEXT>
