<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BabySmothering     08-18 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baby Smothering,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Suspected Of Unusual Form Of Child Abuse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An occupational therapist was charged
with assault after doctors secretly videotaped her smothering her
1-year-old son in his hospital bed and then reviving him,
authorities said.
   The child had been hospitalized eight times since he was 7 weeks
old for what authorities had thought were respiratory attacks and
had suffered numerous, similar attacks at home, according to a
police complaint.
   Jane Swanson Wilken, 36, of South St. Paul was charged Wednesday
with third-degree assault. She is accused of blocking the breathing
of her son, Matthew, until he lost consciousness.
   The incident was recorded on videotape in the sleeping
laboratory at Children's Hospital in St. Paul, where doctors were
diagnosing the child's recurring respiratory attacks.
   The mother, who knows cardiopulmonary resuscitation, revived the
boy on some occasions and paramedics revived him other times, the
complaint said.
   Hospital officials became suspicious of the mother after the boy
was brought in for the seventh time on June 2, the complaint said.
Doctors initially believed he suffered from a breathing disorder,
but tests proved negative.
   Video surveillance began on June 9 and was conducted for seven
days. On June 14 around 10:30 p.m., videotape shows Mrs. Wilken
pressing her son's mouth and nose against her chest while he slept,
the complaint said.
   The video shows the boy struggling to escape before he went
stiff and then limp, the complaint said. When a respiration monitor
alarm went off, the videotape shows Mrs. Wilken calling for help
and giving her son mouth-to-mouth resuscitation.
   Tests indicate the boy has not suffered brain damage, the
complaint said.
   According to police, the boy was released from the hospital to
the care of his father, James Wilken, at the couple's home. Mrs.
Wilken was ordered to move in with her mother and father, who is a
physician.
   Ramsey County Attorney Tom Foley said the case apparently
involves a psychiatric disorder known as ``Munchausen syndrome by
proxy.''
   ``In this case, everybody believes a small child has a serious
illness and it brings attention to the mother,'' Foley said. ``She
acts like a `model' mother being able to take care of this sick
child.''
   The disorder is derived from Baron von Munchausen, an
18th-century German who became well known for elaborate lies.
   John Wodele, executive assistant to Foley, said Thursday that
Mrs. Wilken has cooperated with the investigation and is expected
to surrender to authorities by early next week.
   Mrs. Wilken's lawyer, Linda Gallant, declined to comment beyond
saying that her client is cooperating.
   Wodele said charges were not filed immediately because child
protection measures were in place. ``We're also dealing in an area
that's new to us,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
