<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reagan-Pakistan     08-18 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Pakistan,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Pakistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Nominates Replacement For Envoy To Islamabad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moving with unusual speed,
President Reagan announced Thursday he will nominate veteran
diplomat Robert B. Oakley to replace Arnold L. Raphel, the U.S.
ambassador to Pakistan who was killed in an airplane crash.
   The White House said the president was placing telephone calls
to Nancy Ely-Raphel, the ambassador's widow, and Sara Raphel, his
mother.
   The announcement said the president also planned to call Judy
Wassom, wife of Gen. Herbert M. Wasson, chief U.S. military
representative in Pakistan, who was killed in the crash Wednesday
along with Pakistani President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq.
   ``The president is expressing condolences and sympathy on behalf
of the nation,'' White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said.
   Fitzwater said the president and First Lady Nancy Reagan, along
with Vice President George Bush and his wife, Barbara, had sent
messages of condolence to Zia's wife and family.
   The White House said Reagan and Bush also had sent messages to
Ghulam Ishaq Khan, the newly named acting president of Pakistan.
Reagan's message said, ``Let us all rededicate ourselves to the
task of regional peace and reconstruction to which President Zia
dedicated his life. As you carry out your heavy responsibilities in
his absence, please count on the United States for support.''
   The White House statement said Reagan told Zia's widow that the
Pakistani president ``was a great statesman whose loss will be
mourned by his people and the world.''
   Pakistan is one of the United States' more important allies.
   Fitzwater said the president had asked Secretary of State George
P. Shultz to lead a U.S. delegation to Zia's funeral Saturday in
Islamabad. Oakley, now senior director of Middle East, South Asia,
and North Africa affairs for the National Security Council, will
join several members of Congress in the delegation.
   In Washington, the State Department declined to speculate about
the cause of the fatal plane crash but praised the Pakistani
government's decisions to hold elections in November as scheduled
and to stick to the foreign policy pursued by Zia.
   At the Pentagon, spokesman Dan Howard said eight U.S. accident
investigators was due in Pakistan Thursday to help search for the
cause of the plane crash.
   A second group, including six U.S. military forensic
specialists, will assist the Pakistanis in identifying the victims
of the crash. That team is being sent from West Germany, Howard
said.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley, whose husband is
Reagan's choice to replace Raphel in Islamabad, told reporters that
Acting President Ishaf Khan had reaffirmed Pakistan's pro-U.S.
foreign policy ``and its continuing steps toward democracy.''
   She said Ishaf Khan had indicated elections would be held as
scheduled by Zia in mid-November.
   ``These are sound first steps,'' Mrs. Oakley said, and ``a
welcome sign.''
   Robert Oakley, 57, was a resident fellow at the Carnegie
Endowment for International Peace before joining the NSC staff.
Before that he served from 1984 to 1986 as director of the State
Department's Office for Combatting Terrorism.
   He has served as ambassador to Somali and Zaire as well as
deputy assistant secretary of state for Asia and the Pacific.
   Besides Oakley and Shultz, other members of the delegation to
Zia's funeral will be Undersecretary of State Michael Armacost,
State Department Country Director Robert Flatten, and Army Maj.
Gen. Robert Jones, representing the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
   Congressional members include Rep. John Murtha, D-Pa., Rep. Bill
McCollum Jr., R-Fla., and Rep. Charles Wilson, D-Texas.
</TEXT>
