<1ST_LINE>r p AM-AlaskaPrimary     08-18 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alaska Primary,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alaska Voters Consider 1994 Olympics Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ballot issue crucial to Anchorage's
bid for the 1994 Winter Olympics will be decided in Tuesday's
election, along with lopsided primary races in both parties for the
state's lone congressional seat.
   Anchorage is one of four cities in the running for the 1994
winter games, with the winner to be decided by the International
Olympic Committee next month. The other finalists are in Norway,
Bulgaria and Sweden.
   In 1985, Anchorage voters endorsed the Olympics bid by a 2-to-1
margin, but they were not told at the time that the city would have
to sign a financial agreement. Tuesday's vote will determine
whether they would back financial guarantees.
   In July, a poll sanctioned by the Anchorage Organizing
Committee, the group trying to bring the Olympics here, showed
voters evenly divided on the question.
   If the referendum proposal passes, the Anchorage municipal
government would agree to become jointly liable for the AOC's
costs, should their efforts at private fund-raising fall short. But
at the same time the proposal specifies that the committee is
expected to raise the needed funds itself.
   Any bond issue to build stadiums or other Olympics facilities
would have to be approved by another referendum, the proposal
states.
   Earlier this year, IOC President Juan Samaranch said that for
Anchorage to stay in the running, there would have to be a
significant margin of victory in the election to reassure the IOC
that the city is committed to staging the games.
   The AOC has said private money, mostly from television
contracts, will cover the cost of holding the games.
   Supporters say the games would boost Anchorage's image, but
opponents say they doubt the games can pay for themselves and
dismiss the image argument.
   In the twin congressional primaries, Rep. Don Young, an
eight-term Republican, and Democrat Peter Gruenstein, a former
state prosecutor making his first try for statewide office, both
face only minor opposition.
   Gruenstein has been ignoring his primary competition to aim
verbal jabs at Young, who admitted in a fund-raising appeal June 30
that this fall he ``will be embroiled in a tough re-election
battle.''
   Young for the third time is being challenged for the Republican
nomination by George Johnston, an ARCO Alaska employee from
Anchorage whom Young defeated by a 50-to-1 margin in the 1986
primary.
   Gruenstein is opposed for the Democratic nomination by Eugene
Vick of Juneau and Ryal White of Anchorage, both relative unknowns.
White ran in the Democratic primary for governor in 1986 and lost.
</TEXT>
