<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 2006EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Jordan-PLO     08-18 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jordan-PLO,0652</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jordan Says Confederation With Palestinian State No Longer
Automatic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jordan no longer views confederation with
an eventual Palestinian state in the West Bank and Gaza Strip as
automatic, a palace official said Thursday.
   The development makes U.S. proposals for Middle East peace more
unlikely than ever before.
   The palace official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Jordan no longer wants to be a ``screen'' separating the United
States and Israel from negotiating directly with the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   ``Once the Palestinian state is there, we Jordanians are going
to look at the relationship and decide if we are going to accept a
confederation,'' the official said. ``It's a choice.''
   Ever since the United States arranged the Camp David accords
between Egypt and Israel in 1979, U.S. officials have said their
Middle East peace plans depend on Jordan overseeing a Palestinian
entity on the territories Israel captured in the 1967 Middle East
War.
   Until the war, Jordan considered the West Bank part of its own
territory, and Egypt held a mandate over the Gaza Strip.
   Only five months ago, U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz
told reporters in Amman that he envisioned a Palestinian mini-state
tied to Jordan much as California and Texas are tied to the United
States.
   But on July 31, King Hussein renounced sovereignty over the West
Bank to honor Arab summit declarations making the PLO ``the sole
and legitimate representative of the Palestinian people.''
   After Hussein's announcement, State Department officials in
Washington insisted their peace plans were still alive.
   The palace official said Jordan was still involved in any
Arab-Israeli peace efforts and noted that Jordan shares Israel's
longest border. But he stressed that the PLO was in charge of
dealing with the Palestinian issue.
   The concept of a confederation between Jordan and a Palestinian
state was enshrined in a February 1985 agreement between Hussein
and PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat.
   Most PLO officials, however, insisted that an independent state
should precede a confederation. Jordan argued for recovery of the
occupied lands before settling their status.
   Jordan hoped a confederation would ease fears of an independent
Palestinian state on Israel's border and coax the United States and
Israel into an international peace conference to settle the long
conflict.
   ``It was an instrument to make the international conference
work,'' the palace official said.
   Most officials still regard some form of confederation as
inevitable because Jordan and the West Bank have strong family and
economic links and a separate West Bank may not be economically
viable.
   While Jordan has cooled on the confederation plan, PLO officials
who conferred with leaders in Amman this week reiterated their
support for such a plan.
   They told reporters privately, however, that they received no
response from the Jordanians.
   Ironically, Jordan's decision to step aside in favor of the PLO
appears to have prompted PLO leaders to consider the explicit
recognition of Israel.
   U.S. officials cite the PLO's formal refusal to accept Israel as
a key reason for refusing to deal with the organization.
   PLO officials say an upcoming meeting of the policy-making
Palestine National Council probably will establish a provisional
government and approve a ``declaration of independence'' for the
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Discussions on the form of a government are still under way
within the PLO. But officials said it almost surely will be based
on acceptance of U.N. Security Council Resolution 181, the measure
that created Israel and called for a Palestinian state.
   It would also sidestep clauses in the PLO charter that demand
Israel's eventual replacement with a ``democratic secular state.''
   PLO officials hope such a plan will win Western support and
create a potential bargaining partner for Israel and the United
States in peace talks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880818-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 2009EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--MovieRentals     08-18 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Movie Rentals,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Movie Rentals Up As Republicans Make Bad Theater</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jerry Dorris is one person who would like to see
the Republican National Convention last longer. Business at his
video rental store is up 20 percent as a prime alternative to all
the political talk.
   ``I wish the conventions were each two months long and were held
every year,'' said Dorris, owner of Landmark Video in the Empire
State Building, where comedies and action adventures were
alternatives to acceptance speeches.
   ``The majority of our customers want to be entertained after a
day of work. They don't want to be bored by the convention. The
general comment is they've had enough and they'd much rather watch
a movie,'' Dorris said Thursday.
   A spot check of other stores indicated movie fans have elected
to tune out the George Bush and Dan Quayle show, which has filled
prime time for the three networks, and flicked to fantasyland
instead.
   ``The Manchurian Candidate'' was doing well in some areas, but
political movies such as ``All The President's Men,'' ``The
Candidate'' with Robert Redford and ``Advise and Consent'' gathered
dust on the shelves.
   Nor was there much demand for Ronald Reagan's ``Bedtime For
Bonzo'' or ``Knute Rockne _ All-American,'' the movie where he
first asked his mentor to win one for the Gipper.
   ``People are pretty bored with the convention,'' said Sue
Granat, salesperson at New York City's Videoroom, where rentals are
up 25 percent.
   ``There hasn't been a good convention since the Democrats in
1968. That had drama and violence,'' she said.
   Rentals also increased during the Democratic gathering in
Atlanta, but the earlier convention at least had some electricity
between Jesse Jackson and Miachel Dukakis, store officials said.
   At the Video Circus, rentals were up 33 percent for the week.
   ``Everyone is complaining, coming in here and saying they don't
want to be bored,'' said store owner Frank Lopez. ``I guess it's
important, but it's quite monotonous after a while. I mean, really,
four days of that stuff?''
</TEXT>
