<HEAD>Sinhalese Radicals Kill Six</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four affiliates of the ruling United
National Party and two government militiamen were shot to death in
attacks that military officials blamed Thursday on Sinhalese
radicals.
   Members of the Sinhalese People's Liberation Front, a group of
radicals opposed to an India-sponsored peace plan, allegedly fired
at a group of militiamen in Moneragala district in southern Sri
Lanka, said officials who asked not to be identified. The militants
killed two militiamen and abducted the son of one of them.
   A member of the UNP, Lionel Abeysuriya, was shot and killed in
the town of Tissamaharana, also in the south. In the Akuressa
district, three supporters of the governing party were shot and
killed, officials said.
   The Sinhalese extremists have vowed to kill all supporters of
the peace plan aimed at ending the Tamil separatist war on the
island. They say it grants too many concessions to the minority
Tamils.
   The extremists have been blamed for the deaths of about 400
government officials and ruling party supporters since the accord
was signed July 29, 1987.
