<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SmellingSmoke     08-18 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smelling Smoke,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Girls Call Firefighters to Report Smelling Smoke</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUMTER, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters didn't believe a 12-year-old
girl and her sister when they reported smelling smoke, but the
girls wouldn't give up.
   It turned out the house next door was burning, and the neighbor
says the sisters saved her life.
   Cheryl Price called the Fire Department on Monday and reported
that her two daughters had called her to say they smelled smoke at
their home. Cybil, 12, and Laura, 9, were home alone and thought
their own house was burning.
   But when firefighters arrived, they could find no smoke or fire.
   ``The two little girls kept saying they could smell smoke, but
we couldn't find anything,'' Fire Chief Larry Causey said. ``They
contended that they smelled smoke and they were not going to give
up. They were very persistent on it.''
   Moments later, firefighters rushed into the house next door and
found Kay McDonagh asleep with a pot of chicken burning on her
stove. Neither of her two smoke detectors were working.
   ``I had been to Columbia, and when I came home I took some
medicine for a bronchial infection,'' Ms. McDonagh said. ``I put
some chicken on to boil and laid down to rest. The next thing I
know, 10 firemen are tromping into my house.''
   They arrived just in time, she said.
   Ms. McDonagh credited the girls with saving her life.
   ``If they hadn't been that caring and thoughtful, and if they
had waited until they saw flames, the smoke inhalation may have
gotten to me,'' she said. ``There's a very good possibility that I
may have died.''
</TEXT>
