<HEAD>Outdated Works Will Still Be Available in Libraries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Izvestia, which published a letter saying works of
some former Soviet leaders now in disfavor were being purged from
libraries, said Thursday they were only being moved and would be
readily available.
   The government newspaper was seeking to quiet a storm that arose
after the letter appeared Tuesday saying librarians were ordered to
take the works off their shelves.
   The letter, signed by I. Zavgorognyaya, said the Soviet Union
was creating new ``blank spots'' in its history by removing
information that should be in libraries regardless of the authors'
current political status.
   Among those mentioned were Leonid I. Brezhnev, whose tenure in
1964-1982 is being criticized by Mikhail S. Gorbachev's Kremlin as
a period of stagnation and corruption.
   Izvestia quoted the Ministry of Culture on Thursday as saying
few people were interested in reading the works of Brezhnev or
Konstantin U. Chernenko, who led the Soviet Union for a year and
was Gorbachev's immediate predecessor.
   According to Izvestia, the ministry said it could not use 40
percent of its library fund because there is no space for new books.
   Any books removed from the shelves will be provided to readers
``at their first demand,'' the newspaper said.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov told a regular
news briefing Thursday some libraries have dozens of copies of some
books, such as collected works of previous Soviet leaders.
   He said the libraries had been given permission to remove some
copies in order to make space for new books.
