<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Temptation-Officers     08-18 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Temptation-Officers,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deputy Constables, County Deputies Will Not Be Allowed To Work At
Theater</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chief deputy constable who banned officers in
his precinct from working off-duty security jobs at a theater
showing ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' said he did so because he
believes the movie is sacrilegious.
   Chief Deputy Constable Glen Cheek of Precinct 5 imposed the ban
for deputy constables earlier this week. The movie, which has
angered conservative Christian groups and caused protests in other
cities, opens Friday in Houston at one theater.
   ``I feel the film is simply in bad taste and sacrilegious, and I
just didn't want them working there,'' Cheek said.
   Cheek imposed the ban without consulting Constable Steve Radack,
who was in New Orleans for the Republican National Convention. But
Radack said Wednesday he supports the decision.
   ``It is my personal opinion that the movie is sacrilegious,''
Radack said.
   Constables are officers of the court who serve warrants and
other legal papers, and also have powers of arrest.
   The film by director Martin Scorsese, which has drawn good
crowds despite vehement protests, was scheduled to open in eight
more theaters across the country this weekend after opening in nine
last weekend.
   Because of the protests, officials of Cineplex Odeon's Spectrum
theater in west Houston sought extra security. When Cheek rejected
the request, the theater sought to hire Harris County deputies.
   However, Harris County Sheriff's Chief Deputy Tommy Thomas said
the theater was within Houston city limits and therefore not within
the jurisdiction of county authorities.
   Radack said he understood that one deputy from Precinct 5
normally works at the theater weekdays and two on weekends, but
that six had been requested for the opening of ``The Last
Temptation of Christ.''
   Houston Police Deputy Chief Bill Gaines said he was unsure
whether officers would be allowed to work at the theater.
   ``Normally, we would not let off-duty people work where there is
likely to be a confrontation or unruly crowds,'' Gaines said.
</TEXT>
