<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Train     08-18 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Train,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll Rises to 24, Speed Limit Reportedly Was Lifted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two people died of injuries suffered when a
passenger train speeding from Leningrad to Moscow derailed and
caught fire, raising the death toll to 24, a local official
reported on Thursday.
   Soviet media differed on the probable cause of the incident
Tuesday evening near Bologoye, about 180 miles northwest of Moscow.
   Tass news agency said a preliminary investigation indicated
Bologoye stationmaster V. Khrustalev prematurely raised a speed
limit imposed when inspectors discovered a deviation in the track.
   The government newspaper Izvestia said repairs had been
completed on the section of track, but were poorly done.
   Izvestia said 83 people remained hospitalized Thursday.
   Boris A. Petrov, deputy Communist Party head of the Kalinin
region where the accident occurred, said in a telephone interview
that two of the 107 people initially hospitalized after the crash
had died.
   Petrov said the only foreigners among the 760 passengers aboard
the Aurora were a group of 32 Brazilian tourists and that none of
them was hurt.
   An official of the Brazilian Embassy in Moscow, however,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said 34 Brazilians were aboard
and some suffered minor cuts from broken window glass.
   The route between Moscow and Leningrad, the Soviet Union's two
largest cities, is one of the busiest in the country, and trains
typically operate at capacity.
   Media reports said it is the only high-speed route in the Soviet
Union, normally posted for speeds of up to 120 mph.
   Tass said in a Russian-language report that three hours before
the accident, Khrustalev had removed a 60 kilometer-per-hour (just
over 37 mph) speed limit imposed a day earlier by an inspection
crew that had noticed a deviation of about one inch in the track.
   ``The motive for his decision still has to be clarified: whether
he received inaccurate information, or he himself thought that
there no longer was any danger. In either case, the repair work
carried out by senior engineer N. Gavrilov was not completed,''
Tass said.
   It said the locomotive engineer spotted the variation in the
track and tried to brake, but too late. The locomotive passed over
the spot but the passenger cars tore away and derailed.
   Fire broke out immediately and engulfed the train. Investigators
believe it was caused by leaking fuel from the restaurant car.
   Medical specialists from Moscow, Leningrad and other major
Soviet cities were flown into Bologoye to help, the reports said.
   About 15 trains were delayed in Moscow, stranding hundreds of
people. But in Leningrad buses took tourist groups to the airport
for a special flight to Moscow.
</TEXT>
