<HEAD>Moonshine Deaths Continue in Bombay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOMBAY, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six more people died Thursday after
drinking liquor spiked with methanol, bringing the death toll from
recent poisonings to 32, officials said.
   The number is expected to rise because at least 15 other people
are reported in critical condition at city hospitals.
   Two people who allegedly helped make the lethal brew were
arrested Thursday, bringing the number in custody in the case to
13, said Police Commissioner V.K. Saraf. No charges have been filed
yet.
   Police in the western state of Maharashtra are looking for the
man they believe sold the moonshine, Saraf said.
   Bombay, the capital of the western state of Maharashtra, has
more than 100 illegal distilleries, some large enough to make 220
gallons a day.
   A bottle of illicit liquor costs the equivalent of 72 cents, or
one-sixth the price of regular Indian whiskey.
