<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--$4MillionLunch     08-18 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--$4 Million Lunch,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RNC Gala Nets $4 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Republican Party raked in a whopping $4
million Thursday at an elaborately staged fund-raiser loaded with
lawmakers, corporate chiefs, all manner of celebrities _ and Leo
Nadeau.
   ``You're wondering: Who the hell is Leo Nadeau?'' the
silver-haired man on the stage at the New Orleans Convention Center
told approximately 4,500 mystified guests, most of whom paid $1,000
apiece for their seats.
   The answer: He was George Bush's tail-gunner 45 years ago, when
Bush served as a Navy pilot in the Pacific theater during World War
II. ``We were just a couple of kids,'' Nadeau said. ``But we became
men overnight.''
   Nadeau and other men and women _ wealthy ones, mostly _ honored
Bush and his running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana, at the
fund-raising luncheon, which the Republican National Committee
called one of its most successful ever.
   A final tally was not in, but spokeswoman Katherine Murray said
the event raised $4.2 million to $4.4 million for the committee's
operating budget, double what the RNC raised at its gala at the
1984 convention in Dallas.
   While it was the committee's best-ever showing for a
$1,000-per-plate event, it was not an overall fund-raising record.
The RNC pulled in $5.8 million at a higher-priced dinner-dance in
1984, Murray said.
   The luncheon was staged on a ``Road to Victory'' theme, with a
strip of black carpet leading from a huge mockup of a riverboat to
a mockup of The White House. Bush, Quayle and their wives arrived
in a antique fire engine led by a marching band; celebrities in the
audience ranged from Muhammad Ali to Sen. Strom Thurmond of South
Carolina.
   As well as the private and corporate donors who paid $1,000 per
seat, nine corporations underwrote the luncheon with $100,000
donations.
   Quayle, in his remarks, called the Republican Party ``the party
of the great middle class.'' And Bush rewarded the crowd with a
preview of his acceptance speech, saying he would seek to
illustrate the record of his opponent, Gov. Michael Dukakis, and to
lay out his own plans to take over from President Reagan.
   ``Tonight we shift gears. Tonight I will be the nominee, the
standard bearer, of this great party,'' he said. ``And I will spell
out, with clarity, where I want to lead the United States.''
   Bush also stressed his fidelity to Quayle, who was embroiled in
a controversy over whether he used family connections to join the
National Guard in 1969, at a time when he was eligible for the
Vietnam draft.
   For his part, Nadeau spoke of his and Bush's wartime experience
as he introduced the vice president.
   ``There are millions of Americans like me, men and women who've
seen the face of war,'' he said. ``When we elect our next commander
in chief, we will have made sure he is someone who has the courage
and experience we can depend on for our lives and our livelihoods.''
   Bush rose and hugged his old war buddy.
</TEXT>
