<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pakistan 3rdLd-Writethru a0764 08-18 0861</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0764,0883</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bodies of Zia, Other Victims Brought to Islamabad</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf `There have' to CORRECT spelling of Bahawalpur.
^LaserPhotos LON10,ISL2</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of President Mohammed Zia
ul-Haq was flown to Islamabad on Thursday while investigators
searched a sandy plain 330 miles away for causes of the air
disaster that killed him and the U.S. ambassador.
   A six-man honor guard gently lifted the coffin, draped in the
nation's green-and-white flag and chains of white flowers, from the
ramp of a C-130, the same type of U.S.-built military transport
that crashed Wednesday after taking off from the Bahawalpur airport.
   Killed with Zia were U.S. Ambassador Arnold Raphel; Brig. Gen.
Herbert M. Wassom, the Defense Department representative to
Pakistan; and 27 other people, including five ranking Pakistani
generals. They had witnessed a field trial of the M-1 tank, which
Pakistan is considering buying from the United States.
   Two more C-130s brought the bodies of the other victims to
Islamabad earlier in the day.
   There have been reports, none confirmed, that the crash was
caused by a bomb on board or an anti-aircraft missile. Rumors
spread that it was shot down by India, whose border is 80 miles
from Bahawalpur.
   Ghulam Ishaq Khan, the Senate chairman who became acting
president under the constitution, declared a state of emergency and
10 days of national mourning. He said Wednesday night that sabotage
could not be ruled out.
   Opposition political leaders were silent but there was some
rejoicing Thursday in Karachi, where Benazir Bhutto's Pakistan
People's Party has a large following. People carrying PPP flags
marched in small groups and party supporters distributed candy to
celebrate the end of Zia's 11-year rule.
   Ms. Bhutto, whose father Zulfikar Ali Bhutto was the prime
minister Zia overthrew in 1977 and had executed in 1979, said
Wednesday after the crash: ``Life and death is in the hands of God.
We will not say anything.''
   General calm was reported around the country. Government offices
were closed for three days, by order of Ishaq Khan, and most shops
did not open Thursday.
   United News of India quoted a ``highly-placed Pakistani military
official'' in New Delhi as saying the pilots of the four-engine
Hercules turboprop did not communicate with the control tower. UNI
quoted him as saying the explosion occurred about 40 seconds after
takeoff, probably in the cockpit.
   He said the pilots would have had time to contact the tower if
the plane had been hit by a missile, the UNI reported.
   At the scene in southeast Pakistan, a Pakistan army brigadier
who identified himself only as Zaidi said some witnesses reported
seeing the plane explode but others said it emitted smoke, lost
altitude and crashed.
   The main wreckage lay within a radius of 100 yards, and ``if it
burst in the air it would be spread over a large area,'' he said.
One wing was 1,000 yards away, however, and Zaidi said that was ``a
puzzle to investigators.''
   Pakistani and U.S. teams were searching for the flight recorder,
the ``black box.''
   Wreckage in the concentrated area was charred by fire but a copy
of the Koran, the holy book of Islam, had escaped the flames.
   At the Islamabad airport, weeping relatives walked in a measured
pace to meet the plane carrying the body of the president, who was
64 and a devout Moslem. Floodlights washed away the evening gloom.
   About 300 relatives and state officials, guarded by soldiers
with machine guns and sentries on rooftops, were at the airport to
receive Zia's coffin.
   Men stood in twos and threes, sobbing, with their arms around
one another. Cries and moans rose from the crowd.
   Soldiers formed a chain around the casket and mourners as they
moved slowly across the tarmac to a bus-sized ambulance.
   A state funeral for Zia, a close ally of the United States, is
scheduled for Saturday at a race course in the neighboring city of
Rawalpindi. Secretary of State George P. Shultz will attend.
   In Washington, officials said the United States was sending two
teams of experts to help investigate the crash.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley praised Ishaq Khan's
reaffirmation of Zia's domestic and foreign policies as ``firm
first steps,'' and said civil liberties had not been restricted
under the emergency.
   President Reagan said he will nominate Mrs. Oakley's husband,
57-year-old diplomat Robert B. Oakley, to replace Raphel as
ambassador to Pakistan.
   Letters of condolence arrived in Islamabad from world leaders,
including Reagan and Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi of India, with
which Pakistan has fought three wars since the subcontinent gained
independence from Britain in 1947.
   Three days of mourning were declared in India and in Bangladesh,
which was East Pakistan until a 1971 civil war in which India sided
with the secessionists.
   Some of the deepest sorrow was expressed by leaders of
Afghanistan's Moslem resistance, to which Zia gave unwavering
support.
   ``In the mountains of Afghanistan, commanders and mujahedeen
(guerrillas) hearing of his death will be very sad,'' said Masood
Khalili, spokesman for the Jamiat-i-Islami insurgents. ``No doubt
for all Afghans he was the greatest leader in the Islamic world.''
</TEXT>
