<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     08-18 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCEBURG, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Davy Crockett is more than the ``king
of the wild frontier'' to his descendants, who are meeting at a
state park that bears his name.
   ``David was quite a man in his time,'' said Joy Bland of Paris,
Tenn., a great-great-great-great-granddaughter of the Tennessee
pioneer. ``We think he made quite a contribution to our state in
many ways.''
   More than 100 people who have traced their roots to Crockett
began gathering at David Crockett State Park near here Thursday.
The reunion coincides with David Crockett Days, an annual festival.
   ``We want to keep the knowledge of him alive,'' Ms. Bland said.
``I learn something different every reunion.''
   To be a full member of the four-year-old Descendants of David
Crockett organization, people must trace their lineage to one of
Crockett's six children, two stepchildren or two wives. Those who
are simply interested in Crockett can join as associate members.
   The man who historians say called himself David, not Davy,
Crockett was born in northeast Tennessee on Aug. 17, 1786. He
represented the region as a state lawmaker and then was a
congressman in 1827-31 and 1833-35. He died in Texas defending the
Alamo in 1836.
   Ms. Bland said Crockett's record of public service often becomes
lost in the folklore surrounding him, but the frontiersman is
partly to blame.
   ``He liked to hunt, and he liked to talk about it,'' Ms. Bland
said. ``He only shot big bears.''
   Walt Disney Studios recently announced plans for a new
television series about Crockett. In the '50s, the orignal Disney
series starring Fess Parker had every kid in America wanting to
dress in coonskin.
   ``I really hope they will try to teach the public something
about the man that he was,'' said Ms. Bland. ``If children have
heroes today, it ought to be someone like him.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COLD SPRING HILLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The largest house on Long Island
has been sold for $22 million, or a bargain $170,000 for each of
its 130 rooms, a newspaper reported Thursday.
   Developer Gary Melius sold the Otto Kahn Mansion two weeks ago
to an unidentified Japanese businessman, according to Newsday.
   Melius confirmed the sale but told Newsday he had signed a
non-disclosure clause. The newspaper said it learned the selling
price from a source close to the deal.
   Melius, who bought the house in 1984 for $1.5 million and spent
millions more restoring it, said he was selling it at the request
of his wife, dropping plans to turn it into condos, a tennis club
or health spa.
   ``It was too much money and too much time,'' he said. ``It was
consuming us.''
   The mansion, built on 443 acres overlooking Cold Spring Harbor,
was dubbed Oheka by its first owner, Otto Herman Kahn. It was
second largest house in the nation at the time of construction.
   The home was sold in 1938 to the New York City Sanitation
Department as a weekend retreat for employees. It was a government
training center during World War II and later was a private
military academy.
   Melius' original asking price was $52 million with complete
renovations. He estimated that there was still $8 million to $15
million worth of restoration work still to be done.
</TEXT>
