<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Robertson-Quayle     08-18 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Robertson-Quayle,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Defends Quayle's Military Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former presidential candidate Pat Robertson
on Thursday said controversy swirling around Republican vice
presidential pick Dan Quayle's military service is
``reprehensible.''
   ``I think we've got to give him a break,'' Robertson said. ``He
served six years in a branch of service and it was honorable
service.''
   Robertson's comments came as he toured state delegations from
Iowa and Minnesota, and was questioned by reporters about the
Quayle controversy.
   Quayle is being dogged by reports that influential family
members interceded on his behalf to obtain a slot in the National
Guard in 1969, during an era when the guard was frequently used as
a method of avoiding the draft and service in Vietnam.
   Robertson is no stranger to controversy over military service.
   California Rep. Paul McCloskey, who served with Robertson during
the Korean War alleged that Robertson's father, a U.S. senator,
used his influence to keep Robertson from being posted in a combat
zone.
   ``The National Guard is not something to be ashamed of,''
Robertson said Thursday. ``I think the National Guard is honorable.
I think the Army Reserve is honorable.''
