<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Parties     08-18 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Parties,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Party Prices: Faraway Views, $1,000; Large Sodas, $1</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Will be topped</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-CVN--Convention Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT CHARTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans could lay out $1,000 for a
festive but faraway look at the national ticket on their
convention's closing day, but many opted for cheaper thrills.
   Vice President George Bush and Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle, a day
into their formal anointment as the GOP's top twosome, rode an
antique fire truck into the New Orleans Convention Center for
Thursday's big-ticket luncheon.
   ``Wasn't it thoughtful _ they gave us these little binoculars at
the door,'' said Bertha Bajorek of Metairie, La., who sat at the
most distant table from the podium in the mammoth center.
   She focused the small red magnifiers toward the wide head table,
and, ever-faithful, said it was a fine view. ``Of course, it's hard
to make out details,'' she said.
   At the next table, Nevada Rep. Barbara Vucanovich said she
didn't mind the long-distance luncheon with the candidates. ``We
can actually carry on a conversation back here without all the
noise,'' she said, gesturing to three House colleagues at her round
table. ``We're not on parade ourselves when we're this far out.''
   Sure enough, hoards of photographers converged on tables with
celebrants who looked remotely famous.
   Robed singers from Greater St. Stephen Baptist Church rocked
from a stage at one end of the exhibition hall; across the way, an
orchestra's instruments rested in readiness for a fanfare.
   The nominees and their wives rolled into the hall aboard the
Terrytown Volunteer Fire Department's restored 1927 Ahrens-Fox
truck, which worked blazes in New Orleans for 41 years. ``We've
been polishing it for days,'' said Dan Dauterive, its regular
driver, who temporarily lost his job to a Secret Service agent.
   About 4,000 people consumed beef tenderloin and sliced chicken
breast with tarragon during the luncheon, which was aimed at
raising $4 million in one lick.
   Less-extravagant delegates explored the French Quarter, a dozen
blocks from the convention center but light-years from hometown
ways. ``That Bush-Quayle luncheon, that's not quite our economic
bracket,'' said David Barkhausen, an Illinois delegate. Shucking
pinstripes for walking shorts, he paid a hot dog vendor $1 for a
soda, then headed down Bourbon Street.
   ``It's been difficult to get down here during the convention.
It's been an exhausting week,'' Barkhausen said. ``Besides, there
have been a lot of free diversions.''
   And that has bartenders and restaurant employees peeved.
   ``We've lost business,'' said Bobby Moore, a bartender at a tiny
saloon. The bar and an adjacent restaurant have laid off four
workers and closed an upstairs dining room since last weekend
because of sluggish business, he said.
   ``Oh, they've spent a little. But you can only make so much from
Perrier and Coca-Cola,'' Moore said.
   Catherine Clement, a New York delegate, said she headed to the
French Quarter for the first time on Thursday. ``I've spent a few
dollars,'' she said, ``but I haven't had time to spend a lot.''
   J. Garfield DeMarco, a New Jersey delegate, balanced himself
against a wrought-iron fence as fast-talking Emanuel Gaines
smoothed polish on his black shoes. The shine cost $5. But Gaines
plays a game with customers: ``I'll shine your shoes for $5, but
it'll be free if I can't guess where you got them,'' he sings.
``But if I guess where you got 'em, that's double the price _ and
maybe a tip.''
   DeMarco didn't bite. What's the answer? ``You got them on your
feet!'' Gaines exclaimed.
   ``I'm going to have to recruit you to help raise money for the
party,'' DeMarco told Gaines.
</TEXT>
