<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan-Floods     08-18 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan-Floods,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diseases Spread, One Cholera Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sewage networks have burst and contaminated
water in Khartoum, the capital of Sudan, and up to a million people
are threatened with deadly disease in the aftermath of devastating
floods, a Cairo daily said Friday.
   Government authorities and international relief agencies in
Sudan were reported to have stepped up efforts Thursday to fight
more than 5,000 cases of disease caught by drinking unclean water.
   The Egyptian state-run newspaper al-Ahram, quoting unspecified
sources, said in its early Friday edition that one person had died
of cholera in Omdurman, across the Nile River from Khartoum.
   Egyptian television said in a Thursday evening newscast that the
Sudanese Red Crescent reported 5,211 people as suffering from
severe diarrhea, 70 percent of them young children.
   The television said Sudanese health authorites and international
agencies identified the cases as typhoid, malaria and cholera and
increased their efforts to treat them.
   The Red Crescent is the equivalent in Moslem countries to the
Red Cross.
   Dr. Nicholas Ward, a World Health Organization adviser,
predicted earlier that 400,000 people, most of them under five
years of age, would develop diarrhea and gastro-intestinal
diseases, and 4,000 of them probably would die.
   Left untreated, as many as 40,000 people could perish, Ward
predicted.
   Ward, a diarrheal diseases and immunization specialist, went to
Sudan from his base in North Yemen to help coordinate the
government's response to the crisis resulting from the floods.
   He said the government recruited 300 doctors and medical
students for about 120 emergency clinics and increased staff at 127
existing health units.
   The price of water soared to 10 times its previous level since
the floods. Those unable to pay have had to drink from huge,
brackish pools left behind by the rainstorms and contaminated by
human waste from broken sewer pipes and swamped pit latrines.
   Torrential rains Aug. 4-5 left more than 1.5 people homeless. In
Khartoum alone, 70 people died, 213 were injured and nearly 115,000
houses were destroyed. Another 21 people perished in accidents
caused by the floods, bringing the known death toll to 91.
   International relief poured in from the United States, Europe
and Arab countries. But Osman Omar, Sudan's minister of public
works, was quoted by Egypt's state-run Middle East News Agency
quoted as saying Thursday that the amounts flown in met only 5
percent of needs.
   Distribution of relief supplies, handled by the government, has
been slow. Many affected areas in central, eastern and northern
Sudan were isolated.
   Officials previously denied accusations that the government was
witholding relief from some of those affected, and compared the aid
to a ``drop in the ocean.''
   Omar stressed that any foreign relief would continue to be
chaneled through the government. ``The government is capable of
bearing its responsibilities without any outside advice or
intervention,'' MENA quoted him as saying.
   Besides flood relief scenes, Egyptian TV also showed swarms of
locusts covering the sky in western Sudan, a potential threat to
any remaining crops if the locusts flew on to central Sudan.
</TEXT>
