<HEAD>'87 Syphilis Rate Matches 37-Year High</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd-4th grafs, bgng `Reported U.S....', with 3 grafs to
add 1985 rate, 1986 estimate, picking up 5th graf pvs, `The
rate...'. INSERTS 1 graf after 10th graf pvs, `The increases...',
to add comment from researcher, picking up 11th graf, `The increase
....' For release 6:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States' syphilis rate last year was as
bad as any since 1950, prompting federal health officials to call
Thursday for more emphasis on interviewing patients with venereal
diseases and warning their sex partners.
   Final statistics for 1987 show 35,241 cases of syphilis reported
in the United States _ 14.6 per 100,000 people, equaling the 1982
rate as the highest since 1950's rate of 16.7, the national Centers
for Disease Control reported.
   Reported U.S. cases of syphilis have risen 30 percent in two
years, from 27,143 or 11.5 per 100,000 in 1985, the CDC said. The
number of cases in 1986 was not included in the report but was
estimated at 28,500.
   ``The increase ... was greatest for blacks and Hispanics _
groups for which incidence rates were already high,'' the
Atlanta-based agency said in its weekly report.
   Between 1986 and 1987, among Americans 15-64, the syphilis rate
for black males rose 36 percent, from 106 per 100,000 people to
145; the rate for black females shot up 43 percent, from 56 per
100,000 to 79.
   The rate for Hispanic males rose 7 percent, from 66 to 71 cases
per 100,000, while the rate for Hispanic women rose 24 percent,
from 18 to 22.
   In contrast, the rate for white males dropped from 6.4 to 5.7
cases per 100,000 _ apparently due to a drop in syphilis among
homosexual men _ and the rate for white females rose, but still at
small levels, from 2.2 to 2.6, the CDC said.
   Previously reported drops in the sexually transmitted disease
rates among homosexual men indicate ``changes in sexual behavior''
due to the spread of AIDS, the CDC said.
   ``The increases in incidence of syphilis ... suggest that
efforts to achieve similar behavioral changes in minority
populations have not been successful,'' the agency said.
   ``Homosexual men ... have taken `safe sex' messages seriously,''
said Dr. Joel Greenspan, a CDC specialist in sexually transmitted
diseases. ``They have changed their behavior. Minority people, and
particularly heterosexuals, have not gotten that message.''
   The increase in syphilis appears to be concentrated in a few
urban areas; 57 percent of all U.S. cases last year were reported
in Florida, California and New York.
   In its report, the CDC suggested several steps to curb the
increase in syphilis, including a move to ``re-emphasize the
traditional methods of syphilis control _ interviews and sex
partner notification.''
   The agency also suggested screening for sexually transmitted
diseases in high-risk populations, assuring better access to
medical care with speedy service and evening hours, and further
surveillance efforts to monitor the problem.
</TEXT>
