<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material; Bush speech EMBARGOED for delivery expected
9:50 edt; Barbara Bush EMBARGOED for 9:15 pm EDT; 1st Add to follow
may stand.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush formally launched his quest for
the White House Thursday night, depicting himself as the underdog
in the race against Michael Dukakis and pledging to ``run hard, to
fight hard, to stand on the issues.
   ``And I mean to win,'' he told the Republican National
Convention.
   Bush crafted his prime-time acceptance speech as his high
command sought to quell a controversy over running mate Dan
Quayle's Vietnam-era stint in the National Guard. ``I'm proud to
have Dan Quayle at my side,'' said Bush.
   The script for the convention's final session called for
Quayle's nomination, followed by the 41-year-old senator's
acceptance speech, followed by Bush's turn at the Superdome podium
_ followed by one more spectacular blizzard of balloons.
   He began his prepared speech with a self-deprecating promise,
saying, ``I'll try to keep my charisma in check.'' And the son of a
wealthy and influential Connecticut family fashioned himself an
everyman, talking of his days living in a ``little shotgun house''
in Texas, where he ``lived the dream _ high school football on
Friday night, Little League, neighborhood barbeque.''
   ``I am a quiet man,'' he said. He said he wouldn't attack
Dukakis by name, but that didn't stop him from going after his
rival.
   ``...My opponent won't rule out raising taxes, But I will,''
Bush said in a speech that assailed Dukakis' policies without
mentioning the Democratic nominee by name.
   ``Congress will push me to raise taxes, and I'll say no, and
they'll push and I'll say no, and they'll push again. And all I can
say to them is no new taxes, period.''
   Bush's wife Barbara preceded her husband to the convention
podium, continuing a Bush emphasis on family to match Dukakis' in
Atlanta last month. She praised her partner of 43 years as a ``man
who is as strong and caring and decent as America herself.''
   Vice presidential aides passed the word that there would be no
news conference about Quayle and questions over whether strings
were pulled two decades ago to ease his way into the Indiana
National Guard and avoid almost certain service in Vietnam.
   Campaign chairman James A. Baker III previously promised a
``full disclosure,'' and said, ``We are continuing to explore it''
with Quayle.
   Dukakis campaigned in Miami, where he sidestepped questions
about Quayle, but said he was proud to have served in the Army in
Korea.
   GOP convention week polls charted a dwindling Democratic lead in
the fall campaign as Bush addressed the delegates and a TV audience
of millions.
   ``I'm the one'' who favors the death penalty in certain drug
cases, he said. ``I'm the one'' who opposes giving as weekend
furlough to a first degree murderer.''
   An ebullient Bush spent his day making the rounds of the
convention city, introducing his wife Barbara to one audience as
``sweetie pie.'' The party raised $4 million at a fundraiser at
which the ticketmates lashed out against Democratic ``failed
liberal.''
   In his prepared remarks, Bush said America was at peace and
prosperous after ``two great terms'' under Ronald Reagan. Now a
change in leadership will be made, he said, adding, ``When you have
to change horses in midstream, doesn't it make sense to switch to
the one who who's going the same way?''
   Bush sought to turn Dukakis' Democratic convention rhetoric back
on him. Dukakis said the election wasn't about ideology, but about
competence, and Bush saw an opening.
   ``Well it's nice of them to want to play on our field,'' he
said. ``But this election isn't only about competence, for
competence is a narrow ideal. Competence makes the trains run on
time, but doesn't know where they're going. Competence is the creed
of the technocrat who makes sure the gears mesh but doesn't for a
second understand the magic of the machine.''
   Said Bush:
   ``Two parties this year ask for your support. Both will speak of
growth and peace. But only one has proved it can deliver. Two
parties this year ask for your trust, but only one has earned it.''
   The vice president said the night marked the beginning of his
campaign.
   ``I mean to run hard, to fight hard, to stand on the issues, and
I mean to win.''
   
   MORE
</TEXT>
