<HEAD>GOP TV Ratings Drop Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORELANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television ratings for the Republican
National Convention dropped again Wednesday night, and ABC easily
outdistanced its two rivals for the largest share of the dwindling
audience.
   The A.C. Nielsen Co. reported that ABC had an average rating of
8.7 on the night Vice President George Bush secured the party's
presidential nomination. NBC and CBS tied with ratings of 6.7.
   The three-network total of 16.7 was down from 19.9 on Monday and
17.6 on Tuesday. By contrast, the third night of the Democratic
National Convention drew a cumulative rating of 22.1.
   Each rating point represents 866,000 homes with television.
   For the first three nights of the GOP convention, the three
networks' average rating is 18.1, compared to 21.0 for the first
three nights of the Democratic gathering in Atlanta.
</TEXT>
