<2ND_LINE>AM-Lottery Jackpot,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Twelve Co-Workers Split $20 Million ``Super Lotto'' Jackpot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE McDONALD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winning a $20 million lottery brings a sense of
freedom, 12 industrial workers are learning.
   Fred Bird, 40, of Painesville, one of the winning workers at
Kennametal Inc. in Solon, said he was no longer interested in
winning the prizes the company gives to workers who are on time
every day for a year.
   ``Now they can give their toasters to somebody else,'' he said.
   Bird and his 11 co-workers each contributed $2 for 24 chances at
the prize. One of their plays, selected randomly by the lottery's
computer, turned up the winning combination Wednesday: 12, 17, 25,
26, 32 and 36.
   The prize will be paid out over 20 years, with each winner's
annual share amounting to $66,666.67 after taxes.
   ``I figured sooner or later we'd get it,'' said Matt Goodlin,
48, of Mentor, who bought the winning ticket.
   Members of the group over the years had spent several thousand
dollars to buy lottery tickets, Goodlin said. They bet $700 in
January on a record $32 million ``Super Lotto'' drawing.
   Goodlin and some of the others in his group went to work
Thursday morning to announce their triumph.
   ``They already knew by the time we got there. Somebody told
them. Most of them were very happy,'' Goodlin said.
   Robert Repas, 34, of Maple Heights, said he joined the ``Super
Lotto'' group just five weeks ago. Repas, whose wife had a baby
three days ago, said his share of the winnings would help with new
family expenses.
   Jimmy Robins, 49, of Willoughby, said that as soon as the
winning numbers were announced, he knew the group had won.
   ``I called Matt, then Matt started calling. That started the
whole chain reaction, and by the time it was over with, everybody
was up half the night,'' Robins said.
   Except for Kenneth Stephens, 48, of Chardon, the co-workers said
they plan to keep their jobs, which pay from 25,000 to $28,000 a
year. Stephens said he was considering resigning from Kennametal.
   ``I've got some money now,'' he said.
</TEXT>
