<HEAD>College Board OKs Lease for Black Fraternity House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state College Board on Thursday
approved a two-year lease for a black fraternity to move into a
vacant building on the all-white fraternity row at the University
of Mississippi.
   The 20-member black fraternity, Phi Beta Sigma, had been
restoring a building along the same street, but the structure was
torched by arsonists Aug. 4.
   The lease agreement will allow the black fraternity to move into
the building that once housed the Phi Kappa Theta fraternity.
   ``We think that hopefully, by the first of October, the Phi Beta
Sigmas will be in there,'' Ole Miss Chancellor Gerald Turner said
of the renovation project.
   Renovation of the Phi Kappa Theta house is expected to cost
$15,000 to $20,000, all paid for by private funds, officials said.
