<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 2147EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CDC--Briefs     08-18 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CDC--Briefs,0312</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The effectiveness of last winter's influenza
vaccine may have been reduced by a mid-season drift in the
predominant flu virus, federal health researchers concluded in a
report on the 1987-88 season.
   Health officials reported late last year that the predominant
strain of flu, A-H3N2 _ one of the three major flu types _ appeared
to be ``drifting,'' or changing into a somewhat different form.
   ``Because these variations were not recognized until the fall of
1987, the ... influenza vaccine (which contains vaccine against all
three major types) could not be modified to include the new
variant,'' the national Centers for Disease Control said Thursday
in its weekly report.
   ``As a result, the efficacy of the vaccine, at least in certain
high-risk persons, may have been reduced,'' the agency concluded.
   CDC officials earlier this spring said the recommended 1988-89
flu vaccine should contain a new formula to better protect against
the new A-H3N2 strain, known as the Sichuan flu.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three recent outbreaks of food poisoning in the
Northeast apparently were caused by Salmonella bacteria in Grade A
eggs, federal health officials said Thursday.
   The Centers for Disease Control reported outbreaks of
gastro-intestinal illness among:
   _at least 88 students in May at a Fort Monmouth, N.J., prep
school, where ice cream made with raw eggs was served;
   _at least 47 people in a training session held in June at an
Asbury Park, N.J., hotel, where scrambled eggs were served;
   _at least 12 restaurant patrons at a May brunch at a Livonia,
N.Y., restaurant, where omelets were served.
   The CDC, as is its custom, did not identify the specific
locations involved. The outbreaks were caused by Salmonella
enteritidis, a common Salmonella bacteria, researchers reported.
   Investigations found no improper food handling, the CDC said.
</TEXT>
