<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen Kill Catholic Worker in Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two masked gunmen killed a
Roman Catholic worker renovating a house Thursday, police reported,
and British soldiers defused a letter bomb sent to a leading
Protestant politician.
   The gunmen walked into a house Belfast and fired at close range,
striking 32-year-old Michael Laverty in the head and chest, a
police spokesman said. No group claimed responsibility.
   Laverty, a surveyor, was renovating the house, the spokesman
said, on condition of anonymity in keeping with official policy.
The slain man was from Stewartstown, County Tyrone, about 50 miles
west of Belfast, police said.
   On Wednesday, two gunmen entered a grocery store in a Protestant
enclave in west Belfast and killed the 44-year-old owner, Frederick
Otley.
   The Irish Republican Brigade, previously unknown in the British
province's secretarian warfare, claimed responsibility.
   In 1985, an informer accused Otley of terrorist crimes on behalf
of the Protestant paramilitary Ulster Volunteer Force. He was
charged with a bombing meant to kill a force member during an
internal feud, but the charges were dropped when the informer
recanted.
   The Irish Republican Army has been fighting to drive the British
from the Protestant-dominated province and unite it with the
overwhelmingly Catholic Irish Republic. Militant Protestant groups
also attack Catholics. The parcel bomb was sent to Ken Maginnis,
the Official Unionist Party's security spokesman who represents
Northern Ireland in the British Parliament.
   A similar packet sent two weeks ago to the Rev. William McCrea,
another member of Parliament from Northern Ireland, also was
defused.
   Maginnis said he called the bomb disposal squad after the
package arrived at his home in Dungannon, County Tyrone, 40 miles
west of Belfast.
   ``For some reason I felt uncomfortable,'' he said. ``I saw
something attached to the parcel _ I am not saying what _ and I
called the anti-terrorist officers.
   ``People in political and public life have got to realize the
terrorists are prepared to kill not only them, but also members of
their families.''
   Police said the parcel, about the size of a cigar box, contained
commercial explosives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
