<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Quayle-Honorary     08-18 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Quayle-Honorary,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honorary Degree for Quayle From Alma Mater Was Initially Opposed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 1982 dispute about an honorary degree for
Sen. Dan Quayle was rooted in faculty members' dislike of Quayle's
conservative politics, the former president of DePauw University
said Thursday.
   ``There was real strong sentiment about Quayle because he was a
conservative Republican,'' Richard F. Rosser said. ``I didn't care
if he was a Democrat or Republican. At that time, at his age, he
was holding the highest public position of any DePauw alumnus.''
   On Thursday night, Quayle was unopposed for the Republican vice
presidential nomination.
   Faculty members initially rejected Rosser's request to give
Quayle, a 1969 graduate of the small liberal arts college in
Greencastle, Ind., an honorary doctor of laws at the 1982 spring
commencement, where he was the featured speaker.
   The faculty later relented and approved the degree.
   Faculty members argued against the honorary degree by claiming
Quayle, then 35, was too young and had unimpressive public service
and academic records, DePauw professor O. Ralph Raymond said in an
interview Wednesday.
   ``It wasn't that his career was undistinguished, it was just
that it was such a short career,'' said Raymond, a specialist on
Soviet affairs, who opposed the degree award.
   ``Certainly there were some people quite bothered by the fact
that we were honoring a person whose intellectual achievements were
unimpressive. We like to see students achieve a little bit more
than he did.''
   Rosser, now president of the National Association of Independent
Colleges and Universities in Washington, D.C., conceded Thursday
that Quayle ``was no Phi Beta Kappa. He was not a distinguished
student.''
   DePauw has refused to provide Quayle's college records.
   However, Rosser said Quayle's academic performance shouldn't
have been an issue after his graduation. Quayle was being
recognized for public service, Rosser said.
   The degree spat was followed by another embarrassment for Quayle
when the two student radio reporters who broke the story were
fired. Their student boss said they had reported on what Rossner
said was an off-the-record meeting.
   Quayle, who once worked as a reporter at his father's newspaper,
wrote to the university to urge the reporters' reinstatement,
saying the firings ``could have a chilling effect on freedom of the
press.'' DePauw was the birthplace of the Society of Profession
Journalists, Sigma Delta Chi.
   The students did not get their jobs back, Raymond said.
</TEXT>
