<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heat Relief In Upper Midwest; Records Fall In Carolinas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front stretching from the central Plains to the
mid-Atlantic Coast states brought heat relief Thursday to the Great
Lakes and mid-Mississippi Valley, but records continued to fall in
the lower Ohio Valley and the Carolinas.
   The high of 105 in Raleigh, N.C., tied the all-time high in more
than a century of record-keeping set on July 23, 1952. Greensboro,
N.C., also tied its all-time high with a 102 reading.
   Records for the date were set or tied in Cape Hatteras, N.C.,
93; Charlotte, N.C. 100; Greer, S.C., 101; Lynchburg, Va., 98;
Louisville, Ky., 99; and Roanoke, Va., 96. Earlier in the week,
records were falling across a far wider area stretching as far west
as Minnesota and Iowa.
   Rain finally ended in southern Michigan, where strong
thunderstorms had produced severe weather. Some of the rainfall
totals Wednesday and Thursday topped the 2-inch mark.
   At Lansing, the rainfall for the month of August now totals 4.05
inches, almost twice as much as fell in the months of May, June and
July combined.
   In central Wisconsin, storms brought more than an inch of
rainfall at Coon Valley, and nearly an inch near La Crosse.
Lightning strikes were blamed for power outages in the area. A
thunderstorm watch was posted for parts of northern and central
Illinois.
   In New Jersey, residents cleaned up Thursday from violent storms
that felled trees, knocked down a 30 foot-high circus tent and
disrupted power to more than 90,000 customers.
   The storms Wednesday spawned a tornado with winds up to 140 mph
that left a path of destruction four miles long and a quarter-mile
wide in Trenton. The twister moved cars a dozen feet, ripped up
roofs and toppled trees.
   A 28-year-old migrant worker was struck by lightning as he
worked in a pepper field and remained hospitalized in critical
condition Thursday. In Lavallette, 14 people suffered minor
injuries when the circus tent came down in high winds.
   Thunderstorms also produced brief, heavy rains along the Gulf
Coast region, with Galveston, Texas, getting more than one-third
inch of rain in only 15 minutes.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included 1.95 inches at New Orleans, La.; 0.94 inch at Corpus
Christi, Texas; 0.80 inch at Sioux City, Iowa; 0.65 inch at Wausau,
Wis.; and 0.57 inch at McAllen, Texas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 62
degrees at Caribou, Maine, to 106 degrees at Needles, Calif. The
early-morning low for the nation was 31 degrees at Truckee, Calif.
   The forecast for Friday called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms along a weakening cold front extending from western
Kansas across the southern Ohio Valley to the mid-Atlantic Coast
states; and storms also in parts of Oklahoma, Texas, the Gulf Coast
region, the northern Plains and southern Plateau.
   Higs in the 70s were forecast along the Pacific Coast and
Washington state, and in the northern Mississippi Valley, the Great
Lakes and much of New England; between 95 and 100 in central Texas,
Oklahoma, Mississippi, the Tennessee Valley and South Carolina;
between 100 and 110 in the desert Southwest and the valleys of
California; and in the 80s and 90s in most of the rest of the
nation.
</TEXT>
