<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Colombia-Americans     08-18 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Americans,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Americans Held Captive in Colombia Return Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLIFF EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men held captive by Colombian rebels for 10
months said Thursday they tended gardens, played chess and picked
the banjo with their captors, but still longed for their freedom.
   Jason McLachan, 21, and Stephan Koneman, 22, met with reporters
at a hotel near O'Hare International Airport for a morning news
conference. They were reunited with their families Wednesday night.
   ``The hardest part was waiting to be freed,'' said McLachan.
``For us, it's something that happened in our lives and we're glad
it's over.''
   The two men, both geography majors, were canoeing down the
Amazon River last fall when they were captured by members of a
leftist rebel group who believed them to be CIA agents, said Elmer
Koneman, Stephan's father. The two were taken captive Oct. 4.
   McLachan said the rebels _ men and women of varying ages _ never
mistreated them, but kept them isolated at different camps in the
Amazon jungle. The rebels carried handguns and kept their captives
under constant supervision.
   ``A lot of people had been saying we disappeared,'' McLachan
said. ``For us, it was everyone else who disappeared.''
   The rebels, members of the Colombian Revolutionary Armed Forces,
held the two until Sunday, Koneman said.
   Their release was announced earlier this week.
   McLachan said their captors ``wanted to know what these two
gringos were doing down there.'' After talking with the rebels, the
students convinced them they were not political agents.
   ``My Spanish is now `muy bien,''' he said. ``But without Steve,
it (captivity) would have been more difficult.''
   Koneman, recalling the rebels' camp in the jungle, said there
was no way to determine whether the guerillas had attacked anyone
or were selling drugs.
   ``Probably the two of us were the most bizarre thing there,'' he
said, referring to their white skins.
   Koneman and McLachan said they were in good health, and had
never feared for their lives.
   ``It never got tense that way,'' McLachan said.
   But after 10 months of a diet that included alligators, toucans
and piranha fish, the two agreed that a homecoming hamburger was in
order.
   Koneman's father said earlier the families had all but given up
hope.
   ``We basically went through a period where for so long we felt
that all was lost,'' he said Wednesday. ``It's a marvelous
resurrection.''
   ``It wasn't until I saw him on television yesterday that I
really thought, `My God, this guy is coming home,''' he said.
   A Roman Catholic bishop negotiated with the rebels for four or
five months before gaining the young men's release.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
