<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Quayle-Veterans 1stLd-Writethru a0745 08-18 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Quayle-Veterans, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0745,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vets Group Says Members Upset By Quayle Military Record</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Subs 3rd graf pvs with 4 grafs new comment. Picks up 4th graf
pvs, ``A lot xxxx''
^By WILLIAM M. WELCH</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The spokesman for the Vietnam Veterans of
America said Thursday that National Guard service was regarded as
``cushy duty'' to avoid the draft and that questions about Dan
Quayle's military service were relevant.
   Mike Leaveck, director of public relations for the Vietnam
Veterans of America, said his organization has received several
dozen calls from members ``upset'' about revelations about Quayle's
National Guard record.
   But at least one Medal of Honor winner from the Vietnam War said
criticism of Quayle and the National Guard is ``a bum rap.''
   ``Four of my very close friends in the National Guard were
killed in Vietnam,'' said George ``Bud'' Day, a retired Air Force
colonel and former prisoner of war from Fort Walton Beach, Fla.
   ``These guys that went to the Guard were very good guys. They
got in there and served their country,'' said Day, who headed
Veterans for Reagan in 1984. ``I applaud this guy. If that's the
worst thing they can dig up on this guy, they should make him
president.''
   Leaveck, in a telephone interview from the group's Washington
headquarters, said ``Questions about what did you do during the
Vietnam War, we think, are very relevant for anyone in public life,
particularly of our generation.''
   
   
   ``A lot of people served in the National Guard during those
years, a lot of them served in the National Guard in order to avoid
military service in Vietnam. That's a well known, accepted fact. We
can't comment on what his motivations may have been. ... A lot of
people went into the National Guard because they liked it.''
   But, he added, ``actually the National Guard was considered
cushy duty. ... We've had a lot of calls from our members who are
upset.''
   However, a spokesman for the American Legion said he was
concerned that the impression will be conveyed that National Guard
service is ``somehow dishonorable.'' John Minnick, Legion spokesman
in Washington, said the Guard was important for national defense
and also in domestic emergencies.
   But Minnick said Quayle's military service was ``a legitimate
issue.''
   Leaveck described Quayle as ``non-supportive'' of his group's
position on veterans issues. He said in particular Quayle opposed
continuation of veterans' counseling center program, opposed
compensation for diseases related to Agent Orange exposure, and has
not supported legislation allowing court review of Veterans
Administration benefit decisions, which the VVA backs but some
other veterans groups oppose.
   The VVA has 35,000 memers, is congressionally chartered and
composed entirely of Vietnam veterans.
   The American Legion, the largest veterans group with nearly 3
million members, including 800,000 Vietnam veterans. It is based in
Indianapolis, Ind., Quayle's home state. Minnick said service in
the Guard was not sufficient to qualify for membership in the
American Legion, and that Quayle is not eligible, while Bush and
Democrat Michael Dukakis are.
</TEXT>
