<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--BushonBush 1stLd-Writethru a0828 08-18 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Bush on Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0828,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush: `I Hear The Quiet People Others Don't'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Following embargoed for release on delivery; about 9:50 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts dropped word `his' in 1st graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush used the most important speech of
his life Thursday night to portray himself to the American people
as a man who may ``sometimes be a little awkward,'' who is
reserved, but who nevertheless can lead a nation.
   ``What it all comes down to, after all the shouting and the
cheers, is the man at the desk and who should sit at the desk,''
said Bush.
   ``My friends, I am that man.''
   Accepting his party's nomination for president, Bush defined his
vision for the job, but also sought to expose the inner man. By
doing so, he indirectly attacked the images attached to him.
   The image of Bush, the boring speaker:
   ``I may not be the most eloquent, but I learned early that
eloquence won't draw oil from the ground. I may sometimes be a
little awkward, but there's nothing self-conscious in my love of
country.
   ``I am a quiet man but I hear the quiet people others don't.''
   The wimp image:
   ``My life has been lived in the shadow of war _ I almost lost my
life in one. I hate war. I love peace. We have peace. And I am not
going to let anyone take it away from us.''
   The rich-kid image _ evoked at the Democratic convention by
keynote speaker Ann Richards, of Bush's being ``born with a silver
foot in his mouth.''
   ``My parents were prosperous; their children were lucky,'' Bush
said. ``But there were lessons we had to learn about life.'' He
learned them, he said, by moving to Texas where he ``lived in a
little shotgun house, one room for the three of us. Worked in the
oil business, started my own...''
   Bush said certain traditions guide him.
   ``One is that there is a God and He is good, and His love, while
free, has a self imposed cost: We must be good to one another,''
Bush said.
   And he said:
   ``I believe public service is honorable. Every time I hear that
someone has breached the public trust, it breaks my heart ...
   ``I want a kinder, gentler nation ...
   ``I say it without boast or bravado; I've fought for my country,
I've served, I've built ...I will keep America moving forward,
always forward... That is my mission. And I will complete it.''
</TEXT>
