<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0692 08-18 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0692,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Refuses To Hit Quayle On Military Service</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: To update SUBS lead, grafs 4-5; INSERTS one graf after 15th
graf bgng ``I'm definitely ... '' to show arrival in Dallas and
meeting with Jackson supporters.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede LONGVIEW, Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Lloyd Bentsen pressed his vice
presidential campaign among conservative oil-country businessmen
and then to Jesse Jackson supporters Thursday, and he refused to
criticize Republican counterpart Dan Quayle's service in the
National Guard during the Vietnam war.
   ``I'm not going to question that,'' said Bentsen, a World War II
bomber pilot. ``I'm a strong supporter of the National Guard and
always have been. One of my own sons served in the National Guard.''
   Bentsen passed up the chance to criticize Quayle over reports
that George Bush's vice presidential running mate sought to enter
the Indiana National Guard in 1969 and avoid being drafted for
active duty in Vietnam.
   Instead, the senator and former Houston businessman sought to
explain to his East Texas audiences about his dual candidacies _ as
Michael Dukakis' running mate and for re-election to the Senate. He
reassured them he would remain committed to advancing their
business interests if he is elected vice president on the ticket
with Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis.
   In a speech before the East Texas Regional Development Group in
Longview, Bentsen said he rejected the ``old shibboleths'' about
the vice presidency being an unimportant job. ``Now the vice
president is in the loop,'' he said.
   Bentsen shook hands as he strolled down the main street of the
oil city of Kilgore, starting at Larry Tate's stripper well and
ending up at ``The World's Richest Acre,'' where there were once 24
wells that produced more than 2.5 million barrels of crude oil in
the 1930s through the 1950s.
   City Manager Ron Cox said there once were 1,200 wells in Kilgore
but now there were only about 200.
   Standing in the moist East Texas heat, Bentsen told local oilmen
of his work to repeal the windfall profits tax, which will be
accomplished if President Reagan signs trade legislation approved
recently by Congress.
   ``I understand very much the kind of predicament we're in here
in East Texas,'' said Bentsen, chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee.
   Ronnie Patton, owner of the Patton Corp., a supplier of drilling
rigs and equipment, said his business was bad.
   ``The phones are dead. There ain't anybody calling,'' he said.
   Rusty Howell of Marshall Exploration told Bentsen he hoped the
trade bill would result in ``jobs and money, dollars'' for East
Texas.
   ``So whenever you're up there in the White House, just remember,
stick some of that money down here to us,'' he said.
   Howell told reporters afterward that he had ``mixed emotions''
about Bentsen leaving the Senate if he's elected vice president.
   ``I'm definitely going to vote for Lloyd for senator,'' he said.
``In all probability, I will vote for him for (vice) president.''
   At the end of the day, Bentsen held a closed-door meeting with
the other end of the Democratic party spectrum _ a group of Jesse
Jackson's supporters in Dallas.
   Juggling his two campaigns, Bentsen selected public events for
vice presidential bid and met privately with Senate supporters.
   The senator's staff said his entire nine-day swing through Texas
was a vice-presidential trip, but Senate campaign buttons and signs
were everywhere and Dukakis' name was scarce.
   After dinner and breakfast with supporters of his Senate
campaign in nearby Tyler, Bentsen said he had explained why he
teamed up with Dukakis, a Massachusetts liberal, just as Lyndon B.
Johnson ran with John F. Kennedy in 1960 while simultaneously
running for re-election to the Senate.
   ``I'm visiting with them as to why I went on the ticket, and
that I felt in this election we were playing for all the marbles,''
he said.
   Quitting the Senate campaign would automatically give a six-year
term to his opponent, Rep. Beau Boulter, R-Texas.
   ``I'm sure they'd like that. But we're not going to do that,''
he said. ``I certainly expect to (win),'' he said. ``Lyndon Johnson
did.''
   Bentsen's fellow senator from Texas, Republican Phil Gramm, who
placed Bush's name in nomination for the presidency at the GOP
convention in New Orleans, said Thursday he thought Republicans
could win the White House without Texas' 29 electoral votes.
   Asked if he was surprised at Gramm's concession that the GOP
might lose Texas in the November elections, Bentsen smiled and
said: ``I think he's made a very good forecast.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
