<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Quayle-Kerrey     08-18 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Quayle-Kerrey,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kerrey Won't Criticize Quayle For Guard Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROSE ANN ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Senate candidate Bob Kerrey, who
won the Medal of Honor and lost part of a leg in the Vietnam War,
said Thursday that Dan Quayle should be honest about his military
service record.
   ``Don't drape yourself in a flag and forget what it was like to
be 20 and what it was like for your number to come up,'' Kerrey
said in a telephone interview.
   Kerrey said Quayle, a Republican U.S. Senator from Indiana and
George Bush's choice as a presidential running mate, should admit
that he wouldn't have joined the National Guard unless he was under
the threat of the draft.
   ``I wouldn't have thought of going to Canada or to jail or ask
my dad to make some calls to the draft board,'' said Kerrey. ``But
I also was not overwhelmed by patriotic verve.''
   Kerrey, 44, enlisted in the Navy, were he became a member of the
elite SEALS.
   Still, the former Nebraska governor said, ``I don't have hostile
feelings toward Dan Quayle because he got in the National Guard
instead of waiting for the draft.''
   However, if Quayle or his influential publishing family pulled
strings to keep him out of combat, ``that's a different story.''
   Quayle, a hardliner on defense, said he sought guard duty so he
could attend law school.
   Quayle was 22 in 1969, no longer deferred from the draft and
vulnerable to being conscripted and sent to Vietnam. National Guard
units were rarely activated for Vietnam duty, and many men joined
the guard to avoid the draft and likely Vietnam duty.
   Retired Maj. Gen. Wendell C. Phillippi, who worked for Quayle's
grandfather, Eugene C. Pulliam _ said Thursday that he contacted
guard acquaintances on behalf of Quayle.
</TEXT>
