<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spain-Bombs     08-18 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Bombs,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catalonian, ETA Separatists Claim Responsibility for Bomb Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Catalonian separatists who said they
were targeting heroin dealers claimed responsibility for a bomb
attack that injured three people Thursday, officials said.
   The bomb exploded outside the Bar Maite in Barcelona's run-down
El Rabal neighborhood about 2:30 a.m. It seriously injured a
relative of the bar's owner and a passer-by, a spokesman for the
civil governor's office said. A 10-year-old girl who had been
sleeping in a back room was slightly hurt, he said.
   The Basque terrorist group ETA meanwhile claimed responsibility
for a string of bombings in northern Spain that damaged seven
French firms and ripped up tracks along a railway line Sunday.
   The spokesman for the civil governor's office said a caller
speaking on behalf of the separatist group Terra Lliure told a
local radio station the group had planted the bomb in El Rabal
because the bar had been a hangout for heroin dealers. The
spokesman demanded anonymity.
   This year, at least 100 people have died of heroin overdoses in
Spain, 25 of them in Barcelona.
   Police say the deaths are due to an abrupt increase in the
purity of the heroin. They blame international traffickers who are
offering a high-quality product to capture a wider share of the
Spanish market.
   Terra Lliure stands for Free Land in the Catalan language and
supports independence for the four-province region of Catalonia, of
which Barcelona is the capital.
   The group previously has claimed responsibility for several
attacks in Barcelona, including a March 17 explosion at the British
Consulate and a bomb blast outside the U.S. Embassy last October.
   ETA, which stands for Homeland and Liberty in the Basque
language, claimed responsibility for Sunday's bombings in a note to
the daily newspaper Egin.
   The blasts at six car dealerships and a dairy caused more than
$810,000 in damage. Police safely exploded bombs outside two other
dealerships.
   In the note, ETA repeated a January offer to negotiate an end to
its attacks, which have killed more than 600 people _ mostly
police, civil guard and military officers _ since the group took up
arms in 1968.
   The government of Socialist Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez has
said it would not begin talks with ETA unless all attacks cease.
   Next week will mark the six-month anniversary of ETA's
kidnapping of Emiliano Revilla, a businessman still being held
hostage by the Basque group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
