<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HospitalStrike     08-18 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hospital Strike,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nurses, Hospital Negotiators Hail Proposed 20 Percent Raise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both sides in a strike involving 2,000
nurses hailed a tentative agreement reached Thursday that would
provide a 20 percent wage hike over three years and boost top
annual pay for some nurses to $50,000.
   ``Overall, it's a good, solid contract and it's one of the best
contracts in the country,'' said Maureen Anderson, spokeswoman for
the California Nurses Association.
   ``We're obviously very, very pleased,'' said Karen Henry, chief
negotiator for Affiliated Hospitals, which represents the six
hospitals that were struck.
   The nine-nurse negotiating team recommended union members
approve the contract, but Anderson noted the vote was not
unanimous. A ratification vote was scheduled Friday.
   If the agreement is ratified, nurses would end the two-week-old
strike and return to work Monday at St. Francis, Children's,
Marshal Hale, St. Mary's and Mount Zion hospitals in Francisco and
Seton Medical Center in Daly City.
   Ratification by the nurses also would send about 1,700 hospital
service workers honoring the strike back to work. Striking licensed
vocational nurses, technicians, dietary and housekeeping workers
represented by Local 250 of the Hospital and Health Care Workers
Union this week approved a new contract that ended their three-week
strike.
   However, they continued to honor picket lines at the six
hospitals and at another hospital until the nurses settled their
dispute.
   Under the proposed contract, nurses would receive a 7.5 percent
increase retroactive to Aug. 1, a 6.5 percent increase in August
1989 and a 6 percent hike in August 1990. Nurses with 10 and 15
years experience would get an additional 2 percent hike.
   A full-time, nightshift nurse with five years experience would
earn $50,000 by 1990, said Anderson. A similar nurse on the
dayshift would earn $43,541 by the final year of the contract.
   ``We look forward to prompt ratification of the agreement so
that hospital operations can return to normal as soon as
possible,'' said John G. Williams, president of the Affiliated
Hospitals board of directors and chief executive officer of St.
Francis Memorial Hospital.
   All the hospitals remained open during the strike, but with some
reductions in services.
   Nurses striking a seventh hospital, French Hospital in San
Francisco, are negotiating separately.
   Local 250 first went on strike July 26 at all seven Affiliated
Hospitals in a dispute over sick leave and health benefits. On Aug.
2, registered nurses struck six of the seven hospitals over pay,
overtime, work hours and staffing improvements. Nurses at the
seventh hospital, Pacific Presbyterian, are not unionized.
   On Aug. 6, Local 250 and the CNA walked out in separate strikes
at French Hospital, which does not belong to Affiliated Hospitals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880818-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 2032EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-VincennesReport     08-18 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vincennes Report,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Expected To Accept Findings On Iranian Plane Downing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci was
expected to accept the finding of military investigators that human
error led the USS Vincennes to mistakenly shoot down an Iranian
airliner on July 3, Pentagon sources said Thursday.
   President Reagan earlier said the United States accepted
responsibility for the tragedy and was willing to compensate the
families of the 290 people killed in the incident, although many
members of Congress have expressed reluctance to make such payments.
   The announcement by Carlucci, expected as early as Friday, would
mark the first public acknowledgement by the Pentagon that the loss
of life was caused by U.S. servicemen rather than an equipment
failure or specific action taken by Iran.
   The report implicitly ascribes some blame for the incident on
Iran, however, by noting that since the tragedy Iran has changed
the manner in which its civilian aircraft operate over the Persian
Gulf, climbing to 25,000 feet while over land, the sources said.
   In the past, Iranian civilian aircraft, including the A-300
Airbus, reached 25,000 feet as they travelled over the gulf itself.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said military
investigators found that radar operators aboard the Vincennes
misread data and mistakenly identified the airliner as hostile.
   The error stemmed from pressure on members of a crew facing
their first experience in combat, as well as confusing behavior by
the Iranian airliner, said the sources.
   The report was expected to differ with comments made on the day
of the tragedy by the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Adm.
Willam Crowe, in finding that the plane was ascending or levelling
off when it was hit and that it was in a civilian air corridor
rather than outside it, the sources said.
   ABC News said Thursday evening that the report contradicts
earlier Pentagon claims that the Airbus was putting out two
identification signals _ one civilian and the other military.
Instead, it said, the airliner's transponder was transmitting only
civilian signals and the military signals picked up by the
Vincennes came from a distant plane.
   The report was expected to be consistent with Crowe's comment
that the Vincennes mistook the A-300 Airbus for an F-14 fighter in
part because the jet took off from a joint military-civilian
airfield minutes after the Vincennes ended a surface engagement
with Iranian gunboats, the sources said.
   Some mysteries remain: why the airliner flew into a combat area
and why it ignored repeated broadcast warnings by the Vincennes.
   In earlier versions of the report, senior U.S. military
officials recommended that the servicemen responsible for the error
not be punished. It was not clear whether Carlucci would take more
drastic action, according to the Pentagon sources.
   Crowe, who passed the report up the chain of command to
Carlucci, recommended that the servicemen receive a non-punitive
letter of censure in their files, a step that might damage their
careers, the sources said.
   There was no indication that the Pentagon would formally censure
the commander of the Vincennes, Capt. Will C. Rogers III.
   The investigation was carried out by Rear Adm. William Fogarty,
then given to Gen. George Crist, the commander of U.S. forces in
the Persian Gulf, and then went to Crowe for Carlucci.
   Sources said that the report itself was about 70 pages long,
with an additional 1,000 pages of documentation gathered by Fogarty
and his team.
   The report is said to exonerate the sophisticated Aegis radar
and tracking system aboard the Vincennes, one of the most advanced
ships in the Navy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880818-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 2312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Fahrenkopf-Media     08-18 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Fahrenkopf-Media,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Chairman Assesses Quayle Controversy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Party chairman Frank Fahrenkopf on
Thursday attributed the controversy over vice presidential nominee
Dan Quayle's military service to the fact that Quayle was a
``surprise'' candidate to the news media.
   ``I've never see anything like it,'' Fahrenkopf said in an
interview. ``It's almost like one reporter would talk to another
reporter and they would come and ask another question. It was like
dominoes going down among the press.
   ``It just started taking off and it had a life of its own,
saying that he was going to be removed from the ticket. That's not
the case.
   ``I was with the vice president this morning between 9 a.m. and
10 a.m.. At that time he said he was firmly in support of the
ticket and of Dan Quayle and this would all pass. And at a luncheon
he said it again. Later in the afternoon I was with him. At no time
was there any question, yet the press was running around like it
was a given fact.
   ``So it's just part of the convention process, and a part of a
candidate who was a surprise being named, and people starting to
look into his background.''
</TEXT>
