<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ThriftPlan 1stLd-Writethru a0789 08-18 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thrift Plan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0789,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$1.3 Billion Plan Unveiled To Help Insolvent Texas S&Ls</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New material throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators announced Thursday they
will spend $1.3 billion to help a group of outside investors
acquire 12 insolvent Texas thrifts in the fourth consolidation
under a government plan aimed at recapitalizing ailing thrifts in
the Southwest.
   The Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp., which insures most
of the nation's S&Ls, said it would provide a $499 million note to
help the new company, to be known as American Federal Bank F.S.B.,
restore positive net worth. The total cost to FSLIC is expected to
reach $1.3 billion.
   The FSLIC said the 12 thrifts had combined assets of nearly $2.4
billion and liabilities of $3 billion.
   The merged institution, which will have $3.7 billion in assets,
is to have headquarters in Dallas.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board, regulators of the thrift
industry, said the merger was conducted in conjunction with a
subsidiary of Lone Star Technologies Inc. of Dallas, one of the
world's leading manufacturers of tubular pipe.
   The subsidiary, LSST Financial Services Corp. has agreed to
provide $48 million in the deal.
   It will work Gibson Group Inc., a private investment group
organized by William E. Gibson, executive vice president of
Continental Illinois National Bank and Trust in Chicago, and
Continental Illinois Corp.
   Gibson will be president and chief executive officer of the new
institution.
   Thursday's merger was one of the biggest deals under the
government's ``Southwest Plan,'' which is aimed at ridding the
region of money-losing thrifts.
   ``We now have consolidated 24 of the 109 Texas thrifts that were
insolvent when we started the Southwest Plan,'' said M. Danny Wall,
chairman of the bank board. ``Today's transaction shows that
private investors are willing to bring in hard cash for the
opportunity of participating in the Texas thrift recovery.''
   To accomplish the acquisition, all 12 associations were placed
in receivership, the bank board said.
   The bank board said two of the 12 Texas thrifts _ Mercury
Savings Association of Wichita Falls, and Ben Milam Savings & Loan
of Cameron _ had been in the federally assisted management
consignment program, which replace the management of ailing thrifts
with those from healthy ones.
   A third, Richardson Savings & Loan Association of Dallas, had a
$77.6 million loss in the first quarter of 1988, the 10th-worst
earnings record nationally among thrifts.
   The 12 thrifts had combined assets of nearly $2.4 billion and
liabilities of $3 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880818-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 2233EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--BarbaraBush 1stLd-Writethru a0732 08-18 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Barbara Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0732,320</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to past tense speech and supply crowd reaction.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Speech Lauds Husband-Nominee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush used her national political
convention speech Thursday night to extol the virtues of her
husband and speak from the heart about the death of a daughter.
   Taking the podium shortly before Republican presidential nominee
George Bush was to make his acceptance speech, Mrs. Bush said,
``You've nominated for the presidency a man who is as strong and
caring and decent as America herself.''
   In remarks to the 2,277 Republican National Convention
delegates, which were received warmly, she said, `You're looking at
a woman who couldn't be happier with her life.''
   Mrs. Bush said, ``I have my causes,'' such as eliminating
illiteracy, but added that she also has ``five wonderful children,
each of whom has married an equally wonderful person, and in turn
given me 10 exquisite grandchildren.''
   She also recalled the death of their 3-year-old daughter, Robin,
to leukemia, saying it was ``the hardest thing we ever faced
together.''
   ``When she was gone, I fell apart,'' she said. ``But George
wouldn't let me retreat into my grief. He made me share it and
accept that his sorrow was as great as my own. He simply wouldn't
allow my grief to divide us and push us apart.''
   Earlier Thursday, the Bushes had a light-hearted exchange at a
brunch given for Mrs. Bush by the National Federation of Republican
Women.
   Bush quipped about criticism from some quarters that he fails to
show emotion.
   ``Here we go with an introduction with feeling, demonstrable
feeling,'' Bush said from the podium. ``Come on up, sweetie pie.''
   When Mrs. Bush joined her husband, she turned to him and
exclaimed, ``I hope you can't take your eyes off me,'' then told
the audience, ``and see if he looks at me as adoringly as I looked
at him.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
