<DOCNO> AP880818-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 2323EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-InsuranceSuits     08-18 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Insurance Suits,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Repeals Victim's Right To Sue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An injury victim has no right to sue the
other party's insurance company for dragging out payments, the
California Supreme Court ruled Thursday, overturning a
multimillion-dollar 1979 decision.
   The 5-2 decision bans such lawsuits in the future once the
ruling becomes final. It allows pending cases to continue, but
limits them severely by requiring proof of the wrongdoer's
liability before the insurer can be sued _ a restriction that
eliminates most cases, which are settled without an admission of
liability.
   A 1979 ruling in the Royal Globe case allowed an injury victim
to sue the other side's insurance company for violating laws
requiring claims to be handled in good faith, with claims paid
promptly once liability is clear.
   Such lawsuits often carry punitive damage awards far higher than
the insurance benefits involved. Supporters viewed the lawsuits as
a way to enforce the state's largely toothless laws regulating
insurers; opponents in the insurance industry said the lawsuits
were a form of legal intimidation and drove up insurance rates.
   Thursday's majority opinion by Chief Justice Malcolm Lucas said
the Royal Globe ruling ``has generated and will continue to produce
inequitable results, costly multiple litigation, and unnecessary
confusion unless we overrule it.''
   In dissent, Justice Stanley Mosk, the author of the Royal Globe
decision, said the court had ``replaced Royal Globe with a `Royal
Bonanza' for insurance carriers ... total immunity for unfair and
deceptive practices committed on innocent claimants.''
   The lawsuit involved Parveni Moradi-Shalal, who was hit by a car
driven by a Fireman's Fund insurance policy-holder in 1983. Her
$750,000 lawsuit said the company made no effort to settle the
policy claim for several months after being asked; it settled five
months after she sued the driver.
   The high court dismissed her lawsuit, saying it was not based on
a determination by a judge that the other driver was liable for the
accident.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880818-0223 </DOCNO>
