<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Dole     08-18 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Dole,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole: Quayle `Ready, Willing to Make Tough Choices'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Dole, nominating Dan Quayle for No. 2
spot on the Republican ticket, lauded his Senate colleague Thursday
as a man ``ready and willing to make the tough choices.''
   ``Just let the Democrats try to use experience as a measuring
stick in this campaign,'' said Dole. ``Just let they try.''
   ``Whenever I needed him, Dan was there, ready and willing to
make the tough choices, to cast the tough votes, to transform
President Reagan's vision of America into the law of the land,''
Dole said.
   Dole and his wife, former Transportation Secretary Elizabeth
Dole, both were under consideration for the Republican vice
presidential nomination before George Bush selected Quayle.
   Nowhere in four-minute speech did Dole allude to the controversy
surrounding the circumstances under which Quayle joined the
National Guard during the Vietnam War.
   Instead, Dole, the Senate Republican leader, concentrated on
Quayle's service in Congress and his family.
   ``He's already spent 12 years as a congressman and a senator,
tackling the vital national and international issues that affect
the lives of all Americans and the future of the country,'' Dole
said. ``That is 12 more years of national experience than Michael
Dukakis _ and he is running for president.''
   Following Dole to the podium were Sens. Richard Lugar of
Indiana, Nancy Kassebaum of Kansas and Alan Simpson of Wyoming and
Rep. Jack Kemp of New York.
   Lugar, the senior senator from Quayle's home state of Indiana,
misspoke during his address and told delegates he was endorsing the
nomination of ``the next president of the United States.''
   Simpson, in his seconding speech, said, ``We are the party of
the future and Dan Quayle is the future of our party.''
   Quayle was the only candidate whose name was placed in
nomination, and under rules adopted by the convention earlier this
week, was nominated by acclamation.
</TEXT>
