<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Dodd     08-18 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Dodd,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Connecticut Senator Says Sandinistas Will Extend Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., said
he received assurances Thursday from the leftist Sandinista
government it will extend indefinitely a cease-fire with the
U.S.-backed Nicaraguan rebels.
   Dodd made a brief stop Thursday in Nicaragua and met with
President Daniel Ortega and his brother, Defense Minister Humberto
Ortega.
   ``There are no preconditions on talks'' with the rebels, known
as Contras, Dodd said at Augusto Cesar Sandino Airport shortly
before leaving. ``They said they would extend it (the cease-fire)
indefinitely.''
   The Sandinistas and Contras signed an agreement March 23 to seek
a negotiated settlement to the 7-year-old war. Both sides suspended
offensive military operations on March 21, the start of the talks.
   High-level talks broke off June 9 and each side charged the
other with breaking the cease-fire, which the Sandinistas have been
extending on a monthly basis. The current cease-fire was due to
expire Aug. 31.
   Ortega on Thursday renewed his call for a new round of talks to
take place in Managua on Aug. 26. The rebels, citing restrictions
on their freedom of movement, have said they will not return to the
capital and asked the president to take part in any future
discussions.
   Dodd said he discussed with the Sandinistas the latest U.S.
Senate package to provide humanitarian aid to the Contras.
   ``Obviously they are not happy,'' Dodd said, adding that the
possibility of renewed U.S. military aid to the rebels was ``very
open'' and that the government ``should know about that.''
   The United States has backed the Contras in their battle to
overthrow the Sandinistas since 1981, almost two years after the
new government came to power in a 1979 revolutionary war.
   U.S. military aid for the rebels expired in February. On Aug.
10, the Senate voted for a Democratic proposal to provide the
Contras with $27 million in non-lethal humanitarian aid after Oct.
1 and a possible second vote on $16.3 million in stockpiled
military aid later this year.
   Speaking in Spanish earlier outside the Foreign Ministry, Dodd
said U.S. relations with Latin America would improve with the
election of Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis.
   ``I have hope that if Dukakis wins that the relations between
the United States and Latin America will be much better,'' Dodd
said.
</TEXT>
