<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0757 08-18 0939</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0757,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Blasts Reagan-Bush Drug Fight, Vows to Banish Racism</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 14 grafs with Birmingham speech delivered,
response from crowd and Dukakis aides to Quayle controversy.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis ventured into an
historic Baptist church in the Deep South on Thursday to ask black
voters to join him in resolving that ``we will not rest until every
form of bigotry and racism and religious intolerance is banished
from this land.''
   The Democratic presidential nominee promised the predominantly
black congregation at the Sixth Avenue Baptist church to reverse
the ``indifference'' and ``blind eye'' of the Reagan administration.
   ``After eight long years, this nation needs a president and a
vice president who understand that civil rigths can never be a
sometime thing,'' said Dukakis, who was warmly received at the
Birmingham church.
   The Massachusetts governor came to Alabama from Miami, where he
termed the Reagan-Bush war against drugs an illusion.
   Dukakis accused President Reagan of ``stonewalling'' an
investigation of Panamanian leader Manuel Antonio Noriega's alleged
involvement in drug trafficking and said Vice President George
Bush's anti-drug efforts was ``a failure.''
   ``This war against drugs is non-existent,'' he told reporters.
Dukakis said little about the controversy over GOP vice
presidential candidate Dan Quayle's Vietnam-era service in the
National Guard.
   Some black leaders, including Jesse Jackson, had criticized
Dukakis for not using a recent appearance in Mississippi to outline
his views on minority concerns. On Thursday, he cited a long list
of problems demanding solutions, including a lack of affordable
housing, job training, prenatal care, quality schools and anti-drug
programs.
   ``We can remain frozen in the ice of our own indifference, or we
can invest in the prenatal care and early childhood education that
will give every child in America a healthy start and a fair shot at
the American dream,'' Dukakis told the congregation at the Sixth
Avenue Baptist Church.
   Dukakis paid tribute to four young girls who were killed 25
years ago in a racial bombing at a nearby black church.
   ``We can turn our heads and wish that hate crimes never took
place or ... we can provide the moral leadership we need to banish
racial and religious violence forever in this country,'' he said.
``And that leadership must begin in the White House.''
   Dukakis saluted Martin Luther King Jr., Jackson, Alabama's Rosa
Parks and other civil rights leaders.
   ``I am proud to be here tonight with hundreds of brave men and
women in this congregation who have marched and fought and
struggled against all odds to create a better world, not only for
your children but for all children everywhere,'' Dukakis said.
   ``Those of you who fought and struggled are true American
heroes. And while your names may not appear in history books, you
have made history.''
   He added: ``What better time than now to resolve that we will
not rest until every form of bigotry and racism and religious
intolerance is banished from this land.''
   Dukakis himself sought to steer clear of the controversy over
whether Quayle joined the Indiana National Guard to avoid combat
duty in Vietnam.
   Dukakis said, however, that he was proud to have served in Korea
in the aftermath of the Korean War. Dukakis aides, though, pointed
to the controversy to question Bush's judgment in picking Quayle.
   Dukakis congratulated Bush on winning the Republican
presidential nomination and then harshly criticized Reagan's order
Wednesday that the State and Defense departments and the CIA not
cooperate with a congressional investigation of Noreiga's alleged
drug ties.
   ``If we're serious about fighting the war (on drugs), we can't
have any stonewalling from the federal government or the White
House,'' Dukakis said before he headed for campaign appearances in
Alabama.
   The General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of
Congress, is trying to determine when U.S. intelligence agencies
first suspected Noriega of involvement in drug trafficking and when
Bush and other administration officials were alerted.
   ``I think the White House does not want to cooperate ... because
they are embarrassed by this. They should be embarrassed by this,''
Dukakis said.
   The Massachusetts governor was asked whether, if elected
president, he would put his vice president in charge of anti-drug
efforts. He replied that he would appoint a full-time drug czar
directly accountable to the president.
   He noted that Bush had served in that role as vice president.
   ``It was a failure,'' Dukakis said. ``What's the point of
repeating failure?''
   Dukakis at first refused comment when asked whether Quayle
should have enlisted for active duty in the military in 1969
instead of entering the Indiana Nationl Guard.
   Pressed on the issue, Dukakis said:
   ``I can only speak for myself. I served my country. I did so
proudly. It was an important issue in my life. I can only speak for
myself.''
   Touring the Marshall Space Flight Center at Huntsville, Ala.,
Dukakis declared his support for the multibillion-dollar space
station program. He also promised to revive the National Space
Council, a Cabinet-level agency that oversaw the U.S. space program
before it was abolished by President Nixon.
   ``In recent years, our space program has lost the sense of
purpose that made it such a source of accomplishment and pride,''
Dukakis said at Huntsville.
   ``We are no longer the unquestioned leader in space,'' he said.
``Some have begun to doubt our ability to compete in this vast new
frontier. I don't buy that at all, and I hope you don't either.''
   Dukakis planned to spend the night at St. Louis and campaign
Friday in Missouri, Illinois, Arkansas and Texas. His Saturday
schedule includes appearances in Texas and Tennessee.
</TEXT>
