<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Czechoslovakia 1stLd-Writethru a0770 08-18 0717</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0770,0735</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreigners Expelled After Protesting in Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-18 RECAST lead for style, UPDATE with Italian
report of protesters expelled, others in police custody, American
arrested. Picks up 18th graf pvs, The CTK ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of foreigners distributed
leaflets and staged a brief protest Thursday in central Prague
demanding more freedom in Czechoslovakia and withdrawal of Soviet
troops before police hustled them away. The government later said
it expelled them. An activist in Rome said that eight Italians were
expelled after giving out leaflets earlier this week, but that five
or six other protesters remained in police custody after they were
arrested in Prague on Thursday.
   The demonstration, timed to mark this weekend's anniversary of
the Soviet-led invasion that crushed reform 20 years ago, were
staged by members by the Radical Party, a Europe-wide movement that
has its strongest following in Italy.
   Eight party members held a 75-foot banner across the width of
Wenceslas Square on Thursday that proclaimed ``Together for
Democracy _ 1968 _ Russian Troops Out of the Country _ Freedom _
Human Rights,'' and was adorned with a drawing of a tank.
   Hundreds of people gathered to look at the Czech language
banner. Within three minutes, uniformed and plainclothes police had
hustled the protesters into waiting patrol cars.
   A smaller banner with the word ``freedom'' in Czech fluttered
from the statue of King Wenceslas farther up the square, but police
quickly tore it down and arrested the two people who displayed it.
   The official news agency CTK accused the protesters of
attempting ``a provocation'' on Wenceslas Square. It said the
leaflets stemmed from ``a campaign unleashed by the Western media
against Czechoslovakia under the cloak of the so-called Prague
Spring.''
   The stay of ``these foreign nationals, who misused their visit,
was terminated,'' the news agency said in a brief report that did
not mention how many people were expelled or where they were sent.
   In Rome, a Radical Party official said eight Italians were
expelled from Czechoslovakia Thursday after they gave out leaflets
calling for protests to mark the 20th anniversary of the Soviet
invasion. Party spokesman Antonio Stango said they were detained in
the cities of Kolin, Brno, Bratislava and Budejovice on Tuesday and
Wednesday.
   He also said five or six party members were arrested because
they took part in the demonstration in Prague on Thursday. One of
them is Giovanni Negri, a member of the European Parliament, Stango
said.
   He said the detainees were still being held by police but he had
no details on their condition.
   An American, Antonia Elizabeth Brown, and several Belgians were
also detained in connection with the Prague protest, he said. He
did not know Brown's hometown.
   In Brussels, Radical Party worker Alexander de Berlingh had said
Wednesday that seven Italians and one Spanish woman were presumed
detained after distributing the leaflets in Brno.
   There was no explanation for the different numbers of Italians
arrested in the two reports of party officials.
   Other leaflets were handed out in Slovakia and in the Prague
area, de Berlingh told The Associated Press. De Berlingh said 20
people, mostly Italians, took part in the leaflet distribution and
Thursday's protest.
   At least two underground groups have distributed leaflets in
recent days calling on citizens to mark the anniversary by staging
peaceful protests, wearing the national flag or dressing in the
flag's colors of red, white and blue.
   The Radical Party, which has three deputies in the European
Parliament, distributed thousands of the leaflets around
Czechoslovakia this week, an activist said. The pamphlets called
for freedom, human rights, Soviet troop withdrawal and the release
of political prisoners.
   Wenceslas Square was the scene of fierce protests by thousands
of people after Soviet and Warsaw Pact troops and tanks invaded
Czechoslovakia Aug. 20-21, 1968, to crush the ``Prague Spring,'' a
Communist-led reform under then-party leader Alexander Dubcek.
   The CTK news agency said police who broke up the protest were
summoned ``by Czechoslovak citizens who were on the square.''
   Some onlookers were heard denouncing the protesters as ``fools''
or ``idiots.''
   Others murmured support for the protesters. ``Finally, some
brave people,'' one Czech said. As the demonstrators were detained,
another bystander commented, ``What kind of democracy is this?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
