<1ST_LINE>u p BC-CVN--ThompsonText 1stLd-Writethru a0739 08-18 0670</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Thompson Text, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0739,650</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Provides an as-delivered transcript; no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of remarks by Illinois
Gov. James Thompson introducing Vice President George Bush at the
Republican National Convention Thursday night.
   Mr. Chairman, my fellow Republicans, my fellow Americans.
   The nomination of a candidate for the office of president of the
United States is more than the tribal roar in a convention hall,
more than the sum total of cold caucus days in the dead of winter
on the prairie or in the mountains, more than the raucous shouts
and endless images of primary trails across a nation.
   The presidential nomination of a political party represents more
than the singular and personal triumph of one leader's voice amidst
the chorus of philosophy and alliances and loyalties.
   More than this, the nomination of our presidential candidate
defines the soul of our party and the character and common sense of
the campaign which we now bring to the nation. So that our fellow
Americans _ whose allegiance and approval we want _ may know who we
are, it is imperative that they know who George Bush _ the man and
the leader _ is.
   The American people understand the triumph of the Reagan-Bush
years _ when America regained her voice and place in the world;
when an economy in shambles was rescued and revived; when American
competitiveness was brought back.
   The American people understand that the world is a more peaceful
place today because the Reagan-Bush team brought those who used to
bristle behind their missiles to the bargaining table so that
generations of our children and grandchildren could live in peace.
   The American people are grateful to Ronald Reagan and George
Bush for this and for much more. But that is not what this election
is about. This election is about the future.
   The George Bush that I know believes that as we strengthen our
economy, we must not let the engines of that economy despoil our
land and our air and our water. The George Bush that I know loves
this land of ours, and a Bush administration will protect it.
   The George Bush that I know believes that the future begins with
family _ he has always been sustained and strengthened by his
family.
   The George Bush that I know wants hope and opportunity for all
the children of America; the chance to learn and the opportunity to
earn; to make their way in a world of equality. But, he knows that
what government does is not a substitute for what good-hearted
people can do with encouragement and self-help.
   The other candidate for president believes that a new government
bureaucracy can best tell us how to and where to care for our
children. But George Bush believes that the American family and the
American neighbor and the American church know best how to care for
our children.
   And the George Bush that I know believes that freedom from
criminals is more important than freedom for criminals.
   The George Bush that I know seeks peace. But George Bush knows
that America cannot hide behind its own borders without the risk of
the toxic waste of unchallenged tyranny may someday wash up on our
shores if we shrink from defending freedom anywhere in the world.
   Maybe you don't need to be shot from the skies at the age of 20
in the defense of your country, or run the spies and the spooks
from Langley, to know that it's a dangerous world from decade to
decade. But my guess is, it sure helped. George Bush knows that we
have to be brave, and strong, and daring, but we have to be
``careful out there.''
   My fellow Republicans, let's take a closer look at America's
best hope for progress without risk, for change and for growth
without destruction of the accomplishments we have gained, and the
values that hold us together. All of us, as Americans.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End Thompson Text _ 1 Take</HEAD>
