<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Bush 4thLd-Writethru a0914 08-18 1198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Bush, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0914,1,000</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Sees Election As `Choice Between Different Ideas of Future'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts new grafs 7-13 to update with closing color, ``The
new xxx</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Before an uproarious Republican National
Convention, George Bush claimed the presidential nomination
Thursday with a declaration that the election is a choice between
``two very different ideas of the future:'' America as a rising
nation or one in decline.
   In remarks to the convention's closing session, Bush described
himself as the underdog determined ``to run hard, to fight hard, to
stand on the issues.''
   ``They call it a swiss cheese economy,'' he said of his
Democratic opponents. ``Well, that's the way it might look to the
three blind mice. But when they were in charge, it was all holes
and no cheese.''
   Bush chuckled when some began singing, ``Three Blind Mice.''
   Bush also addressed the desire for change after nearly eight
years of the Reagan presidency, a desire the vice president's
campaign advisers believe is one of his biggest hurdles.
   ``But when you have to change horses in midstream, doesn't it
make sense to switch to one who's going the same way?'' he asked.
   The new presidential nominee closed his speech by asking the
delegates to stand and join him in reciting the Pledge of
Allegiance to the flag.
   His wife, Barbara, was the first to join Bush on the podium.
They kissed and then turned and faced the roaring crowd. Then came
the four Bush sons and a daughter and 10 grandchildren.
   The vice presidential nominee, Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle, his
wife, Marilyn and their children, joined the Bush family on the
podium.
   It was the scene Bush had promised the previous day when he said
he would drop his reluctance to put his family in the spotlight.
   For 10 minutes it was only family. Then the politicians joined
them, the men whom Bush defeated in the fight for the nomination _
Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas, former Gov. Pete du Pont of Delaware, Rep.
Jack Kemp of New York, and television evangelist Pat Robertson.
   Thousands of red, white and blue balloons and flakes of confetti
drifted down on the celebrating crowd.
   The demonstration died down after 15 minutes.
   Bush was introduced by Gov. Jim Thompson of Illinois and by a
videotape that showed him shaking hands with Soviet Leader Mikhail
Gorbachev as well as playing with one of his granddaughters.
   Also featured on the video was President Reagan saying, ``I
trust George Bush. America can trust him too.''
   The huge hall erupted into cheers and flag-waving with the
announcement, ``Ladies and gentlemen, the vice president of the
United States,'' and Bush strode alone to the podium.
   Hundreds of young people who had filed into the hall during the
video fueled the demonstration, which went on for seven minutes.
   It was a night Bush had awaited for eight years, ever since the
1980 campaign when he lost out to Reagan and ended up with the
party's vice presidential candidate.
   Barbara Bush watched her husband's speech from the VIP box,
where she sat between the Rev. Billy Graham and Greek Orthodox
Archbishop Iacavos. Also seated in the box were the vice
presidential nominee, Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle and his family.
   In his acceptance speech, the vice president cited campaign
themes of his Democratic opponent, Michael Dukakis, and tried to
turn them to his advantage.
   ``Some say this isn't an election about ideology, it's an
election about competence,'' said Bush, a reference to Dukakis'
speech accepting the Democratic presidential nomination.
   ``But this election isn't only about competence, for competence
is a narrow idea,'' said the Republican nominee. ``Competence makes
the trains run on time but doesn't know where they're going.''
   On jobs, he said, ``Someone better take a `message to Michael:'
tell him we've been creating good jobs at good wages.'' The need to
create good jobs at good wages, is a favorite Dukakis campaign
theme.
   Bush conceded that ``I may not be the most eloquent ... I may
sometimes be a little awkward, but there's nothing self-conscious
in my love of country. I am a quiet man _ but I hear the quiet
people others don't. The ones who raise the family, pay the taxes,
meet the mortgage.
   ``I hear them and I am moved, and their concerns are mine.''
   He praised his running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana, under
fire over his National Guard service at a time when many draftees
were being sent to Vietnam.
   He caled Quayle ``a young leader who has become a forceful in
preparing America's workers for the labor force of the future. ...
I'm proud to have Dan Quayle at my side.''
   Paying tribute to President Reagan, Bush said he spent the last
7{ years helping ``a president conduct the most difficult job on
earth.
   ``Ronald Reagan asked for, and received, my candor. He never
asked for, but he did receive, my loyalty.''
   But the time had come, he said when ``you must see me as I am:
the Republican candidate for president of the United States.''
   He said the election was between ``not only two very different
men but two very different ideas of the future.''
   ``My opponent's view of the world sees a long slow decline for
our country, an inevitable fall mandated by impersonal historical
forces.
   ``But America is not in decline. America is a rising nation.''
   He said he and Dukakis have contrasting views on such questions
as whether the Pledge of Allegiance should be required in the
schools, on school prayer, the death penalty, gun control, abortion
and taxes.
   Bush vowed to ``do whatever it takes to make the sure the
disabled are included in the mainstream.''
   He pledged to stop ocean dumping and said, ``Our beaches should
not be garbage dumps and our harbors should not be cesspools.''
Bush said he would order the FBI to find out who was responsible
for the recent dumping of medical waste that washed up on beaches
in New York and new Jersey.
   He repeated his call for tougher ethical standards, saying
``there are those who have dropped their standards along the way,
as if ethics were too heavy and slowed their rise to the top.'' He
made no direct reference to the Reagan administration officials
accused of ethical violations.
   Earlier in the day, Bush appeared at a tribute to his wife,
Barbara, and said that he was told ``you've got to be a little more
demonstrative'' after seeing Michael Dukakis and his wife, Kitty,
openly display their affection toward each other at the Democratic
convention in July.
   Recently, Bush has often said that he is not given to public
displays of affection or emotion.
   ``Here we go,'' he said, looking at his wife who was seated to
his right, ``the introduction with feeling.
   ``Come on up, sweetie pie.''
   With that, Mrs. Bush stepped forward and they hugged.
   ``Thank you very, very much ... sweetie,'' he said.
   Then she told the audience, ``I hope you don't take your eyes
off him and see if he looks at me adoringly.''
   Later, she said, ``Nobody ever had a better husband.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
