<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--PakistanCrash     08-18 0133</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Pakistan Crash,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Convention Observes a Minute of Silence for Zia, Raphel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Republican National Convention observed a
minute of silence Wednesday night in memory of President Mohammed
Zia ul-Haq of Pakistan and U.S. Ambassador Arnold L. Raphel, who
were killed in an aircraft explosion.
   Among the 35 others aboard the aircraft were Brig. Gen. Herbert
M. Wassom, chief U.S. defense representative to Pakistan, and
several Pakistani army generals. All were reported killed.
   It was not clear what caused the explosion.
   Zia was a close U.S. ally and ruled Pakistan for 11 years,
longest of anyone in the nation's 41-year history. In accordance
with the constitution, he was succeeded by Senate chairman Ghulam
Ishaq Khan, who declared a state of emergency and 10 days of
national mourning.
</TEXT>
