<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Mecham,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham Attacks Dukakis on `Socialist Agenda'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis' ``socialist
agenda'' could wreck the U.S. economy, former Arizona Gov. Evan
Mecham told a conservative youth group Wednesday.
   The former governor also told the mostly college-age Young
Americans for Freedom he might try to win back the office he lost
through impeachment conviction in April.
   Responding to questions, Mecham, a George Bush delegate to the
Republican National Convention, acknowledged that many people were
``not enthused'' about the prospect of a Bush presidency.
   ``I suggest that they look at the alternative of absolute
disaster that would be wrought upon America and the world by a
Dukakis presidency,'' Mecham said.
   ``I assure you that the Dukakis socialist agenda will so
unsettle investor confidence that it will wreak havoc on our
economy in unprecedented proportions,'' he said.
   Later, Mecham told reporters he might seek to regain the
governorship in 1992 ``if there wasn't somebody better to run that
I could support.''
   Mecham was convicted on impeachment charges of misusing $80,000
from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto
dealership, and of trying to thwart an investigation of an alleged
death threat.
