<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN-MoneyMuscle 1stLd-Writethru a0724 08-18 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN-Money Muscle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0724,490</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Deletes future tense, graf 10, ``There's also ...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>GOP Strikes Back at Democratic Fund-raising Challenge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican fund-raisers, facing true
competition from their Democratic counterparts for the first time
in decades, are striking back this week by trying to raise $4
million at one event.
   ``We're concerned about it,'' said Fred Bush, chief fund-raiser
of Vice President George Bush's campaign. ``There seems to be a lot
of interest in fund raising on the Democratic side. I've never seen
that before.''
   Fred Bush, no relation to the vice president, is squaring off
against vaunted Democratic money man Robert Farmer, who has pledged
to raise $50 million for Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis' effort in the fall campaign.
   It remains to be seen if Farmer can deliver: that sum would be
unprecedented for a Democrat. But he has succeeded in instilling
newfound fervor in Republican campaign donors.
   ``Our guys understand. They know what's going on out there,''
Fred Bush said in an interview this week. ``A lot of them have come
to us and said, `I don't want the Democrats to beat us on fund
raising. What can I do?'''
   For one thing, they can attend a $1,000-per-plate lunch at the
city Convention Center on Thursday to benefit the Republican
National Committee. The goal is $4 million, compared to $2.5
million at the Dallas gala in 1984.
   ``It's our one big gala every year,'' said RNC spokeswoman
Katherine Murray. ``It's an opportunity for us to honor the new
nominee and vice presidential nominee. It's a celebration of our
all being here together.''
   It's also a chance for corporations to get in good with the GOP
by reserving tables at $100,000 each. And it's a way for the
Republicans to stroke their wealthy supporters with a personal
appearance by the nominee.
   But Thursday's lunch is by no means the only event for
fund-raisers this week. More than 600 contributors of $10,000-plus
are in town, Fred Bush said, and they're being treated to a full
plate of parties and receptions.
   There's also some hard business: a 1{-hour meeting for about 200
top fund-raisers to organize GOP efforts in each state, with
campaign chairman James Baker as host of the event.
   So far the Republicans have done well at raising money. Fred
Bush said the Republicans already have collected the $8.3 million
limit to supplement the Bush campaign's federal financing of $46
million; about $7 million, of a $25 million goal, for state party
accounts to be spent in coordination with the presidential
campaign; and several million more for general party-building. A
separate item is the RNC's operating budget, beneficiary of
Thursday's gala.
   ``Our goal is to keep pace with the Democrats,'' said Fred Bush.
``All this big money they're raising _ we're trying to do it too.''
</TEXT>
