<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Quayle-Last Lunch,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle And Wife Had Sought Private Lunch When Word Came From Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle and his wife, Marilyn, had
slipped away for what they suspected would be a last private lunch
when they got word George Bush was trying to reach him with an
offer for the No. 2 spot on the ticket, Quayle revealed Wednesday.
   Quayle said that when it appeared Bush might let his prospective
running mates know of his decision on Tuesday, ``my wife and I did
the only thing that spouses might do when you think that a call
might come and it might be your last private lunch and so we took a
walk down Bourbon Street.''
   They chose a seafood restaurant for lunch, and then their beeper
went off.
   ``Marilyn said, `Well, there it is,''' Quayle said in an ABC
interview.
   Back at their hotel, Quayle said, there was a message to call
James A. Baker, Bush's campaign chairman. Bush came on the line and
offered the Indiana senator the post, Quayle said.
   ``I went like this to my wife,'' Quayle said, raising his hand
in a thumbs-up gesture. ``And said, `yes sir.' And here we are.''
