<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0144EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FBI-Hispanics     08-18 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FBI-Hispanics,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hispanic Agent Complains of Mormon Superior</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Mormon who is a now high-ranking FBI
official tried to destroy a Hispanic agent's career for racial and
religious reasons, the agent testified Wednesday in a
discrimination suit against the bureau.
   Sammy Martinez, testifying in a class action by Hispanic agents,
said he was falsely accused of wrongdoing by John Walser, now
executive assistant director of the FBI, when Walser was his boss
in Mexico City in 1986.
   ``I know there was a contract on me,'' Martinez said, explaining
that in FBI jargon, a contract ``means someone's out to get you''
and sabotage your career.
   Martinez testified that he had been discriminated against, and
that he did not believe the incident would have happened were he
non-Hispanic or Mormon. Walser did not return an Associated Press
phone call to his office Wednesday.
   The 311 Hispanic agents who have joined the lawsuit being tried
in U.S. District Court contend the FBI discriminates against
Hispanics in hiring, promoting and disciplining. They want damages
and a change in the way the FBI promotes agents and handles
discrimination complaints.
   About 400 of the FBI's 9,000 special agents are Hispanic, or 4.4
percent. Nationally, 8 percent of the population is Hispanic.
   Martinez said Walser accused him of a security violation; the
agent did not specify what it was. Martinez was demoted and
assigned to Los Angeles _ a post he asked not to be assigned to
``because I knew Hispanic agents there had complained about Mormon
superiors.''
   Before Martinez was transferred from Mexico City, he filed an
internal equal employment opportunity complaint protesting Walser's
actions. He said he found out later that the chief of the equal
employment opportunity office mailed the confidential complaint to
Walser.
   Martinez said he appealed his demotion and transfer, and the FBI
did not resist. He was reinstated to his previous grade and
transferred to Washington, where he works in the same division as
Walser, he said.
   When defense attorney Alan Ferber reminded Martinez that Walser
has adopted four Mexican children and that his brother-in-law is
Hispanic, Martinez said he studied Mormon theology to further
understand Walser.
   ``The Book of Mormon says Mexican-Americans are cursed with dark
skin and are defiled,'' Martinez said. ``It says when they are
brought into the church, they become white and delightsome.''
   Martinez said he believes Walser is biased against Hispanics,
but that he did not know whether the alleged bias is based on
religious belief.
   Ferber said Walser likely will be called as a defense witness
next week. In his opening arguments Monday, Ferber prominently
mentioned Walser's adoption of four Mexican children and implied it
would be a central argument in the FBI's defense.
   Plaintiff co-counsel Hugo Rodriguez said Wednesday that other
agents with complaints about Mormon superiors are expected to be
called.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880818-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0714EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Economy     08-18 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Economy,0741</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Leader Says Plan Would Free State Enterprises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese leader Zhao Ziyang said the Politburo was
working on a five-year economic plan that would allow state-run
enterprises more autonomy, but he added that inflation threatens
reform, news reports said Wednesday.
   Zhao, general secretary of the Communist Party, also said the
first Chinese-Soviet summit meeting in three decades is possible if
Moscow first urges Vietnam to withdraw its troops from Cambodia.
The statement represented a softening of previous Chinese stances.
   Vietnam has announced plans to withdraw 50,000 troops, half of
its force, from Cambodia by the end of the year and the rest by
early 1990.
   Zhao's remarks came Tuesday in an interview with Shinji Sakai,
president of Japan's Kyodo News Service, at the coastal resort of
Beidaihe. They were reported Wednesday by Kyodo staff members who
attended and the official Chinese Xinhua News Agency.
   Zhao, a leading proponent of economic reform with senior leader
Deng Xiaoping, said the Politburo was convened Monday to discuss
the comprehensive five-year program. The Politburo is China's
highest decision-making body.
   The general secretary said the package would be adopted in
principle by the Politburo and could be put into effect starting at
the beginning of next year.
   Zhao said the government will give priority to reform of
state-run enterprises _ giving them more independence and making
them liable for losses. The key to better efficiency lies in making
all enterprises compete for markets, promoting the better ones and
eliminating the inferior ones, he said.
   China's state-run enterprises operate under the control of local
party officials and central planners. The nation's private
enterprises already enjoy a large measure of autonomy.
   Zhao also told the Japanese that price reform, another key goal,
cannot succeed unless the economy becomes more efficient.
   The government is moving to lift price controls and let prices
be determined by market value, but producers cannot keep up with
rising demand. He said the problem helped push consumer inflation
rates to near 20 percent in the first half of the year.
   ``Whether we can in the course of reform check excessive price
rises will be the deciding factor in whether the reform program for
the next year is carried out smoothly,'' Zhao said. ``Sharp
inflation could erode people's confidence in economic reform.''
   The government raised interest rates on loans and savings
accounts Tuesday in an effort to discourage capital investment and
encourage personal savings. State banks have also announced they
will curtail loans to cool off the economy, which grew at an
excessively rapid pace of 11 percent in the first half of the year.
   Zhao denied reports in the foreign press that the annual summer
policy meetings at the Beidaihe resort broke down in late July
because of a split over how to handle rising prices.
   ``We didn't even have a meeting then,'' he said. ``How could we
suspend it?''
   The general secretary said in regard to Chinese-Soviet relations
that the Soviet stance on Vietnam's withdrawal from Cambodia
remains the key to whether a Chinese-Soviet summit will take place
in the near future.
   In saying that a summit hinged only on Moscow's urging Vietnam
to leave Cambodia, Zhao appeared to tone down China's past tough
conditions for high-level talks. Previously, China stressed that
the Soviet Union must first bring about an actual withdrawal by
exerting its influence.
   Zhao said he was confident senior leaders from the two countries
will meet when conditions are ripe.
   Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev has sought an end to decades of
hostility between the two communist giants and proposed a summit
with Deng and other Chinese leaders.
   Deng, however, has said he will meet Gorbachev only when the
Kremlin removes what China calls the ``three obstacles,''
particularly Soviet support for Vietnam's invasion of Cambodia.
   The other two obstacles, now being lifted, are Soviet troops in
Afghanistan and military tensions along the Chinese-Soviet border.
   China, the main backer of the communist Khmer Rouge and other
resistance forces fighting the 10-year occupation by Vietnam, and
the Soviet Union will meet with Chinese leaders later this month to
discuss the Cambodian question for the first time.
   Zhao said he hoped the vice minister-level talks would resolve
differences between the two countries in one session. He gave no
date.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
