<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--China-Storm,0154</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storms Kill 163 In Central China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain and floods in central Shaanxi province
killed 163 people, bringing the toll of storm-related deaths this
year to more than 1,600, the official Xinhua News Agency said
Wednesday.
   It said the latest weekend storm set off mountain torrents that
destroyed 3,000 homes, 14,326 acres of farmland, 167 miles of roads
and 16 bridges.
   The government air-dropped food supplies to stranded people,
according to the Central Flood Control Headquarters.
   It said typhoons and floods have caused $1.2 billion in damage
in the first seven months of the year.
   In Henan province east of Shaanxi, rains and flash floods killed
34 people and destroyed 20,000 homes over the past nine days,
according to Radio Beijing, monitored in Tokyo.
   In northeastern Heilongjiang province, Xinhua said 120,000
people are working to buttress the banks of the rain-swollen Nen
River.
