<HEAD>Two Convicted of Damaging Jewish Graves in Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Moscow city court convicted two men of smashing
46 Jewish gravestones, the weekly newspaper Moscow News said
Wednesday, after the vandalism raised fears of a tide of
anti-Semitism.
   The paper said survivors were divided on whether the attack at
Moscow's Vostryakovo Cemetery stemmed from anti-Semitism or
represented only a random act.
   Moscow News, which reported the May 15 vandalism soon after it
occurred, said Alexander Yershov and Pavel Lyashenko were found
guilty after an emotional trial attended by many survivors of those
whose graves were smashed.
   Yershov and Lyashenko had been drinking beer, cognac and
champagne before and during their visit to the grave of Lyashenko's
father in a different part of the cemetery, the newspaper said.
   It said Yershov was sentenced to 13 months of corrective work at
his workplace and Lyashenko was given a 2{-year term in a labor
camp.
