<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile-Strike     08-18 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Strike,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Chilean Labor Leaders Convicted For Calling Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Wednesday convicted
three labor leaders of violating internal security laws for calling
a national strike that challenged the economic policies of military
leader Augusto Pinochet.
   The strike led to anti-government riots in which three people
died.
   In another case, the court upheld a ruling that journalist
Fernando Paulsen be tried on charges of slandering the armed
forces, and a military prosecutor ordered opposition politician
Felipe Sandoval arrested on similar charges.
   Leaders of the National Workers' Command, Chile's main labor
confederation, called an illegal general strike on Oct. 7 to
protest the economic policies of Pinochet's right-wing military
government.
   The court on Wednesday ordered Workers' Command President Manuel
Bustos confined for 541 days to the city of Parral, about 210 miles
south of Santiago, and his vice president, Arturo Martinez,
confined for the same amount of time to the town of Channaral,
about 600 miles north of the Chilean capital.
   The court issued a 60-day suspended sentence for the labor
movement's strike coordinator, Moises Labrana.
   A lower court dismissed the charges, but the prosecutors
appealed to the Supreme Court, which overturned the earlier ruling.
   The high court upheld a ruling calling for Paulsen to face a
military trial on charges of slandering the armed forces. Paulsen
is deputy director of the leftist opposition magazine Analysis,
which published an article suggesting that the military accepted an
inflated price in buying navy helicopters.
   A military prosecutor ordered the arrest of Sandoval, a leader
of the Christian Democratic Party's youth wing, on charges of
slandering the armed forces in a television appearance.
   Chilean law allows military prosecutors to order arrests.
</TEXT>
