<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PolishDefector     08-18 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polish Defector,0452</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Polish Defector Says Harassment, Not Love, Moved Him
^By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish folk dancer Sigmund Irinauch came out of
hiding Wednesday and said it was harassment, not love, that caused
him to defect to Israel.
   In his first public appearance since he disappeared in Haifi,
Israel, on Aug. 9, the 29-year-old Irinauch said he left Poland
because authorities hounded his family after he helped organize
labor strikes.
   He denied earlier reports by Israeli newspapers and Haifa police
that he defected because he fell in love with an Israeli dancer he
met two years ago at a folk dancing festival in Canada.
   ``I would like very much to return to Poland, but I think it
will be better both for me and for my family if I stay here,'' said
Irinauch, who wore a white polo shirt and spoke through a Polish
interpreter on Israel Television.
   ``The reasons for my defection have to do only with me and my
family, and they are much more serious (than his reported
romance).''
   The woman's friends said earlier she told him she was engaged
before he came to Israel, but he decided to defect anyway. They
said the woman and her fiance agreed to help Irinauch defect.
   Irinauch said his problems with communist authorities began
after he helped organize workers' strikes in April and May in his
native Krakow.
   ``I was a law student, and we organized protests,'' he said. ``I
was one of the chief organizers and was chosen to represent the
rest before the authorities. As a result, the authorities started
to harass not only me but my family as well.''
   He gave no details about what form the harassment took.
   The Krakow strikes were part of a 15-day national wave of labor
unrest. Security police put down the strike at the Lenin steelworks
outside Krakow on May 5, arresting 38 people.
   Irinauch said his maternal grandmother is Jewish, which means he
too is Jewish by Israeli law and therefore would qualify for
automatic citizenship.
   He said he decided to live at the Ayelet Hashachar kibbutz, or
collective farm, in northern Galilee and enrolled in an intensive
Hebrew class. Irinauch said he chose the kibbutz because it offered
foreign volunteers work, room and board.
   Irinauch came to Israel with the 46-member Slovianki Polish folk
dancing troupe and was described as one of its star dancers.
   Troupe members, who were performing at a folk festival in Haifa,
searched for Irinauch for hours before departing for Poland last
week. The dancer left them a note telling them he was staying
behind.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880818-0252 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0207EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--AnthemSinger     08-18 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Anthem Singer,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Washington Girl Gets Star-Spangled Attention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID AMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten-year-old Heather Ostrom, a rock-music fan
who likes singing to large audiences, drew thunderous cheers at the
Republican National Convention on Wednesday with her rendition of
the national anthem.
   ``Glad it's over!'' the Bonney Lake, Wash., girl cried to her
mother, Carolee, when she bounced away from the podium. ``I sounded
froggy, like Peewee Herman.''
   Heather, a professional singer since she was 5, belted out ``The
Star-Spangled Banner'' a cappella with a country lilt. When she was
through, she flashed a shy grin, and the place erupted with
applause.
   She admitted to a slight case of nerves.
   ``It was really a neat experience, but when you're starting to
sing it, it's scary. You don't ever get used to it. But when I got
started, it was just great,'' she said in an interview after she
joined the Washington state delegation on the convention floor,
receiving hugs and congratulations.
   ``I really like singing before larger audiences than to two or
three people,'' said Heather, a blonde clad in a new white knit and
lace dress.
   The national anthem is fun to sing ``because of all the high
notes'' and isn't as difficult as many people think, she said.
   But she confided, ``I do get a little tired of it.''
   Heather often appears with her 11-year-old sister Kirsten and
their mother. The three sang for about 15 minutes as delegates
arrived at the convention hall, performing mostly pop and
inspirational music.
   Heather said she prefers rock music, probably will become an
artist rather than an entertainer and listed ``my mom and my
sister'' as her favorite singers.
   She said her older sister wasn't jealous that she was invited to
sing at the convention by Republican National Committee Chairman
Frank Fahrenkopf, who learned of the family from state party
chairman Jennifer Dunn.
   ``It all evens out _ she got to do the David Letterman Show,''
said Heather, who will be a fifth grader this fall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
