<2ND_LINE>AM-Digest Briefs,1124</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: This package does not contain the following items from the
News Digest: NEW ORLEANS _ Convention Rdp; NEW ORLEANS _ CVN--Bush;
NEW ORLEANS _ CVN--Quayle-Guard; ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ Pakistan;
BONN, West Germany _ Bandits; HELENA, Mont. _ Montana Fires; LOS
ANGELES _ Frequent Flier;
^By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It is 1969, Danny Quayle is graduating from
college and at 22 years old he is facing the shared dilemma of his
generation: what to do about Vietnam. He's lucky, he has options.
Nineteen years later, his decision casts a shadow on the Republican
National Convention.
   The Bush campaign wanted a baby boomer, they got one, and he
carries the baggage of his generation. This is not World War II
we're talking about, this is the Vietnam War and millions of kids
were trying to avoid it.
   In Quayle's case, he is wrestling with the image of a rich kid
who chose law school over Vietnam and traded on his family
influence to make his dreams come true.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel on Thursday outlawed grass-roots
committees that carry out the orders of the Palestinian uprising's
leaders, and Red Cross and hospital officials said troops beat more
than 250 Arabs in four days of unrest in the occupied Gaza Strip.
   Also on Thursday, Palestinians launched a two-day general strike
in the West Bank to protest Israel's policy of deporting those it
deems activists in the eight-month uprising. Word of the impromptu
strike was passed around the West Bank by masked youths, many of
whom shouted their message on loudspeakers.
   A three-day curfew was lifted before dawn Thursday from much of
the Gaza Strip, but 180,000 Arabs in 11 refugee camps and
neighborhoods remained confined to their homes. In addition, 85,000
West Bank Palestinians from nine villages and camps were under
curfew.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pro-Iranian kidnappers who hold at least
two Americans said Thursday the hostages won't be freed soon and
compared predictions of their release to a desert mirage.
   There has been speculation some or all of the 18 foreign
hostages, who include nine Americans, would be released now that
Iran has accepted a cease-fire in its 8-year-old war with Iraq.
   Thursday's declaration was in a statement from Islamic Jihad, or
Islamic Holy War, delivered to the Beirut office of a Western news
agency with a photograph of captive journalist Terry A. Anderson.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House has halted cooperation with a
congressional study of alleged drug trafficking by Panamanian ruler
Manuel Antonio Noriega, administration and congressional officials
confirmed Thursday.
   In Miami, Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis
accused the administration of ``stonewalling'' the General
Accounting Office probe, which potentially could delve into
Republican nominee George Bush's knowledge about the Noriega case.
Administration officials argued they needed time to ``review'' the
GAO's requests for information.
   ``I think the White House does not want to cooperate because
they are embarrassed by this. They should be embarrassed by this,''
Dukakis said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Regional disparities in personal incomes
widened in 1987, as booming coastal states continued to outstrip
wage gains in much of the rest of the nation, the government
reported Thursday.
   The Commerce Department said all 10 of the states with the
highest average personal incomes last year were on the nation's
coasts, eight along the Atlantic and Alaska and California on the
Pacific.
   Connecticut ranked No. 1 with residents earning $21,266 for
every adult and child last year, an increase of 8.8 percent over
1986.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An intentionally flawed space shuttle
booster rocket performed successfully Thursday in the last
test-firing required before the resumption of manned U.S. space
flights, officials said.
   ``We're ready to go launch,'' Alan McDonald, Morton Thiokol vice
president for engineering, said on examining the booster after the
122-second, horizontal test.
   The $20 million firing was a ``redundancy verification test'' to
make sure the booster's new joints do what they're supposed to:
contain super-heated gases during launch. The failure of the seals
on one joint led to the explosion of shuttle Challenger and the
death of its seven-person crew in 1986.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JASTRZEBIE, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikes spreading through Poland
crippled production at five vital Silesian coal mines Thursday and
paralyzed Szczecin's port and public transport, opposition leaders
said.
   Workers demand higher wages, better working conditions and that
the outlawed Solidarity trade union federation be made legal again.
   Strikes that began Tuesday when employees occupied the July
Manifesto mine, near Jastrzebie in southwestern Poland, spread to a
fifth mine Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The call by Vice President Salvador
Laurel for new presidential elections has attracted little support
and is widely regarded as an attempt to revive his flagging
political fortunes.
   On Aug. 13, Laurel accused President Corazon Aquino of
incompetence and suggested both step down so an election could be
held. She has not responded, but said at the time that he did not
support her during coup attempts in 1986 and 1987.
   The vice president has met with opposition leaders, including
Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile and members of former President Ferdinand
Marcos' New Society Movement.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rolling Stone magazine, long the definitive word
on rock 'n' roll, has chosen the 100 best singles of the past
quarter-century, and the magazine's name is high on the list.
   ``(I Can't Get No) Satisfaction'' by the Rolling Stones topped
the list, followed by Bob Dylan's ``Like a Rolling Stone.'' The
Beatles were third with ``I Wanna Hold Your Hand'' and its flip
side, ``I Saw Her Standing There.''
   The Rolling Stones hit the list three more times: at No. 27 with
``Honky Tonk Women''; at No. 68 with ``Jumpin' Jack Flash''; and at
No. 74 with ``Brown Sugar.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stillwater National Wildlife Refuge becomes
the nation's second Western Hemisphere Shorebird Reserve this
weekend, but the honor may be a hollow one for the ailing swamp.
   ``Things are looking pretty bleak right now,'' said Norm Saake,
a waterfowl biologist for the Nevada Department of Wildlife. He
predicts that 80 percent of the marshes in the 164,000-acre refuge
will be dried up by the end of the summer.
   Racked by back-to-back drought years that have distilled the
wetlands to a suffocating, toxin-ridden stew, the refuge 60 miles
east of Reno has become a murky grave to more than 7 million fish
and 2,000 birds in the past 18 months.
</TEXT>
