<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WeekendTV-NewsPromo ADV02-04   08-18 0906</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekend TV-News Promo, ADV02-04,0931</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 2-4, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Promotions for TV News: Too Cute, Coy, Concocted?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a television news commercial filmed in
documentary style, a camera takes the viewer into a hospital, past
waiting news reporters in the corridors and up to the rooftop
heliport.
   A trench-coated reporter is interviewing an accident victim as
he is being eased onto a stretcher. And the victim has been brought
to the hospital in the news team's helicopter.
   Watch WTNH in New Haven, Conn., and you'll get the story ahead
of everyone else, the announcer explains. Especially the story just
shown. It never happened.
   Across the continent in Los Angeles, viewers of KNBC see news
anchorman John Beard and anchorwoman Linda Alvarez share a fan
letter. The fan says Beard deserves a hug and a ``there, there''
pat when he's telling folks bad news.
   Then Beard reads a compliment for ducking under his desk during
the Oct. 2 earthquake. Wrong anchorman. That was morning news
anchorman Kent Shocknek.``Yo, Kent, mail call,'' Beard says,
rapping the desk top.
   Promotions for television news shows _ cute, coy or concocted _
have slipped out of the narrow restrictions that once dictated that
such spots feature only the depth and capability of the news team.
   The new generation of commercials are forged from years of
behind-the-scenes wars between news and promotion departments. Did
one side win?
   ``I would say it's kind of a meeting of the minds,'' said Jay
Curtis, member services manager of the Broadcast Promotion &
Marketing Executives. ``The advertisements are taking the content
of news and fitting it into the form of promotion.''
   Curtis estimated that concocted news events were featured in 20
percent of the 600 news promotions the BPME received recently for
its gold medallion awards.
   Although the scenario for the WTNH commercial ``was not based on
a specific event, it was indicative of things that happen at
hospitals,'' said WTNH Promotion Manager Donald Cohen. He said
there had been no negative comments from the public or journalists
about the spot.
   WTNH, an ABC affilliate, has been running a neck-and-neck
ratings war with WFSB, the Hartford-based CBS affiliate, Cohen said.
   ``I find that promotion directors use as a litmus test for
themselves whether they can make their news No. 1,'' Curtis said,
adding that the tighter the market, the tougher the promotion
campaign. ``When the news gets the numbers, everything else falls
into place.''
   ``They were a pretty boring station when they hired me,'' said
former KNBC promotion manager Vince Manze, now an executive vice
president with Steve Sohmer, Inc. ``My mandate was to put some life
in the station. The network had taken off, the local station had
not,'' he said.
   Cohen said he was prepared for criticism of the WTNH commercial.
``I was ready to explain the thinking that went behind the spot,
and we were prepared to put the word `dramatization' over it.''
   But Cohen said the viewers of WTNH were sophisticated enough to
understand the commercial was not a real event.
   ``But we wanted to make sure we were doing something that was
actually related to covering the news,'' he said.
   The commercial for KNBC was one of several spots devised by
Chuck Blore and Don Richman Inc. that involves on-camera reporters.
   The first series of ads featured weather reporter Fritz Coleman
and sports reporter Fred Roggin facing off on the basketball court
or marathon course. In the former, Coleman fries Roggin with
lightning after the sportscaster's half-court razzle dazzle.
   The newest KNBC spot features KNBC anchorwomen Kelly Lange and
Colleen Williams discussing the propriety of anchormen and
anchorwomen doing such a commercial. The women decide not to, and
walk off the basketball court.
   ``You can't play around with the news,'' Blore said in an
interview. He said his guidelines for promoting KNBC's news forbade
him from concocting events, but had to grab the attention of the
public. He and KNBC management settled on using personalities from
the station, usually in a scripted comedy piece.
   ``A couple of years ago, it would have been shocking to put news
people in a comedy situation,'' said Blore. ``I was even a little
hesitant about it.'' For one of the commercials, Blore associate
Bill McDonald had to write 19 scripts before finding the right
balance between promoting the news and avoiding perceived
credibility damage.
   The trend is not pleasing to everyone in the industry.
   ``I think it's easy to do bizarre and different and silly
campaigns and avoid the nuts and bolts of what goes into the
news,'' said KABC Los Angeles Director of Advertising and Promotion
Bob Burris.
   His station, rated No. 1 locally, concentrates on the experience
and recognition of its reporters, anchormen and anchorwomen.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in Television:
   VIDEO VICTORS... The Video Software Dealers Association _
retailers who sell and rent tapes _ has named ``Dirty Dancing'' as
the top video release of the past year, but ``Top Gun'' won the
honors for best-selling videocassette. Along with ``Top Gun,''
video winners from Paramount studios included ``Fatal Attraction''
for best drama and ``Crocodile Dundee'' for best comedy. The VSDA
Awards are based on ballots mailed to 3,000 store-owner members.
``Lethal Weapon'' won in the action adventure category, ``Lady and
the Tramp,'' children's, and ``The Lost Boys,'' horror.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Sept. 2-4</NOTE>
