<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction rose a moderate 2.4
percent in July, the government reports, but economists warn that
rising mortgage rates could make the two-month housing rebound a
brief one.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that new homes and
apartments were built at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.49
million units last month after advancing 4.4 percent in June.
   Housing starts dropped a sharp 12.1 percent in May to the
slowest pace in three years, and rising mortgage rates were blamed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fewer housing units were built during the second
quarter of 1988 than a year ago, reflecting continued softness in
the rental housing market, a research group has reported.
   For the April-June period, new housing construction slipped 9
percent to 406,882 units, compared with 446,955 units built during
the second quarter of 1987, said the F.W. Dodge Group of
McGraw-Hill Information Services Co. on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farm subsidies in the United States and Europe
that were enacted to cope with domestic gluts are continuing even
though the drought has cut stockpiles and raised prices.
   Subsidies encourage overproduction, keep farmers dependent on
their governments for support, hurt farm exports of developing
nations and cost taxpayers billions of dollars.
   The drought created an opportunity to phase out the subsidies by
pushing up worldwide market prices closer to the prices that the
United States and Europeans guarantee to their farmers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a year after the United States slapped
penalty tariffs on Japan for allegedly violating an agreement on
semiconductor trade, Japanese officials are stepping up pressure on
Washington to remove the penalties before President Reagan leaves
office.
   U.S. officials counter that the Japanese government is
continuing to renege on a pledge to boost the market share of
imported U.S. chips.
   The $300 million in tariffs, since reduced to $165 million, were
the strongest trade retaliation the United States has taken against
Japan since World War II.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan will increase investment in Mexico,
import more Mexican goods and ``seriously consider'' Mexican
proposals for reducing its massive foreign debt, Japanese officials
say.
   On Wednesday, the officials praised Mexico's attempt to
restructure its economy and said Japan, one of the world's
mightiest creditors and exporters, look forward to increasing
imports of Mexican goods.
   Mexico's inflation-fighting plan, a pact between government,
business and labor to restrain prices and wages, is credited with
sharply reducing the record 159.2 percent inflation Mexico suffered
last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Food and Drug Administration
has given approval for Upjohn Co. to market the first hair-growth
formula in the United States.
   Rogaine will become the first prescription drug on the market
designed to stimulate hair growth on men with male-pattern
baldness, company officials said Wednesday.
   It is scheduled to hit the market in up to six weeks. Price has
not been determined, the company said.
</TEXT>
