<TEXT>
   A former Merrill Lynch & Co. stockbroker
has pleaded guilty to engaging in a scheme in which he illicitly
obtained advance copies of Business Week, then reaped profits from
trading stocks mentioned in the magazine.
   William Dillon, 33, who was dismissed last month from Merrill
Lynch's New London office, on Wednesday became the first person to
be criminally charged in the widening insider-trading scandal
involving leaked copies of Business Week.
</TEXT>
