<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     08-18 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Housing Starts Up for 2nd Straight Month In July</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says housing starts rose for the second straight
month in July, but some economists say rising interests rates could
make the construction rebound short-lived.
   The Commerce Department reported Wednesday that new home and
apartment construction was up 2.4 percent last month after rising
4.4 percent in June.
   Housing starts dropped a sharp 12.1 percent in May, and
economists blamed rising mortgage rates for the slowdown.
   The June-July recovery was attributed to stabilized mortgage
rates, but that trend was thrown into question last week when the
Federal Reserve boosted the discount rate, the interest it charges
for loans to member banks.
   A variety of other interest rates _ including mortgage rates _
moved higher as a result of the Fed action. Fixed-rate mortgages
averaged 10.57 percent nationwide by the end of last week and
analysts predicted mortgages soon would top 11 percent.
   The Commerce Department report had little impact on financial
markets.
   Bond traders brushed off the July figures, and Treasury issues
closed narrowly mixed.
   Meanwhile, the dollar surged against major foreign currencies,
despite action by the Fed and the West German central bank to limit
the dollar's climb against the West German mark.
   On Wall Street, stocks finished mixed in a slow session. The Dow
Jones industrial average closed up 4.45 points to 2,025.96.
   The Commerce Department also reported Wednesday that housing
permits, considered a good barometer of future activity, fell in
July by 5.4 percent to an annual rate of 1.41 million units.
   Economists were pessimistic about the construction report.
   ``I believe we have seen the peak for housing starts this year
as rising interest rates cut into sales,'' said Richard Peach, an
economist with the Mortgage Bankers Association, a trade group.
   Sales of homes and other high-priced items usually are the first
to fall off when the Federal Reserve tries to dampen inflation by
raising interest rates.
   Michael Sumichrast, an economist and publisher of a construction
industry newsletter, said that if mortgage rates climb to 11.5
percent or higher, it could hit the housing industry hard. He said
home sales already have been hurt by big price increases in many
parts of the country.
   Separately, a private survey found fewer housing units were
built during the second quarter of 1988 than the same period a year
ago.
   For the April-June period, new housing construction slipped 9
percent to 406,882 units, compared with 446,955 units built during
the second quarter of 1987, the F.W. Dodge Group of McGraw-Hill
Information Services Co. said.
   George A. Christie, chief economist for F.W. Dodge, said most of
the decline was in rental housing, where high vacancy rates have
hindered new apartment construction.
   Construction of single-family homes remained steady during the
period, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880818-0270 </DOCNO>
