<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SchererFight     08-18 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scherer Fight,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scherer Proxy Vote To Be Announced In One Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TROY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident family shareholders pushing for a
buyout of R.P. Scherer Corp. say they are confident they won two of
three board of directors seats considered instrumental in their
attempt, but are unsure of the third.
   Scherer stockholders cast proxy votes at a meeting Wednesday to
fill the three seats. Results were scheduled to be announced next
Wednesday, said Peter R. Fink, the pharmaceutical capsule company's
president and chief executive.
   In national over-the-counter trading, Scherer closed up $1.37{ a
share to $26.25.
   John S. Scherer and his sister Karla Scherer Fink, the estranged
wife of Peter Fink, have spearheaded the effort to win the three
seats as a prelude to attempting to arrange a buyout of the company.
   The two, who are children of the company's late founder, Robert
P. Scherer, control 38.2 percent of the company's outstanding
shares. Karla Fink filed for divorce from her husband several
months ago.
   John Scherer said he was encouraged by a state Court of Appeals
ruling Wednesday that barred the voting of a 9.8 percent block of
the company's stock in the proxy contest.
   Schere and his sister are beneficiaries of a trust at
Manufacturers Bank of Detroit that holds the block and have sought
to prevent the bank from voting the shares, saying it had a
conflict of interest because of business dealings with Scherer.
   The trustee had indicated it planned to back management in the
proxy fight.
   In a statement released after the meeting, John Scherer said the
pair was ``confident our candidates had won the two board
seats...We were not certain about the third seat. But as the
meeting progressed and we learned the bank could not vote the
trust, our optimism increased.''
   About 200 people attended the calm, hourlong annual meeting at a
Troy hotel. Arguments for both sides drew applause.
   Karla Scherer Fink urged selling the company now, in the wake of
two yearas of record corporate earnings. ``There is no guarantee
this level of profitability will continue,'' she said.
   ``There are interested potential buyers watching closely what
goes on here today,'' she said. ``But they will not come forward in
the kind of hostile environment the management has created.''
   But Peter Fink said, ``A stockholder who seeks full value for
his or her investment in Scherer will not find it on the auction
block today.''
   The board determined after thorough analysis that shareholders
would best be served if the company remained independent, he said.
However, Fink also said there had been no offers to date to buy the
company.
   While management does not intend to ``put a for-sale sign on the
door,'' he said, ``If a bona fide offer were to emerge, it would
clearly be our board's duty to give it thorough and full
consideration.''
   Scherer, which employs about 2,800 people at 22 facilities in 13
countries, is the world's largest maker of gelatin capsules for the
pharmaceutical and nutritional supplement industries. The company
had $290.7 million in sales and $15.1 million in net income in its
last fiscal year, ended March 31.
   Karla Fink and her brother control about 38.2 percent of the
company. The support of another shareholder, Cilluffo Associates,
brought the total shares backing the pair to 39.9 percent.
</TEXT>
