<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0337EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-KodakUnit     08-18 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kodak Unit,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kodak Decides to Keep Sterling Household Products Business</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No one was willing to pay Eastman Kodak
Co. its asking price for the profitable household products group of
the recently-acquired Sterling Drug Co., so Kodak has decided to
keep it.
   Kay Whitmore, Kodak's president and executive officer, said
Wednesday that Kodak had decided not to sell the Lehn & Fink unit
of Sterling, which makes Lysol disinfectant, D-Con pesticides and
other products.
   Whitmore also said the unit ``is too important to lose.''
   Kodak bought Sterling Drug for $5.1 billion earlier this year in
a ``white knight'' maneuver to thwart a hostile takeover attempt of
Sterling by Swiss pharmaceutical giant F. Hoffman-LaRoche & Co.
   Published reports and rumors on Wall Street in recent weeks
indicated Kodak was planning to sell the Montvale, N.J.-based Lehn
& fink unit, which had sales of $594 million last year.
   Many stock analysts believe that if Kodak could have found a
buyer, it would have sold the unit with little hesitation.
   ``I'm not surprised they're keeping it,'' said Mark Obenzinger,
an analyst with the brokerage firm Wood, Gundy & Co. in New York.
``They couldn't get the price they wanted. They paid top dollar for
it, so they have to get top, top dollar for it.''
   Eugene Glazer, an analyst for Dean Witter Reynolds in New York,
expressed similar sentiments but noted that one reason Kodak needed
to get a higher price for the unit was to cover the hefty tax bill
that would have been levied on the deal.
   Tax law changes in 1986 make it harder, or at least more
expensive, for buyers to sell off the unwanted businesses of
acquired companies, Glazer said.
   Because of the new law, Kodak would have to pay ``hundreds of
millions'' of dollars in taxes if it sold Lehn & Fink, he said.
   ``So Kodak had to add that onto the price and I think that
discouraged people from buying,'' Glazer said.
   Lehn & Fink still does not fit into Kodak's strategic plans, but
analysts said it is a successful and well-run company that will not
hurt Kodak's bottom line.
   Whitmore told Lehn & Fink employees in Montvale Wednesday that a
study about the relationship between Kodak and the household
products unit had turned up many positive things.
   He said he envisioned Lehn & Fink marketing products that might
be developed by Kodak's chemical division; Kodak using its strength
in convenience store outlets to get Lehn & Fink products onto more
store shelves; and Kodak helping market Lehn & Fink's products
overseas.
   Whitmore said that while Kodak originally just had interest in
Sterling Drug's pharmaceutical operations, Kodak's broader strategy
always had included expansion of Sterling's consumer products
presence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
