<DOCNO> AP880818-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0342EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-AMC-TPI     08-18 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AMC-TPI,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AMC To Sell 40 Percent Of Its Theaters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AMC Entertainment Inc. announced
Wednesday it planned to sell about 40 percent of its screens for
about $200 million to New York-based TPI Enterprises Inc.
   The Kansas City movie theater chain, which owns almost 25
percent of TPI's stock, will manage the theaters that are sold. The
theaters also are expected to retain the AMC name, and AMC would
retain its ability to negotiate films for all of the screens.
   The AMC sale, which involves 605 of AMC's 1,549 screens, is not
expected to affect the company's estimated 7,800 employees.
   TPI operates a paging and mobile telephone business in Puerto
Rico and recently acquired Shoney's South Inc., a restaurant
company.
   Analysts said that although the transaction immediately would
pump much-needed cash into debt-burdened AMC, it was unclear how
much revenue AMC would lose in the long term because of the sale.
   AMC's debt has swollen to about $376 million due to an
aggressive expansion that began a few years ago. Although AMC grew
under the expansion to become the country's second-largest movie
exhibitor, its debts and losses also have increased.
   AMC's losses more than doubled, to $13.7 million, in its latest
fiscal year, ended March 31. AMC then reported that its
first-quarter losses amounted to $7.6 million, more than half of
all of last year's losses.
   Steven Zell, AMC's senior vice president of finance, would not
say where the 605 screens were, but he said they were in 90
theaters mostly in the Southeast. All the theaters are in buildings
for which AMC has long-term leases, he said.
   Zell said AMC thought that it was important to reorganize its
balance sheet and reduce the company's debt. He said AMC was
expected to receive $150 million in cash and a $50 million note
from TPI for the screens.
</TEXT>
