<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against most major currencies in
moderately active European trading early today. Gold prices rose.
   Dealers said the market pushed the dollar lower in a technical
reaction to its sharp rally Wednesday.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose 0.78 Japanese yen to a closing 133.93 yen. Later,
in London, it fell back to 133.72 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.9040 West German marks, down from
1.9123; 1.5980 Swiss francs, down from 1.6025; 6.4525 French
francs, down from 6.4750; 2.1552 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1550;
1,409.75 Italian lire, up from 1,401.50; 1.2295 Canadian dollars,
down from 1.2323.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.6950 from $1.6905 late
Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $429.10 a troy ounce, up
from $428.50 bid late Wednesday. At mid-morning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $430.20.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $430.25, up from $428.50 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 97 cents to close at a bid
$432.28.
   Silver bullion rose to a bid price of $6.65 a troy ounce, up
from $6.62 bid late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
