<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     08-18 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Lose Ground</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted higher against the Japanese yen
today, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost ground.
   Opening at 134.00 yen, a 0.85 yen leap from Wednesday's close,
the dollar ranged between 133.73 and 134.10 yen, finishing at
133.93 yen, up 0.78 yen.
   The foreign exchange market remains bullish toward the dollar
for the moment, due to the currency's quick recovery despite the
wide U.S. trade deficit for June, according to a commercial bank
dealer who requested anonymity.
   ``The dollar is basically firm, but profit-taking pushes it down
when it surpasses the 134.00 mark,'' another bank dealer said,
adding that the dollar will stay within the 132.00 to 134.00 yen
range for a while.
   Spot trading totaled $4.155 billion, down from Wednesday's
$5.256 billion.
   After opening higher at 28,291.11 points, the Nikkei Stock
Average of 255 selected issues, which gained 282.31 points the
previous day, edged down 49.50 points from Wednesday's close, or
0.18 percent, to close at 28,129.36 points.
   The afternoon session slowed down, with a total of 750 million
shares, compared with 500 million shares traded on the first
session.
   The market's loss is just a little break after the previous
day's hectic business, said a stock dealer at a major securities
firm in Tokyo, requesting anonymity.
   Steel- and finance-related stocks did not do as well as on
Wednesday, he added.
   Other brokers said the loss is, in part, due to profit-taking by
institutional investors centering on giant-capital issues.
</TEXT>
