<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 0740EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-DetroitNewspapers Bjt   08-18 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Detroit Newspapers, Bjt,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Officials Disappointed With JOA Restraining Order</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUSTIN BURKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge stunned the publishers of the
Detroit News and Detroit Free Press by temporarily blocking today's
scheduled merger of the newspapers' business operations, saying the
plan would do ``irreparable'' harm.
   U.S. District Judge Joyce Hens Green issued an emergency order
Wednesday preventing the joint operating agreement between the
newspapers from taking effect. The JOA will be postponed until at
least Sept. 17.
   Former Attorney General Edwin Meese III approved the JOA before
leaving office last week. Both newspapers sought the agreement
under an antitrust exemption of the Newspaper Preservation Act.
   William B. Schultz, an attorney representing a group of
advertisers and readers, had argued that Meese arbitrarily ignored
an administrative law judge's finding that neither daily qualified
for the antitrust exemption as a ``failing newspaper.''
   Green agreed with Schultz' contention, saying, ``Consolidation
of the Free Press and the News will harm their employees, their
advertisers and their customers as well. ... Besides being
immediate, these injuries will also be irreparable.''
   Knight-Ridder Inc., which owns the Free Press, has said it will
close the morning newspaper if the partial merger doesn't go
through, meaning the loss of 1,500 jobs. Alvah Chapman, the
company's chairman, has said the Free Press sustained $100 million
in operating losses since 1979.
   ``I am very disappointed,'' said Free Press Publisher David
Lawrence. ``It (the decision) seems to me to be so cruel to all the
individuals involved.
   ``The people of the Free Press have gone through 28 months of
uncertainty and now they still don't know what will happen to them
and this newspaper.''
   Frank Hawkins, spokesman for Miami-based Knight-Ridder, said the
parent company was studying its options.
   Louis Weil, publisher of The Detroit News, said he was stunned
by Green's decision, issued in Washington, D.C.
   ``Everything was ready to go,'' Weil said. ``But now with the
restraining order we will go back to what we were doing before and
that is putting out a fine newspaper.''
   Green scheduled a hearing for Sept. 8.
   Both papers rank among the nation's 10 largest in terms of
circulation but each has posted significant losses in recent years
in a continuing battle to dominate Detroit's newspaper market.
   Since applying for the joint operating status in May 1986, the
two newspapers together have lost $45 million to $50 million, said
Philip A. Lacovara, an attorney for the Free Press.
   Officials of Knight-Ridder and Gannett Co. Inc., owners of the
News, said they expected the JOA to return the newspapers to
profitability.
   Under the partial merger, the Free Press would remain a morning
newspaper while the News, which has published as a 24-hour paper,
would publish evening editions on weekdays. The papers would
publish joint weekend editions. About 500 jobs at the two papers
would be eliminated by the consolidation.
   In 1987, the Free Press had a circulation of 639,720 daily and
724,342 on Sundays while News' circulation was 678,720 daily and
839,319 on Sundays, according to the Audit Bureau of Circulation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
