<1ST_LINE>u f PM-JobSeekers Bjt   08-18 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Job Seekers, Bjt,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Lives In Tent While Job Hunting</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH KIRKPATRICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARLISLE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four months after leaving home, Richard and
Maureen Johns are camped on the edge of despair, living in a tent
with their four young children and searching for the good job
supposedly here for the asking.
   The family remains unfazed by a summer of searing heat and
sinking finances. They came here from Pittsburgh 2{ months ago and
have been sleeping in a 9-by-9-foot tent and eating in a screened
canopy at the Western Village Park and Campground while Johns looks
for a steady, decent-paying job.
   ``No, no,'' said Mrs. Johns, when asked whether her spirits had
fallen. ``I'm not depressed yet. ... If we're living here in
November, then I'll be concerned.''
   As her husband talked with a reporter, Mrs. Johns prepared
peanut butter and jelly sandwiches for the children: Mary
Katherine, 7; Ben, 5; Elizabeth, 4 and Brian, 2.
   Bikes were scattered about the campsite. Some belongings were
kept under a tarp next to the tent. The family's 1976 Ford station
wagon was parked nearby.
   Johns said he moved his family out of their Pittsburgh home June
1 after reading news accounts about plenty of jobs around Carlisle,
a small central Pennsylvania town in an area with a rising economy.
The town sits near an important north-south junction, Interstate 81
and the Pennsylvania Turnpike.
   ``Coming from job-depressed Pittsburgh, it sounded great,'' he
said.
   Once here, Johns, 33, who has training in electronics, could
find only fast-food and truck-driving jobs. He has worked several
temporary jobs, including one for the telephone company, but has
yet to come up with something permanent.
   He has sought help from the state Job Service and local programs
and had expected his search would end by this month.
   Experienced campers, the Johns enjoyed the prospect of a summer
outdoors, but now worry about how they'll meet another $235 monthly
payment on Sept. 1 to stay at the campground.
   ``The money's getting tight,'' Johns said.
   The site has electricity and restrooms. Relatives have given
them a small refrigerator and electric skillet. They drive about 15
minutes away to a roadside spring for drinking water. For a change
of scene, they've driven to nearby state parks and a cousin gave
them tickets to Hersheypark amusement park.
   ``The kids consider it a vacation,'' Johns said. ``They love it.
They really enjoy it.''
   Married eight years, the Johns endured similar frustrating job
hunting in Pittsburgh. He said he sent out 240 resumes and got only
one interview. Although they invested many improvements into their
Pittsburgh home, they feel no point in returning and are trying to
sell the house. The real estate agent believes it will be tough
with so many houses on the market, they said.
   ``The saying is, `The grass is always greener on the other
side,''' Johns said. ``Back in Pittsburgh, the grass is dead.''
   He said he refuses to give up on central Pennsylvania and feels
it has an optimism about the economy that is missing in western
Pennsylvania, which has been hurt by the slump in steel, coal and
other core industries in the last decade.
   ``If I stay and be persistent, something is going to come up,''
he said. ``There's no alternative. I can't go back to Pittsburgh.
There is nothing to go back to.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
