<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Apple-Microsoft     08-18 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Apple-Microsoft,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Date For Apple Copyright Suit Set For 1989</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. District Judge Robert Aguilar has
imposed a one-year delay on Apple Computer Inc.'s landmark
copyright violation case against Hewlett-Packard Co. and Microsoft
Corp.
   Aguilar, who set the trial date as Aug. 14, 1989, gave no reason
for the decision, which legal experts said will hurt the strategies
of Microsoft and other companies including International Business
Machines Corp. to bring ``Macintosh-like'' traits to IBM-compatible
computers.
   The trial will decide whether Microsoft violated its contract
with Apple, which gave Microsoft the right to use copyrighted
elements of Apple's Macintosh visual display in its software.
   ``Microsoft would like to get the issue resolved as soon as
possible,'' said G. Gervaise Davis, a Monterey attorney
specializing in high-tech law.
   The trial dates apply only to the question of the scope of the
licensing agreement between Microsoft and Apple. Apple's claims
that Microsoft and Hewlett-Packard have produced software
infringing on its copyrights will be decided separately.
   Aguilar in June granted Microsoft's request to break Apple's
suit into those two major elements. The action was designed to
speed up the trial and was considered a victory for Microsoft.
</TEXT>
