<HEAD>Computerland Delays Stock Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAYWARD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Computerland Corp. has decided to put off
going public in light of volatile market conditions that have
created havoc for high-technology stocks.
   The Hayward company said Wednesday it will indefinitely suspend
its first public stock offering, which had been expected this week.
   Computerland, which runs an international chain of independently
owned computer retail stores that sell personal computers, hoped to
sell 4 million shares in the United States and 1 million shares
overseas at a price of $16 to $19, raising $80 million to $95
million. Some of the shares would have been sold by Computerland's
founder, William Millard, and his wife.
   The proposed price range gave Computerland an indicated value of
$254 million to $302 million.
