<HEAD>Pennwalt Announces Sale To Fisons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennwalt Corp. announced today it has
reached an agreement to sell its pharmaceutical operations to the
British firm Fisons for $460 million.
   Edwin E. Tuttle, chairman and chief executive officer of
Pennwalt, said the sale of the worldwide operation could mean a
special dividend or a stock repurchase program. The closing on the
deal, which is subject to shareholder approval, is expected to take
place within the next two to three months.
   Pennwalt had pharmaceutical sales last year of $129.3 million,
representing 11 percent of the company's total 1987 sales of $1.1
billion. Pre-tax earnings for pharmaceuticals was set at $20
million.
   Fisons, headquartered in Ipswich, Suffolk, England, makes
pharmaceuticals, scientific equipment and horiticultural products.
   Pennwalt's pharmaceutical division is headquartered in
Rochester, N.Y. It makes both prescription and over-the-counter
drugs. Prescription products include cardiovascular,
anti-depressant, anorectic and cough-cold products. Name brands
include Microx, Zaroxolyn, Adapin, Ionamin, Tussionex and Penntuss.
   Over-the-counter products include Allerest, Desenex, Cruex,
Sinarest and Caldecort.
   The division also includes the Pharmasol Corp., a specialized
aerosol manufacturer.
</TEXT>
