<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 1310EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-Britain-Unemployment Adv20-21-1stLd-WritkExchange1p.m.index:
  08-18 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Unemployment, Adv 20-21-1st Ld-Writethru,0670</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 20</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Aug. 20-21 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Rate Has Fallen For Two Years, But Critics Claim It Is Massaged</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-6, The jobless ... in 1979., to UPDATE with
latest unemployment figures.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thanks to a strong economy, Britain's persistently
high unemployment rate has fallen sharply, but critics claim the
government is massaging the figures to make them look even better
than they are.
   Opponents of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government agree
that unemployment is down, but say exaggeration in the degree of
improvement is encouraging apathy toward the unemployed.
   The jobless rate has been falling for two years, reaching 8.2
percent in July, its lowest point in nearly seven years, the
Department of Employment says.
   Unemployment has fallen to 2.31 million people from a peak of
11.5 percent, or about 3.31 million in June 1986.
   The decline is the fastest among major Western industrialized
nations, the government says.
   But the Unemployment Unit, a private research and lobby
organization, says the rate would be 10.4 percent, representing
2.98 million people, if the calculation method were the same as
when the Conservatives first came into power in 1979.
   The British figures compare with a West German rate of 8.9
percent in June, which is unchanged from two years earlier, and a
French rate of 10.9 percent in May, which is up from 10.7 percent
two years before.
   An Employment Department spokesman, who requested anonymity,
said: ``We're still reasonably confident that it (ours) is an
accurate measure of unemployment.''
   Lawmaker Michael Meacher, the opposition Labor Party's spokesman
on unemployment, said: ``Unemployment has indeed been going down
over the last two years, but only about half as fast as the
government has been claiming.''
   Peter Kellner, a columnist for the Independent newspaper, wrote:
``If ... the calculations were done differently, it is doubtful
whether the government could claim, or would receive, anything like
the credit that the media and the public now bestow upon it.''
   Paul Convery, a director of the Unemployment Unit, said Britons
have become ``a little bit anesthetized,'' partly because they
generally are feeling better off economically, and partly because
the government has scored ``several sizable propaganda victories.''
   National unemployment registers have been the source for
unemployment statistics in all Common Market countries except
Spain, Portugal and Greece, the Unemployment Unit said.
   In 1982, Britain alone began basing its unemployment rate on the
number claiming unemployment benefits, rather than the number
registered as unemployed, it said.
   Since 1979, the government has made 22 changes in the way it
measures joblessness, all except one of which have reduced the
official unemployment rate, the Unemployment Unit said.
   The government denies that it has made that many changes or that
its alterations are designed to make the numbers look better.
   In a recent monthly unemployment report, the government said it
began counting as employed those people who are in government
training programs. That reduced the unemployment rate by 0.1
percent.
   The unit said the government has removed from the unemployment
benefit lists jobless men over age 60 who receive other kinds of
benefits.
   Part-time workers, whose numbers are increasing, have always
been counted as employed, and many jobless married women aren't
eligible for unemployment benefits, it said.
   Another way of measuring unemployment is to conduct surveys
which ask adults questions about their employment status. This
method is used monthly in the United States.
   In Britain, the government uses the method once a year, and
reveals the results a year later. By the survey method, Britain had
an unemployment rate of 10.7 percent in the spring of 1987. By the
government's regular method, the rate was 10.8 percent.
   ``They are so close that it shows that our own measure is
accurate,'' the department spokesman said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Aug. 20-21</NOTE>
</DOC>
