<DOCNO> AP880818-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 1312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f PM-AnotherLook:TugStrike Adv22   08-18 1060</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Another Look: Tug Strike, Adv 22,1091</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Monday Aug. 22 and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Striking Tugboat Workers Struggle To Be Noticed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE ANDERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For six months, New York's tugboat workers have
been on strike, boycotting the passenger liners and cargo ships
that negotiate the nation's busiest port.
   But no one notices. There has been a sea change in the maritime
industry.
   A 12-day strike in 1946 practically paralyzed the city _ fresh
produce disappeared, coal shortages forced the closing of public
places, Army and Navy tugs were pressed into action. But the 1988
strike, the longest in history, ``really hasn't had an appreciable
effect on shipping,'' said Greg Storey of the New York Shipping
Association.
   And the 2,500 strikers, men like Capt. Vinnie Hilser, fear the
walkout's ineffectiveness signals the end of a way of life.
   ``I've never had another job,'' said Hilser, a resident of
Langhorne, Pa. ``I came out of the Marine Corps and went right to
the tugs. When you're that long in one thing, what else can you
do?''
   Hilser's comrades face a double-barreled threat. Their jobs have
been taken by replacement workers who work longer hours for lower
pay, many of them veterans of the slumping offshore oil industry in
the Gulf of Mexico.
   But the tug workers also must deal with a changed industry.
After World War II, some 450 tugs plied the harbor. Now there are
just 170.
   Container ships and oil pipelines have greatly reduced the need
for seamen and longshoremen as well as tug and barge crews. Barges
are bigger _ some are self-propelled _ and tugs more powerful, so
fewer are needed. And modern ships are bigger and cheaper to
operate; they can almost berth themselves.
   The liner Normandie, launched in 1935, needed 14 tugs to dock.
The Queen Elizabeth II needs only one.
   Still, tugs run to Boston, down the Intercoastal Waterway to
Virginia, up the Hudson River to the Erie Canal.
   Tug men, many of whom have crewed together for years, often on
the same vessel, are gone from their families for up to a fortnight
at a time.
   Before the strike, the usual tour was a week on, a week off, or
two weeks on, two weeks off. Winter or summer, in calm water or
heaving waves, the men were aboard 24 hours a day and worked 12
hours a day in intervals of six hours on, six hours off.
   The cook worked 12 straight hours, serving three hot meals a day
plus ``night rats'' or rations. It's the cook, the union says, who
created an orderly life at sea; it was he who woke the men up with
fresh brewed coffee and put them to sleep with cookies and milk.
   But the tug companies say the cooks are an extravagance and 750
of them lost their jobs. They installed microwave ovens in the
galleys and urged the crew to take turns cooking, as firefighters
do.
   Cooks are not the only issue in a strike that began Feb. 16. The
companies had demanded that 450 other jobs be eliminated, that
wages be cut up to 60 percent, that overtime pay and weekend
premiums be eliminated, that holidays be cut back and that captains
and mates lose union protection.
   The union offered to cut labor costs 13 percent, according to
Albert Cornette, head of Local 333 of the International
Longshoremen's Association.
   But the owners, fresh from victories over tug unions in Norfolk,
Va., Baltimore and Philadelphia, rejected the offer. There was no
last-minute bargaining and some companies took pre-emptive action,
hiring security guards to eject crews days before the contract
expired.
   The replacement workers already had been hired. Their tours were
stretched to 30 days on, two weeks off.
   The companies cut crews from six to four or five, or even to
three, depending on whether the tug is making an inshore or
offshore trip. Wages for deckhands dropped from $175 a day to $80,
engineers from $245 to $170.
   It cost about $2,100 a day to operate a union-manned tugboat
before the strike. Now, operating costs have been slashed to about
$800 a day.
   ``When they talk about how much money we make a day,'' says cook
Richard Anson, ``they forget we work 12 hours. But what about the
other 12 hours? We can't go home. We're shanghaied.''
   ``The owners don't want to sit and bargain the way we did with
their fathers,'' said Frank Gragnani, a tug captain for 42 years
and union leader. ``They fell into money. They don't know how to
work for money.''
   There have been no talks since the start of the strike. The
National Labor Relations Board issued a complaint against the
owners, alleging failure to bargain in good faith, and set an Oct.
27 hearing.
   Company officials, through lawyers, declined numerous interview
requests.
   Picket lines at remote piers are few and limited in size by a
federal injunction, sought by employers in the early days of the
strike to curb violence.
   Firebombs were tossed, a shot was fired into a tug's wheelhouse,
fist fights erupted, windshields were smashed and rocks thrown.
   At the union's rundown storefront strike headquarters near the
Staten Island wharfs, they track ``turncoats'' on the ``War
Board,'' which lists more than 150 men who returned to work. ``This
scum sold out their union, friends, shipmates and family,'' a sign
says.
   After six months, the strike is taking its toll. Some strikers
have sold their cars or taken out second mortgages. Others have
taken jobs: ``We have people painting, flipping hamburgers, doing
things they would never have done,'' said Gragnani, who charged a
$1,000 cash loan to his credit card.
   The strikers are not entirely shackled to the land. A small
picket boat accosts tugs manned by those who cross picket lines.
   Patrick Egan, a tug cook, enjoyed jeering through a megaphone as
the boat pulled alongside a barge owned by one of the struck
companies.
   ``How much did they cut your pay? You slimy turncoat, you scab,
you galley roach,'' Egan shouted.
   ``It's not that we like to curse, but we can't help it,''
Gragnani explained. ``Screaming lets you get your animosity out. If
you hold it all in, you get sick.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, Aug. 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
