<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade with conflicting weather
factors dominating the market action.
   Support stemmed from the National Weather Service's latest
six-to-10-day forecast, which predicted above nomal-temperatures
and widely varied rainfall in the Corn Belt during the middle five
days of next week, analysts said.
   They said ideas that crop conditions had deteriorated during the
past three days of triple-digit heat added to the bullish sentiment.
   But cooler temperatures and showers were expected to move into
the Midwest today, which accounted for the mixed opening, analysts
said.
   ``I don't see any rain coming yet but it will come and I assume
that's the reason we're under a little pressure here,'' said John
Frazier, grain specialist with Balfour Maclaine Corp. in Chicago.
   The wheat market got an additional boost from talk that Egypt
had purchased 94,000 metric tons of subsidized U.S. wheat, analysts
said.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 1{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.91{ a bushel; corn was 1}
cents lower to } cent higher with September at $2.85{ a bushel;
oats were 3 cents to 3{ cents lower with September at $2.67 a
bushel; soybeans were 3 cents lower to 3 cents higher with August
at $8.80 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower, hogs were mixed and frozen
pork bellies were higher in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Live cattle were .28 cent lower to .17 cent higher with August
at 70.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .47 cent
lower with August at 81.90 cents a pound; hogs were .28 cent lower
to .28 cent higher with August at 46.82 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .63 cent to 1.58 cents higher with August at 35.40
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
