<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 1233EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PennwaltSale     08-18 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pennwalt Sale,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pennwalt Announces Sale To Fisons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennwalt Corp. has agreed to sell its
pharmaceutical operations to the British firm Fisons for $460
million as part of a two-phase company restructuring, the company
announced Thursday.
   Edwin E. Tuttle, chairman and chief executive officer of
Pennwalt, said the sale of the worldwide operation would include a
special distribution of proceeds to shareholders.
   Closing on the deal, which is subject to approval by
shareholders, is expected to take place within the next two to
three months, he said.
   J.S. Kerridge, Fisons' chairman and chief executive officer,
said the acquisition is ``an excellent fit for Fisons, reinforcing
its success in the U.S. pharmaceuticals market and accelerating its
growth plans'' worldwide.
   Fisons just bought an Italian pharmaceutical company,
Italchimici SpA, on Aug. 11.
   The Pennwalt operation, based in Rochester, N.Y., has 1,200
employees and sells primarily in the United States, but also has
sales in Canada and Mexico. It makes prescription drugs as well as
over-the-counter products such as Desenex and Allerest.
   Kerridge said the sales forces, 275 for Fisons and 260 for
Pennwalt, will be combined and trimmed to 400.
   ``The sale of the Pennwalt Pharmaceutical Group to Fisons will
meet one of the major objectives of the company's strategic plan,''
Tuttle said.
   The second phase, he said, will be the sale of Pennwalt's
equipment operations, and ``we are confident that this will also be
achieved in the near future.''
   Tuttle said the board of directors would consider various
alternatives on how to handle the proceeds from the sale.
   ``These alternatives could include a special dividend and-or a
stock repurchase program,'' he said.
   Pennwalt had pharmaceutical sales last year of $129.3 million,
representing 11 percent of the company's total 1987 sales of $1.1
billion. Pre-tax earnings for pharmaceuticals was set at $20
million.
   Fisons, headquartered in Ipswich, Suffolk, England, makes
pharmaceuticals, scientific equipment and gardening products.
Fisons reported sales of 760.3 million pounds, the equivalent of
$1.29 billion, in 1987 and net earnings of 81.3 million pounds.
   Pennwalt's pharmaceutical division's prescription products
include cardiovascular, anti-depressant, anorectic and cough-cold
products. Name brands include Microx, Zaroxolyn, Adapin, Ionamin,
Tussionex and Penntuss.
   Over-the-counter products include Allerest, Desenex, Cruex,
Sinarest and Caldecort.
   The division also includes the Pharmasol Corp., a specialized
aerosol manufacturer.
   Kerridge said Fisons' new U.S. pharmaceutical operation will
remain headquartered in Rochester and will depend on existing
management there. Fisons currently operates out of Bedford, Mass.
The entire Bedford operation will be moved to Rochester next year,
Kerridge said.
   The British company has 500 employees in Bedford.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
