<DOCNO> AP880818-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 1241EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Westinghouse     08-18 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Westinghouse,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Age Discrimination Cases Settled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse Electric Corp. has tentatively
agreed to pay $35 million to settle an age-discrimination suit
brought by employees whose jobs were eliminated over the past eight
years in a series of plant closings, the government said Thursday.
   The settlement with the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission
is believed to be the largest for such a suit. The federal aency
said thousands of former Westinghouse employees could receive
substantial payments.
   Westinghouse said it agreed to deposit the $35 million in escrow
to be used by the EEOC to make severence payments to an
undetermined number of former employers whose jobs were lost in the
closings. The employees had received pensions but no severence pay.
   The tentative agreement would resolve class-action suits filed
in New Jersey and Pennsylvania, said EEOC spokeswoman Margaret
Fernandez. The Pennsylvania suit was expanded to cover Westinghouse
employees nationwide.
   The deal awaits review by U.S. District Court in Philadelphia.
   Other contingencies include the company and the agency agreeing
that a layoff policy being proposed by Westinghouse is lawful, Mrs.
Fernandez said.
   The EEOC must also determine the number of people eligible for
payments before the settlement can be concluded, she said.
</TEXT>
