<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 1319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Venezuela-BondIssue     08-18 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Venezuela-Bond Issue,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Venezuela To Issue $100 Million in Eurobonds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Venezuela will issue $100 million of
Eurobonds Monday, marking the second time a developing nation
debtor ventures into the international bond market since the Third
World debt crisis began.
   The issue, which is registered in Luxembourg, was arranged by
Samuel Montagu & Co. Ltd., a part of Britain's Midland Bank group,
according to Peter Wallin, a Midland Bank representative in Caracas.
   The signing ceremony will take place Sept. 22 in London, Wallin
said in a phone interview Thursday.
   The 5-year notes mature in 1993 and have an interest rate of
1.875 percent over the London Interbank Offered Rate, or LIBOR. The
issue was arranged on a best efforts basis and in theory has been
fully underwritten, Wallin said.
   He said the bonds should be on the market for trading by next
Friday.
   Venezuela is the only debtor nation which has reentered
international bond markets since the debt crisis began in 1982. It
owes $34 billion abroad.
   Last February, Venezuela launched its first Eurobond issue in
eight years with a $100 million issue underwritten by J.P. Morgan
Securities and Banco de Venezuela, a local private bank. The issue
was considered a success.
   The Venezuelan government is currently seeking up to about $2.5
billion in new loans to help cover a balance of payments deficit
caused by low oil prices.
   The bond issues are considered important as a symbolic measure
of Venezuela's creditworthiness.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
