<1ST_LINE>r f BC-JetOrder     08-18 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Jet Order,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delta In Market For New Aircraft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Air Lines is in the market for a new
long-range aircraft and hopes to place an order by the end of the
year, but its size and the type of plane have yet to be decided, a
Delta spokesman said.
   Jim Lundy, a spokesman for Atlanta-based Delta, made the
comments after The Wall Street Journal reported Thursday that the
airline was considering placing an order for as much as $6 billion
in new planes.
   If made, the order would be a record for commercial plane sales.
The biggest on record is a $4.6 billion order placed with aircraft
maker Boeing Co. earlier this year by International Lease Finance
Corp. of Beverly Hills, Calif.
   ``What I can confirm for you is that we are indeed in the market
for a new long-range airplane,'' Lundy said. ``The size of the
order will depend on which airplane we select and what we see as
our long-range need. It really is too early to say.''
   The Journal reported that Delta is considering rival offers from
Boeing and McDonnell Douglas Corp. for a transaction that would
include as many as 30 to 40 jumbo jets and 70 to 100 smaller
twin-jets.
   Lundy confirmed that Delta is interested in exploring propfan
technology on its new jets. Propfan engines combine propeller
technology with traditional turbofan jet engines to produce a
quieter, more fuel-efficient engine.
   Lundy noted that when Delta placed 80 orders and options for
McDonnell Douglas' MD-88 plane two years ago, a required condition
was being able to retrofit the aircraft with propfan engines.
   Delta's interest in propfans hinges on whether ``the performance
of the engine and the fuel savings and noise reductions turn out to
be as good as the predictions,'' Lundy said.
   Without being specific, Lundy said Delta is interested in new
planes not just to replace existing aircraft, but as part of an
expansion program on foreign routes. Delta currently serves more
than 150 cities, including three in the Pacific Rim and seven in
Europe.
   David Jimenez, a Boeing spokesman in Seattle, would not comment
on the Journal report, citing the company's policy never to comment
on sales efforts until a sale is finalized.
   Boeing officials early this year discussed how their 7J7 program
to develop a fuel-efficient propfan plane was delayed for at least
a year because of lack of airline interest.
   Boeing was to decide last August whether to go ahead with 7J7
development for a 1992 introduction. But the decision was delayed,
setting the program back at least a year. Boeing later scaled back
its 7J7 workforce from 900 to 300.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
