<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BlountSteelSale     08-18 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Blount Steel Sale,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blount To Sell Steel Unit to Mercury Stainless</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blount Inc. announced an agreement to
sell its Washington Steel subsidiary to Mercury Stainless Corp. for
$290 million, taking Blount out of the specialty steel business.
   The transaction includes $260 million in cash, a $5 million
subordinated note and a cash price adjustment to Blount, which
depends on the net worth of Washington Steel at the closing of the
sale, the company said Thursday. Blount currently estimates the
cash price adjustment at around $25 million.
   The companies said they expect to complete the sale within three
months.
   Blount, based in Montgomery, is a large manufacturing and
construction company.
   Washington Steel, which Blount acquired in 1979, has 600
employees. It had income of $33.5 million on revenue of $222.6
million in its latest fiscal year.
   Winton M. ``Red'' Blount, chairman of Blount, said proceeds from
the sale might be used for several purposes, including debt
reduction and acquisitions of other companies.
   Blount announced in April that it was interested in selling
Washington Steel. Blount spokesman Charles Barnette said the
company was approached by a dozen prospects, including some foreign
companies, about buying the subsidiary. He said the unit had been
profitable for Blount, but this was ``an appropriate time'' to get
out of the specialty steel business.
   Mercury Stainless Chairman Dietrich Gross said the acquisition
will make his company a stronger competitor with a full range of
stainless steel products.
   Mercury Stainless, based in Wheeling, Ill., operates a stainless
steel cold rolling mill in Massillon, Ohio, and six stainless steel
service centers in the United States and Canada.
</TEXT>
