<HEAD>Batus Extends Deadline on Hostile Offer; Talks Continue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Batus Inc. on Thursday extended the deadline
for its hostile $4.9 billion buyout of Farmers Insurance Group
Inc., as both sides continued negotiating a truce in the lengthy
takeover battle.
   Batus said it was giving shareholders until midnight Wednesday
to accept its $63-per-share tender offer. The offer had been set to
expire at midnight last Wednesday.
   Batus said 16.3 million of the 68.4 million shares outstanding
had been tendered, or offered for sale, as of Wednesday.
   The announced extension came on the second day of scheduled
meetings between executives of Batus and Farmers.
   Farmers agreed to discuss a sweetened, $72-a-share offer from
the Louisville, Ky.,-based tobacco and retailing company. In making
the offer last week, Batus set a deadline of Friday for negotiation
of a definitive agreement.
   The friendly offer values Los Angeles-based Farmers at about $5
billion, taking into account the price for 68.4 million shares
outstanding and employee options to buy an additional 1.5 million
shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
