<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly higher
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade with support stemming from
rumors the Soviet Union was considering new purchases of U.S. corn,
analysts said.
   Corn and wheat finished mostly higher, oats were lower and
soybeans were mixed.
   Traders continued to focus on export news instead of weather
factors, which on Thursday included the arrival of light showers
and lower temperatures in the drought-striken Midwest.
   Although this summer may go down as the 20th Century's hottest
and driest, ``those things have been very well publicized and
factored into the market,'' said Ted Mao, grain specialist with
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   ``The market seems like it wants to be more responsive to the
demand side right now,'' he said.
   Export sales of corn have been flat recently but Mao said it
wouldn't be unlikely for the Soviets to step into the market.
   At the close, wheat was 2\ cents to 4{ cents higher with
September at $3.92{ a bushel; corn was 2\ cents lower to 3\ cents
higher with September at $2.88 a bushel; oats were 4 cents to 9{
cents lower with September at $2.61 a bushel; soybeans were 3 cents
lower to 4 cents higher with August at $8.81 a bushel.
