<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Funds,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $3 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund
Report are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the
week ended Wednesday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 447 money market mutual
funds rose by $3 billion in the latest week, the Investment Company
Institute said Thursday.
   The rise to $268.56 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a revised $846.5 million rise in the funds'
assets the previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual
fund trade group. The increase originally was reported as $840.3
million.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 221 general purpose funds rose $1.66 billion to $85.36
billion, a record high amount for that category.
   Assets of 101 broker-dealer funds increased by $770.6 million to
$113.98 billion, and assets of 125 institutional funds rose $575.3
million to $69.22 billion, the institute reported.
   Jacob Dreyer, the institute's chief economist, attributed the
increases largely to the growing attractiveness of yields on money
market funds vs. yields on money-market accounts and short-term
certificates of deposit.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 7.14 percent from 6.98 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 6.99 percent from 6.90 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
34 days, unchanged from the previous week, Donoghue's said.
   The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and savings banks in
the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield
available on money market accounts rose to 5.87 percent as of
Wednesday from 5.83 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, was 5.13 percent, unchanged.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 7.51
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 7.42 the
previous week. Yields were 7.82 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 7.72
percent; 8.12 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 8.04 percent; and
8.45 percent on 5-year CDs, up from 8.40 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880818-0315 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 2122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Armtek-MarkIV     08-18 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Armtek-Mark IV,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mark IV Raises Its Offer For Armtek</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mark IV Industries Inc. on Thursday
sweetened its tender offer for Armtek Corp. to $44 a share, or
about $550 million, a day after Armtek's board rejected its initial
offer as inadequate.
   Armtek's board on Wednesday urged stockholders not to tender
their shares to Mark IV's original $40-a-share tender offer. The
board also directed management to consider measures to increase the
company's stock price.
   Bob Jones, an Armtek spokesman, said the company's board had no
immediate comment on the new offer, which covers all outstanding
shares and associated preferred stock purchase rights.
   In a letter to the Armtek board, Mark IV Chairman Sal H. Alfiero
reiterated his request for a meeting ``to discuss any and all
aspects of our increased offer, including the price to be paid to
Armtek stockholders.''
   Armtek is facing four class action suits in Delaware, where it
is incorporated, from shareholders who charge the company's
directors are trying to thwart the takeover attempt and haven't
satisfactorily explored the offer.
   One suit claims Armtek's directors have ``embarked upon a course
of action designed to entrench themselves in the management and
control of Armtek and to protect and enhance their personal
financial benefits'' at the expense of shareholders.
   Armtek, formerly known as Armstrong Rubber Co., is a supplier of
engineered drive and heat exchange systems, modules and components
and specialty polymers. It had $1.2 billion in sales last year.
   Two month ago, Armtek sold its largest unit, Armstrong Tire Co.,
to the Italian tire maker Pirelli Group for $197 million, capping a
corporate restructuring.
   Mark IV, based in West Amherst, N.Y., produces professional
audio, technical and aerospace products. The company had 1987 sales
of $292 million.
   Mark IV's new offer will expire at midnight Sept. 2, unless
extended.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
