<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0267 08-18 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0267,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Stocks Up Slightly In Quiet Tokyo Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with later trading, comments. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar recovered slightly from a lower
opening against the Japanese yen on Friday, while share prices
edged higher in quiet trading on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar opened at 133.23 yen, down 0.70 yen from the previous
day's close, and traded sluggishly throughout the morning. The
currency was changing hands at 133.43 yen by late morning.
   ``There is a strong wait-and-see mood in the market,'' said one
foreign exchange dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   In the stock market, the widely-watched Nikkei Stock Average of
225 selected issues rose 44.96 to 28,174.32 points by the morning
close.
   A stock dealer in Tokyo, who asked not to be identified, said
the market was slow because it had no clear no direction at the
moment.
   ``It's just a few stocks that are getting picked up and
pushed,'' he said.
</TEXT>
