<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 1030EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-TowerPurchase     08-18 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Tower Purchase,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bear Stearns-Led Group Buying Dallas Bank Tower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York-based Bear Stearns Cos. has announced it
will purchase another prominent chunk of the Dallas skyline, the
60-story First Interstate Bank Tower and adjacent property for $167
million.
   Bear Stearns said Tuesday it had organized an investment group
to buy the angular, green-glass skyscraper and adjacent property
from Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.
   The deal will be the second purchase by Bear Stearns in downtown
Dallas. The investment banking firm already agreed to buy 40 of the
50 floors of Thanksgiving Tower from companies controlled by the
billionaire Hunt family.
   Bear Stearns also has been hired as an adviser to the owners of
three commercial properties in Dallas and may buy into those
projects as well, company officials said.
   The buyer group for First Interstate Bank Tower includes New
York investor Norman Alexander; Dallas-based Crosland Investment
Properties Inc.; New York-based M&M Realty Partners L.P.; and
American Universal Insurance Co., of Providence, R.I.
   ``Each of them has made a signifcant cash investment in the
deal,'' said Stephen P. Jarchow, managing director of Bear Stearns'
Dallas office.
   Bear Stearns plans to invest about $1 billion in Texas real
estate in the next two to three years, company officials said.
   Manufacturers Hanover has owned First Interstate Bank Tower
since April 1987, when it foreclosed on the building after its
developers, Dallas-based Criswell Cos., defaulted on $214 million
in construction loans.
   Manufacturers Hanover has agreed to finance $125.5 million of
the deal, which is expected to close in September, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
