<DOCNO> AP880818-0319 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-88 1033EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-NorthropDebt     08-18 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Northrop Debt,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aerospace Firm Cancels Public Debt Offering; To Do Private
Offering</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northrop Corp. has announced plans to
restructure its debt by converting up to $450 million of short-term
bank loans to intermediate-term notes sold privately to investors.
   The Wall Street Journal quoted unidentified sources Wednesday as
saying the private placement represented a change from earlier
plans to sell notes to the public, and said the switch was brought
about by concern over investigations into the company's dealings in
South Korea.
   But Northrop spokesman Tony Cantafio denied Wednesday that plans
for the debt offering had been changed, saying the company had been
considering various alternatives for converting the debt since
first announcing its intention to do so in April.
   ``We explored a number of financing alternatives available to us
... and the private placement plan was adopted in July,'' Cantafio
said.
   Plans for a private sale of notes were revealed in the company's
second-quarter report.
   The Journal, quoting an unidentified investment banker who had
dealt with Northrop on the matter, said the company originally
planned to sell notes to the public.
   The investment banker said the public offering had been ruled
out for fear approval of the offering could be delayed if the
Securities and Exchange Commission decided to study the company's
activities in South Korea.
   A private placement, involving sale of notes to institutions and
wealthy individuals, would be exempt from registration with the SEC.
   A congressional committee and a federal grand jury in Los
Angeles are looking into payments the company made to Korean
companies and individuals in 1984 and 1986 in connection with
attempts to sell its ill-fated F-20 fighter jet to the South Korean
government. Northrop denies any impropriety.
   The sale of notes is intended to reduce the risk that rising
interest rates could push up the cost of servicing the company's
$905 million worth of short-term, floating-interest-rate bank
loans. The notes would have fixed interest rates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
